## Section 7: Realistic Pathway Summary (Roadmap)

Here is a realistic, layered pathway many Californians follow. You might not hit every step, and you can work on several at once.  

1. **Call 211 → Enter Coordinated Entry**  
   - Dial 211 or visit https://211ca.org to get connected to local shelters, outreach, and your CoC’s Coordinated Entry System. [hudexchange](https://www.hudexchange.info/homelessness-assistance/coordinated-entry/)

2. **Apply for County Housing Assistance**  
   - Visit or contact your county DPSS/social services (for example, LA County DPSS: https://dpss.lacounty.gov) to apply for CalWORKs, General Relief, HSP, HA, and HDAP if you may qualify. [cdss.ca](https://www.cdss.ca.gov/inforesources/cdss-programs/housing-programs/calworks-homeless-assistance)

3. **Stabilize with Temporary Aid**  
   - Use motel vouchers, emergency shelter, and short‑term assistance (CalWORKs HA, HSP, HDAP) to get off the street and gather documents. [cdss.ca](https://www.cdss.ca.gov/inforesources/cdss-programs/housing-programs/housing-and-disability-advocacy-program)

4. **Get Referred to Rapid Rehousing or Bridge Housing**  
   - Through CES and county programs, seek referrals to rapid rehousing or bridge‑housing programs when your vulnerability and program fit line up with an opening. [nlihc](https://nlihc.org/node/94756)

5. **Apply to All Open Section 8 Waitlists Statewide**  
   - Regularly check HUD’s PHA contact list and major PHA websites (HACLA, SHRA, SDHC, etc.) for open waitlists and apply whenever you see an opening. [hacla](https://www.hacla.org/en/about-section-8/homeless-initiatives)

6. **Apply to Tax Credit and Project‑Based Units**  
   - Use HUD Resource Locator (https://resources.hud.gov), HUD’s California page, and tools like the California Affordable Housing Map (https://affordablehomes.chpc.net) to find and apply to LIHTC and project‑based properties. [affordablehomes.chpc](https://affordablehomes.chpc.net)

7. **Maintain Documentation and Follow‑Ups**  
   - Keep copies of your documents, track applications and case workers’ contact information, and check in regularly with your CES access point, county worker, and PHAs. [hudexchange](https://www.hudexchange.info/homelessness-assistance/coordinated-entry/)

[Citations] [sdhc](https://sdhc.org/housing-opportunities/affordable-rentals/)

***

## Section 8: Document Checklist

Having your paperwork ready can speed up housing placements and reduce delays. Many programs in California will ask for:  

- **Photo ID** (state ID, driver’s license, or other government ID).  
- **Social Security cards** or proof of having applied.  
- **Income proof** (pay stubs, award letters for SSI/SSDI, CalWORKs, General Relief, unemployment, etc.).  
- **Homeless verification letter** from a shelter, outreach worker, or agency, or documentation of staying in places not meant for habitation. [shastacounty](https://www.shastacounty.gov/media/8331)
- **Disability verification** (for HDAP, SSI/SSDI applications, or supportive housing) – medical records or forms completed by a licensed provider. [hudexchange](https://www.hudexchange.info/homelessness-assistance/coordinated-entry/)
- **Eviction notices** (3‑day, 30‑day, unlawful detainer paperwork) to prove risk of homelessness, which can be used for programs like CalWORKs HA and prevention funding. [cdss.ca](https://www.cdss.ca.gov/inforesources/cdss-programs/housing-programs/calworks-homeless-assistance)
- **Birth certificates** for children in the household (often needed for CalWORKs, BFH, and some housing programs). [cdss.ca](https://www.cdss.ca.gov/calworks)

If you are missing documents, tell your worker; many programs can help you obtain replacements or give temporary approvals while you gather records.  

[Citations] [shastacounty](https://www.shastacounty.gov/media/8331)

***

## Section 9: Timeline Reality Check

### Shelter and Interim Housing

Shelter beds, bridge housing, and motel programs depend on local capacity and funding. In some areas there are frequent openings; in others, shelters are full and people wait days or weeks for a spot. Some state and county programs (like motel vouchers) have strict limits (for example, HA’s 16‑day limit) so you must plan for what comes next from day one. [hcd.ca](https://www.hcd.ca.gov/sites/default/files/docs/grants-and-funding/calich/performance_measure_guide.pdf)

[Citations] [hcd.ca](https://www.hcd.ca.gov/sites/default/files/docs/grants-and-funding/calich/performance_measure_guide.pdf)

### Rapid Rehousing and Permanent Supportive Housing

Rapid rehousing slots and permanent supportive housing units are limited and are often reserved for those with the highest vulnerability scores or specific eligibility (chronic homelessness, disability, veterans). It can take months or longer after your CES assessment before you receive a referral, and many people are never matched because demand is higher than supply. [providers.anthem](https://providers.anthem.com/docs/gpp/california-provider/CA_CAID_HomelessCoordinatedEntrySystems.pdf?v=202411131531)

[Citations] [providers.anthem](https://providers.anthem.com/docs/gpp/california-provider/CA_CAID_HomelessCoordinatedEntrySystems.pdf?v=202411131531)

### Section 8 and Affordable Housing

Section 8 waitlists in California can be closed for long periods, and when they open, they may receive tens of thousands of applications for a small number of slots; actual wait times can range from 1 year to over 10 years in some areas. Affordable housing properties also maintain their own waitlists, which can range from a few months to many years depending on location and unit size. [sdhc](https://sdhc.org/housing-opportunities/affordable-rentals/)

Because of these realities, the best strategy is to treat housing as a long‑term process, keep your name on as many appropriate lists as possible, and use interim resources (shelters, rapid rehousing, county subsidies) to stay housed while you wait.  

[Citations] [sdhc](https://sdhc.org/housing-opportunities/affordable-rentals/)

***

## Section 10: Common Mistakes to Avoid

Avoiding these mistakes can protect your spot on waitlists and improve your chances of being housed.  

1. **Waiting for one program only**  
   - Relying on Section 8 alone or just one shelter program can leave you stuck for years; you should be in CES, county programs, and multiple waitlists at the same time. [hudexchange](https://www.hudexchange.info/homelessness-assistance/coordinated-entry/)

2. **Not applying in multiple counties or cities when possible**  
   - Many PHAs and affordable properties in different counties have their own waitlists; you may be able to apply to several even if you don’t live there yet, depending on local preference rules. [affordablehomes.chpc](https://affordablehomes.chpc.net)

3. **Not updating your contact information**  
   - PHAs and property managers often send notices by mail or email; if they can’t reach you, they may remove you from the waitlist. Always update your address, phone, and email with CES, DPSS, and every housing provider where you applied. [hud](http://www.hud.gov/helping-americans/housing-choice-vouchers-tenants)

4. **Missing document deadlines or appointments**  
   - Many programs have strict timelines; missing an appointment or failing to turn in documents can close your case or move you down the list. [cdss.ca](https://www.cdss.ca.gov/inforesources/cdss-programs/housing-programs/housing-and-disability-advocacy-program)

5. **Not opening mail or ignoring unfamiliar numbers**  
   - Housing authorities and agencies may call from blocked or unfamiliar numbers and send important letters that look generic. Open all mail, keep a folder for housing letters, and check voicemail regularly.  

6. **Not asking questions when you don’t understand**  
   - Programs can be confusing; ask your case worker, shelter staff, or legal aid to explain your options, appeal rights, and what to expect next. [cdss.ca](https://www.cdss.ca.gov/inforesources/cdss-programs/housing-programs/housing-and-disability-advocacy-program)

[Citations] [affordablehomes.chpc](https://affordablehomes.chpc.net)

***

## Section 11: Where to Get Legal Help

Legal help can protect you from illegal evictions, discrimination, and loss of benefits that could lead to homelessness.  

### LawHelpCA

LawHelpCA is the statewide legal information and referral site funded by the State Bar of California and legal aid organizations.  

- Website: https://www.lawhelpca.org [lawhelpca](https://www.lawhelpca.org/issues/housing/landlord-and-tenant-issues)

On LawHelpCA you can:  

- Search for free or low‑cost legal aid in your county.  
- Find information on evictions, habitability, discrimination, and public benefits.  

[Citations]  

### California Civil Rights Department (CRD)

CRD enforces California’s housing discrimination laws, including protections against source‑of‑income discrimination (for example, landlords refusing vouchers) and discrimination based on race, disability, family status, and more. [calcivilrights.ca](https://calcivilrights.ca.gov/housing/)

- Housing discrimination info and complaint process: https://calcivilrights.ca.gov/housing [calcivilrights.ca](https://calcivilrights.ca.gov/housing/)

If a landlord refuses to rent to you because of your voucher, disability, race, or other protected trait, you can file a complaint with CRD.  

[Citations]  

### Stay Housed LA (Los Angeles County)

If you are in Los Angeles County and at risk of eviction or displacement, Stay Housed LA provides free legal services and tenant education to eligible tenants. [lafla](https://lafla.org/who-we-are/stay-housed-la/)

- Website: https://www.stayhousedla.org [stayhousedla](https://www.stayhousedla.org)

This program is run by legal aid and community organizations and focuses on keeping tenants housed and preventing homelessness through advice, representation, and workshops. [lafla](https://lafla.org/who-we-are/stay-housed-la/)

[Citations] [lafla](https://lafla.org/who-we-are/stay-housed-la/)

| CalWORKs HSP / HA               | County DPSS, CDSS          | Shelter, move‑in help, short‑term rent     | Apply for CalWORKs and request HSP/HA [cdss.ca](https://www.cdss.ca.gov/inforesources/cdss-programs/housing-programs) |
| HDAP                             | County (CDSS‑funded)       | Disability advocacy + housing aid          | Ask DPSS/HDAP contact if disabled & homeless [cdss.ca](https://www.cdss.ca.gov/inforesources/cdss-programs/housing-programs/housing-and-disability-advocacy-program) |
| Rapid rehousing / bridge housing | CoC, counties, nonprofits  | Short‑term housing on path to permanency   | Usually via CES referral, sometimes DPSS [hudexchange](https://www.hudexchange.info/homelessness-assistance/coordinated-entry/) |
| Section 8 HCV                    | Public Housing Authorities | Long‑term rent subsidy in private market   | Apply to PHA waitlists when open [hud](http://www.hud.gov/states/california) |
| LIHTC/tax credit & project‑based | Property owners, PHAs      | Below‑market rent units                    | Apply directly to each property [hud](http://www.hud.gov/states/california) |

[Citations] [providers.anthem](https://providers.anthem.com/docs/gpp/california-provider/CA_CAID_HomelessCoordinatedEntrySystems.pdf?v=202411131531)

***

## Conclusion: Moving from Shelter to Stable Housing in California

There is no one form that takes you straight from a shelter bed into Section 8, and most Californians will move through a mix of shelters, county programs, rapid rehousing, and multiple waitlists before they reach permanent housing. Coordinated Entry is often required for referrals to rapid rehousing, bridge housing, and permanent supportive housing, while county programs like CalWORKs HSP, HA, and HDAP can provide the temporary boost you need to get into a unit and stay there long enough to stabilize. [hudexchange](https://www.hudexchange.info/homelessness-assistance/coordinated-entry/)

The system is slow and far from perfect, but many people do make it to stable housing by using a layered strategy: staying connected to CES, applying for all available benefits, getting on every appropriate waitlist, and protecting their rights with legal help when needed. With persistence, organization, and support, you can move step by step from crisis shelter toward a permanent home. [stayhousedla](https://www.stayhousedla.org)

rows.title: LGBTQ+ Resources in California - Complete Survival Guide
rows.content:
A) FAST START (READ THIS FIRST)  

If you’re in crisis in California, start with these five moves. You can do them from a phone, shelter lobby, library, or hospital waiting room.  

1. Call 211 to find a safe place to sleep and basic help  
   - Dial 2-1-1 from any phone or visit https://211ca.org to be routed to your local 211. [211ca](https://211ca.org)
   - In Los Angeles County, you can also call 2-1-1 or 800-339-6993 or use https://211la.org. [211la](https://211la.org/homeless-housing-support-programs)
   - Tell them: “I am LGBTQ+, I’m currently homeless/at risk, and I need emergency shelter or motel placement and help getting into housing programs.” [211la](https://211la.org/homeless-housing-support-programs)

2. Contact an LGBTQ+ center for intake, case management, and safer services  
   - Los Angeles: Los Angeles LGBT Center, 323-993-7400, housing info at https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/housing. [lalgbtcenter](https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/housing/)
   - San Francisco Bay Area: SF LGBT Center, 415-865-5555, https://sfcenter.org. [sfcenter](https://sfcenter.org)
   - San Diego: San Diego LGBT Community Center (The Center), 619-692-2077, https://thecentersd.org. [thecentersd](https://thecentersd.org/timeline/the-sunburst-youth-housing-project/)
   - Ask for: “intake or case management for housing, benefits, and employment; I’m LGBTQ+ and need affirming services.” [sfcenter](https://www.sfcenter.org/program/housing-financial/)

3. If you are escaping family violence, partner abuse, or trafficking  
   - Call 211 and say “I need domestic violence shelter and I am LGBTQ+.” Many DV programs and 211 lists can connect you to confidential shelters and safety planning. [211](http://www.211.org)
   - If you’re in immediate danger or seriously hurt, call 911. If calling 911 doesn’t feel safe, consider 988 for crisis counseling and safety planning. [sandiegocounty](https://www.sandiegocounty.gov/content/sdc/hhsa/programs/bhs/ACL.html)

4. For urgent HIV, PEP/PrEP, or lost medications  
   - PEP (post-exposure) must start within 72 hours after a possible HIV exposure; PrEP helps prevent HIV before exposure and is covered under Medi-Cal when medically necessary. [ryanwhite.hrsa](https://ryanwhite.hrsa.gov/about/parts-and-initiatives/part-b-adap)
   - Call:  
     - LA LGBT Center Sexual Health Services: 323-993-7500, https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/sexual-health-services. [lalgbtcenter](https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/sexual-health-services/)
     - APLA Health HIV support: 213-201-1426, https://aplahealth.org/service-type/hiv-support-services. [aplahealth](https://aplahealth.org/service-type/hiv-support-services/)
     - AIDS Healthcare Foundation (AHF) California clinics: start at https://aidshealth.org (see “Locations”). [npin.cdc](https://npin.cdc.gov/organization/aids-healthcare-foundation-3)
   - Say: “I need urgent HIV testing/PEP/PrEP and I am uninsured/low income; what can you do same-day?” [medi-calrx.dhcs.ca](https://medi-calrx.dhcs.ca.gov/cms/medicalrx/static-assets/documents/provider/bulletins/2022.07_A_Inappropriate_Treatment_of_HIV_PrEP_and_PEP.pdf)

5. Get legal help if you’re being evicted, discriminated against, or threatened over immigration  
   - Housing/eviction (statewide): LawHelpCA legal aid directory, https://www.lawhelpca.org. [lawhelpca](https://www.lawhelpca.org/find-legal-help/directory/area)
   - LA County eviction defense: Stay Housed LA (tenant assistance program for people facing eviction), https://www.stayhousedla.org. [dcba.lacounty](https://dcba.lacounty.gov/newsroom/stay-housed-l-a-county-tenant-assistance-program-launched-free-legal-services-to-tenants-facing-eviction/)
   - LGBTQ+ impact litigation and advice:  
     - Lambda Legal Western Regional Office (Los Angeles): 213-382-7600, https://lambdalegal.org/contact. [lambdalegal](https://lambdalegal.org/contact/)
     - National Center for Lesbian Rights (NCLR) Legal Help Line: 800-528-6257 or 415-392-6257, https://www.nclrights.org (Legal Help Line info at resources.legallink.org link). [resources.legallink](https://resources.legallink.org/referral/national-center-for-lesbian-rights-advice-line/)
   - If housing discrimination is based on LGBTQ+ status, contact the California Civil Rights Department: https://calcivilrights.ca.gov/housing. [calcivilrights.ca](https://calcivilrights.ca.gov/housing/)

---  

B) HOUSING & SHELTER (LGBTQ+ FRIENDLY)  

How California’s housing access system works  
- 211 and county hotlines are usually the front door for shelter, motel vouchers, and connection to your local Coordinated Entry System (CES). [211ca](https://211ca.org)
- Coordinated Entry is how counties match people experiencing homelessness to limited slots in shelter, bridge housing, rapid rehousing, or permanent supportive housing; you usually need an intake/assessment to get on the list. [homelessness.acgov](https://homelessness.acgov.org/coordinated-entry.page)
- HUD-funded programs (including vouchers and supportive housing) run through local public housing agencies (PHAs) and homelessness systems; you can find PHAs and HUD-funded programs through HUD’s online resource and PHA locators. [ryanwhite.hrsa](https://ryanwhite.hrsa.gov/about/parts-and-initiatives/part-b-adap)

Key entry points  

1. 211 California (statewide)  
- Call 2-1-1 or go to https://211ca.org to search for “emergency shelter,” “transitional housing,” or “LGBTQ+ shelter.” [211ca](https://211ca.org/search/?category=BH-8600&search=Transitional+Housing%2FShelter)
- 211 can connect you to local programs, DV shelters, and sometimes motel vouchers. [211la](https://211la.org/homeless-housing-support-programs)

2. Los Angeles County  
- 211 LA: Dial 2-1-1 or 800-339-6993, https://211la.org. [211la](https://211la.org)
- 211 LA screens for LA County’s Coordinated Entry System for Families and can issue motel vouchers and connect you to Family Solutions Centers where eligible. [211la](https://211la.org/homeless-housing-support-programs)
- LA’s CES includes LGBTQ+ providers such as the LA LGBT Center as core partners. [211la](https://211la.org/homeless-housing-support-programs)

3. Alameda County (example for Bay Area CES)  
- Alameda County Coordinated Entry information: https://homelessness.acgov.org/coordinated-entry.page. [homelessness.acgov](https://homelessness.acgov.org/coordinated-entry.page)
- Coordinated Entry provides access points to assessments, prioritization, and connection to Home Stretch permanent housing opportunities. [homelessness.acgov](https://homelessness.acgov.org/coordinated-entry.page)

LGBTQ+ specific housing options  

Los Angeles County  
- Los Angeles LGBT Center – Youth housing and supportive housing  
  - Website: https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/housing. [lalgbtcenter](https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/housing/)
  - Phone: 323-993-7400 (main line; ask for youth or housing services). [lalgbtcenter](https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/housing/)
  - Programs include emergency shelter, transitional living, permanent supportive housing, host homes, and rental assistance for LGBTQ+ youth ages 18–24 experiencing homelessness. [lalgbtcenter](https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/housing/)
- APLA Health – Housing navigation and support for people living with HIV  
  - HIV support services: https://aplahealth.org/service-type/hiv-support-services. [aplahealth](https://aplahealth.org/service-type/hiv-support-services/)
  - Phone: 213-201-1426. [aplahealth](https://aplahealth.org/service-type/hiv-support-services/)

San Francisco / Bay Area  
- SF LGBT Center – Housing and financial services  
  - Website: https://www.sfcenter.org (housing & financial services section at https://www.sfcenter.org/program/housing-financial). [sfcenter](https://www.sfcenter.org/program/housing-financial/)
  - Phone: 415-865-5555. [sfcenter](https://sfcenter.org)
  - Services: rental counseling, budgeting, credit support, and connection to San Francisco’s housing programs; they can help you build an action plan for more stable housing. [sfcenter](https://www.sfcenter.org/community/how-the-center-helps-lgbtq-families-achieve-their-dreams/)
- Covenant House California – Youth housing (LGBTQ+ inclusive)  
  - Locations:  
    - Los Angeles: 1325 N Western Ave, Hollywood, CA 90027, 323-461-3131.  
    - Oakland: 200 Harrison St, Oakland, CA 94607, 510-379-1010. [covenanthousecalifornia](https://covenanthousecalifornia.org/locations/)

San Diego County  
- The San Diego LGBT Community Center (“The Center”)  
  - Website: https://thecentersd.org. [thecentersd](https://thecentersd.org/timeline/the-sunburst-youth-housing-project/)
  - Phone: 619-692-2077. [thecentersd](https://thecentersd.org/timeline/the-sunburst-youth-housing-project/)
  - The Sunburst Youth Housing Project provides supportive housing for 23 unhoused LGBTQ+ and HIV+ youth ages 18–24. [thecentersd](https://thecentersd.org/timeline/the-sunburst-youth-housing-project/)

“What to say when you call” (sample script)  
- “Hi, my name is [first name]. I am LGBTQ+ and currently homeless / about to lose my housing. I am in [your city] in California. I need:  
  - a safe place to sleep tonight,  
  - help getting into the coordinated entry or housing queue, and  
  - LGBTQ+ friendly or trans-affirming options if possible.”  
- If you’re youth (18–24): “I’m a LGBTQ+ youth, [age], and I’m homeless or in danger if I stay where I am.” Mention DV or trafficking if it’s part of your situation so they can prioritize safety. [thecentersd](https://thecentersd.org/timeline/the-sunburst-youth-housing-project/)

Documents checklist (bring if you can, but ask for help if you don’t have them)  
- Photo ID (any country).  
- Social Security card or number (if you have one).  
- Proof of income or benefits: pay stubs, EBT card, award letters.  
- Medical card (Medi-Cal or other insurance).  
- HIV labs or prescription bottles if you are in care.  
- Any eviction or court papers.  
Many programs must still serve you even if you lack documents; ask the worker to help you replace lost ID and records. [sonomacounty](https://sonomacounty.gov/health-and-human-services/human-services/apply-online-at-benefitscal)

Safety notes for trans and nonbinary people in shelters  
- California civil rights and health laws prohibit discrimination based on gender identity or gender expression in many settings, including health plans and services. [dmhc.ca](https://www.dmhc.ca.gov/HealthCareinCalifornia/GettheBestCare/TGICare.aspx)
- You can say: “I am a transgender [woman/man/nonbinary person] and I want to be housed consistent with my gender identity, not my sex assigned at birth.” [dmhc.ca](https://www.dmhc.ca.gov/HealthCareinCalifornia/GettheBestCare/TGICare.aspx)
- If a shelter misgenders you, refuses to house you according to your gender identity, or harasses you:  
  - Write down names, dates, and what happened.  
  - Report to the program’s supervisor and your county homelessness office.  
  - For legal support, contact Lambda Legal (213-382-7600) or NCLR (800-528-6257). [lambdalegal](https://lambdalegal.org/contact/)
  - You can also explore filing a housing discrimination complaint with the California Civil Rights Department: https://calcivilrights.ca.gov/housing. [calcivilrights.ca](https://calcivilrights.ca.gov/housing/)

**Section B citations:** [covenanthousecalifornia](https://covenanthousecalifornia.org/locations/)

---  

C) HIV & SEXUAL HEALTH (CARE, MEDS, FINANCIAL COVERAGE)  

Ryan White & ADAP basics  
- The federal Ryan White HIV/AIDS Program provides medical care and support services for people with HIV who are low-income or uninsured; Part B’s AIDS Drug Assistance Program (ADAP) provides HIV medications to low-income people with HIV who have limited or no insurance. [ryanwhite.hrsa](https://ryanwhite.hrsa.gov/about/parts-and-initiatives/part-b-adap)
- Each state (including California) runs its own ADAP to cover antiretroviral medications and some related drugs; eligibility is set statewide and must be applied consistently. [ryanwhite.hrsa](https://ryanwhite.hrsa.gov/about/parts-and-initiatives/part-b-adap)

Medi-Cal, PrEP, and PEP in California  
- Medi-Cal is California’s Medicaid program; it covers HIV medications and, when medically necessary, HIV PrEP and PEP as a benefit. [medi-calrx.dhcs.ca](https://medi-calrx.dhcs.ca.gov/cms/medicalrx/static-assets/documents/provider/bulletins/2022.07_A_Inappropriate_Treatment_of_HIV_PrEP_and_PEP.pdf)
- The California Department of Health Care Services (DHCS) has clarified that HIV medications for both PrEP and PEP are Medi-Cal benefits when medically necessary, and providers should not delay or deny appropriate treatment. [medi-calrx.dhcs.ca](https://medi-calrx.dhcs.ca.gov/cms/medicalrx/static-assets/documents/provider/bulletins/2022.07_A_Inappropriate_Treatment_of_HIV_PrEP_and_PEP.pdf)

Major HIV/sexual health providers  

Los Angeles / Southern California  
- LA LGBT Center Sexual Health Services  
  - Website: https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/sexual-health-services. [lalgbtcenter](https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/sexual-health-services/)
  - Phone: 323-993-7500 (new patients). [lalgbtcenter](https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/sexual-health-services/)
  - Services: HIV testing, STI testing and treatment, PrEP and PEP prescriptions, including free or low-cost PrEP care for uninsured and insured patients. [lalgbtcenter](https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/sexual-health-services/)
- APLA Health – HIV Support Services  
  - Website: https://aplahealth.org/service-type/hiv-support-services. [aplahealth](https://aplahealth.org/service-type/hiv-support-services/)
  - Phone: 213-201-1426. [aplahealth](https://aplahealth.org/service-type/hiv-support-services/)
  - Services: intensive HIV home health, medication support, mental health, and substance use help. [aplahealth](https://aplahealth.org/service-type/hiv-support-services/)
- AIDS Healthcare Foundation (AHF) – Multiple California clinics  
  - Provider listing: AHF Healthcare Center Westside details at CDC NPIN: free HIV testing, PrEP navigation, HIV medical treatment, and STI services. [npin.cdc](https://npin.cdc.gov/organization/aids-healthcare-foundation-3)

Step-by-step: Get HIV care in 72 hours  

If you think you were exposed to HIV in the last 72 hours:  
1. Act now (do not wait for symptoms).  
2. Call or walk into:  
   - LA LGBT Center Sexual Health Services (323-993-7500). [lalgbtcenter](https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/sexual-health-services/)
   - APLA Health or AHF clinics listed for your area. [npin.cdc](https://npin.cdc.gov/organization/aids-healthcare-foundation-3)
   - Your county public health STI/HIV clinic (find via 211 or county public health site). [sandiegocounty](https://www.sandiegocounty.gov/content/sdc/hhsa/programs/bhs/ACL.html)
3. Say clearly: “I had a possible HIV exposure within the last 72 hours and I need PEP. I have [Medi-Cal/no insurance].” [medi-calrx.dhcs.ca](https://medi-calrx.dhcs.ca.gov/cms/medicalrx/static-assets/documents/provider/bulletins/2022.07_A_Inappropriate_Treatment_of_HIV_PrEP_and_PEP.pdf)
4. Ask for same-day or walk-in care; if they try to schedule you out, ask: “Is there an urgent care or emergency department you can send me to for PEP today?” [medi-calrx.dhcs.ca](https://medi-calrx.dhcs.ca.gov/cms/medicalrx/static-assets/documents/provider/bulletins/2022.07_A_Inappropriate_Treatment_of_HIV_PrEP_and_PEP.pdf)
5. Once you start PEP, schedule follow-up HIV testing and talk about PrEP if you expect ongoing exposure risk. [ryanwhite.hrsa](https://ryanwhite.hrsa.gov/about/parts-and-initiatives/part-b-adap)

If you are living with HIV and lost meds or got disconnected from care:  
1. Gather what you have: pill bottles, clinic cards, old lab results.  
2. Call your last clinic or pharmacy and ask for an emergency refill or bridge supply.  
3. If that’s not possible, contact:  
   - APLA Health (213-201-1426). [aplahealth](https://aplahealth.org/service-type/hiv-support-services/)
   - AHF clinic in your area (see AHF location listings). [npin.cdc](https://npin.cdc.gov/organization/aids-healthcare-foundation-3)
   - Local county public health HIV clinic (via 211). [211ca](https://211ca.org)
4. Say: “I am a person living with HIV. I lost my medications / ran out. I need urgent meds and to re-establish care. I am in [city] and have [Medi-Cal/no insurance].” [ryanwhite.hrsa](https://ryanwhite.hrsa.gov/about/parts-and-initiatives/part-b-adap)
5. Ask the clinic or case manager to help you apply or re-enroll in ADAP and Ryan White services to cover meds and labs. [ryanwhite.hrsa](https://ryanwhite.hrsa.gov/about/parts-and-initiatives/part-b-adap)

**Section C citations:** [211ca](https://211ca.org)

---  

D) TRANS & NONBINARY RESOURCES  

Your rights to gender-affirming care  
- California law prohibits health plans from denying care or discriminating against you because of your gender identity or gender expression. [dmhc.ca](https://www.dmhc.ca.gov/HealthCareinCalifornia/GettheBestCare/TGICare.aspx)
- The state’s TGI Inclusive Care Act protects access to gender-affirming health care that aligns with standards of care and respects gender diversity. [dmhc.ca](https://www.dmhc.ca.gov/HealthCareinCalifornia/GettheBestCare/TGICare.aspx)
- DHCS guidance for Medi-Cal confirms that transgender (gender-affirming) services are covered when medically necessary, including surgery that meets reconstructive criteria. [dmhc.ca](https://www.dmhc.ca.gov/HealthCareinCalifornia/GettheBestCare/TGICare.aspx)

Name and gender marker changes  
- California courts provide self-help resources and forms to change your name and gender marker; court self-help centers and LawHelpCA’s directory list legal aid organizations that can assist. [lawhelpca](https://www.lawhelpca.org/find-legal-help/directory/area)
- Legal organizations like NCLR (800-528-6257) and Lambda Legal (213-382-7600) often provide guidance on name and gender marker changes, especially when discrimination or family court issues are involved. [resources.legallink](https://resources.legallink.org/referral/national-center-for-lesbian-rights-advice-line/)

Trans-affirming support and crisis lines  
- Trans Lifeline  
  - Peer support hotline run by and for trans people.  
  - US number: 877-565-8860. [en.wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trans_Lifeline)
- The Trevor Project  
  - Crisis support for LGBTQ+ youth.  
  - 24/7 phone: 1-866-488-7386. [alhambraca](https://www.alhambraca.gov/835/LA-County-Department-of-Mental-Health)
  - California has partnered with The Trevor Project to improve LGBTQ+ competency for 988 crisis counselors. [gov.ca](https://www.gov.ca.gov/2025/07/16/following-trump-cut-to-lgbtq-youth-suicide-hotline-california-steps-up-to-fill-the-gap/)

Accessing hormones and gender-affirming care  
- If you have Medi-Cal, you can:  
  - Call your plan’s member services and ask for an LGBTQ+/trans-competent provider who can manage hormones and surgical referrals; remind them transgender services are covered when medically necessary under DHCS guidance. [dmhc.ca](https://www.dmhc.ca.gov/HealthCareinCalifornia/GettheBestCare/TGICare.aspx)
- If you are uninsured or underinsured in large metro areas:  
  - LA LGBT Center health services (323-993-7500) offer LGBTQ+ primary care and sexual health services and can often help with hormones or referrals. [lalgbtcenter](https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/housing/)
  - SF LGBT Center can connect you with local clinics that provide gender-affirming care and financial counseling to stabilize your situation. [sfcenter](https://www.sfcenter.org/program/housing-financial/)

Documentation support (IDs, Medi-Cal, etc.)  
- BenefitsCal (https://benefitscal.com) lets you apply for or renew Medi-Cal, CalFresh, and CalWORKs; having stable benefits helps keep your gender-affirming care and meds covered. [sonomacounty](https://sonomacounty.gov/health-and-human-services/human-services/apply-online-at-benefitscal)
- If your ID doesn’t match your gender, you can still get benefits and health care; staff should use your affirmed name and pronouns and not deny services based on documentation. [calcivilrights.ca](https://calcivilrights.ca.gov/housing/)
- If you face discrimination at a government office or clinic because you are trans or nonbinary, document what happened and consider contacting:  
  - California Civil Rights Department (housing and some services): https://calcivilrights.ca.gov/housing. [calcivilrights.ca](https://calcivilrights.ca.gov/housing/)
  - ACLU of Southern California’s LGBTQ employment rights resources, which explain how state law protects against discrimination based on sexual orientation, gender identity, and gender expression. [aclusocal](https://www.aclusocal.org/know-your-rights/california-lgbtq-employment-rights/)

**Section D citations:** [alhambraca](https://www.alhambraca.gov/835/LA-County-Department-of-Mental-Health)

---  

E) MENTAL HEALTH, SUD TREATMENT, DV, SAFETY  

Core crisis lines  
- 988 Suicide & Crisis Lifeline  
  - Dial 988 from anywhere in California for 24/7 crisis counseling. [gov.ca](https://www.gov.ca.gov/2025/07/16/following-trump-cut-to-lgbtq-youth-suicide-hotline-california-steps-up-to-fill-the-gap/)
  - California’s 988 centers operate around the clock; a state partnership with The Trevor Project is improving LGBTQ+ affirming care. [gov.ca](https://www.gov.ca.gov/2025/07/16/following-trump-cut-to-lgbtq-youth-suicide-hotline-california-steps-up-to-fill-the-gap/)
- The Trevor Project (LGBTQ+ youth)  
  - Phone: 1-866-488-7386. [alhambraca](https://www.alhambraca.gov/835/LA-County-Department-of-Mental-Health)
- Trans Lifeline (peer support for trans people)  
  - US: 877-565-8860. [en.wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trans_Lifeline)

County behavioral health access  

Los Angeles County  
- LA County Department of Mental Health 24/7 Help Line (behavioral health & SUD): 800-854-7771. [dmh.lacounty](https://dmh.lacounty.gov/our-services/disaster-services/access-hotline/)
- The same number connects you to mental health screening, referrals, and substance use disorder services. [dmh.lacounty](https://dmh.lacounty.gov/get-help-now/)

San Francisco County  
- San Francisco County Behavioral Health Access Line: 888-246-3333 (per statewide Medi-Cal behavioral health access list). [med.stanford](https://med.stanford.edu/content/dam/sm/childpsychiatry/documents/Medi-Cal-Bx-Health-Access-Line-Information-by-County-2021-.pdf)

San Diego County  
- San Diego Access & Crisis Line (ACL): 1-888-724-7240 or 988, 24/7 for mental health and substance use issues, crisis intervention, and referrals. [sandiegocounty](https://www.sandiegocounty.gov/content/sdc/hhsa/programs/bhs/ACL.html)

Substance use treatment (SUD)  
- In California, county behavioral health departments (via access lines above) are the front door for publicly funded SUD treatment, including detox, residential, and outpatient programs, and can help you find LGBTQ-friendly services. [dmh.lacounty](https://dmh.lacounty.gov/get-help-now/)
- When you call, say: “I’m LGBTQ+, newly sober or trying to get sober, and I need an assessment for substance use treatment covered by Medi-Cal or for people without insurance.” [dmh.lacounty](https://dmh.lacounty.gov/get-help-now/)

Domestic violence and safety  
- 211 can connect you with local DV shelters and legal resources; tell them you are LGBTQ+ and need confidential DV services. [211](http://www.211.org)
- Many DV agencies do not require police reports to help you and will safety-plan around your immigration status or justice-involved history. [crla](https://crla.org/get-help/housing/evictions-and-lockouts/know-your-rights-eviction)
- If you are experiencing abuse and fear calling 911, you can still call 988 or county crisis lines first to talk through options and safety. [sandiegocounty](https://www.sandiegocounty.gov/content/sdc/hhsa/programs/bhs/ACL.html)

**Section E citations:** [dmh.lacounty](https://dmh.lacounty.gov/mental-health-resources/)

---  

F) EMPLOYMENT, TRAINING, SCHOOL  

America’s Job Center of California (AJCC)  
- AJCCs are California’s one-stop workforce centers, offering job search help, training, resume support, and connections to employers at no cost. [ajcc.lacounty](https://www.ajcc.lacounty.gov/ajcc)
- Many centers serve veterans, people with disabilities, low-income workers, and reentry populations; they can be particularly helpful if you’re justice-involved and LGBTQ+. [ajcc.lacounty](https://www.ajcc.lacounty.gov/ajcc)

Los Angeles County AJCCs  
- LA County operates 18 AJCC locations with employment experts, training options, and workshops. [ajcc.lacounty](https://www.ajcc.lacounty.gov/ajcc)
- Example: Veterans AJCC, 1816 S Figueroa St, Los Angeles, CA 90015, 213-742-9560. [ajcc.lacounty](https://www.ajcc.lacounty.gov/ajcc)
- You can walk in or call the nearest AJCC (see table on LA County AJCC site) and say: “I’m LGBTQ+, currently homeless or low income, and I need help with job training and finding work.” [ajcc.lacounty](https://www.ajcc.lacounty.gov/ajcc)

Education and training  
- AJCCs offer career exploration, skills assessments, and connections to high-quality training, which can include certificates, apprenticeships, or short-term programs; many have special programs for young adults. [ajcc.lacounty](https://www.ajcc.lacounty.gov/ajcc)
- Combining AJCC training with housing and case management from LGBTQ+ centers can help you move from survival jobs to more stable careers. [sfcenter](https://sfcenter.org)

**Section F citations:** [sfcenter](https://www.sfcenter.org/program/housing-financial/)

---  

G) LEGAL HELP & YOUR RIGHTS  

Housing discrimination and harassment  
- The California Civil Rights Department (CRD) enforces fair housing laws and explains that California’s fair housing protections apply regardless of citizenship or immigration status. [calcivilrights.ca](https://calcivilrights.ca.gov/housing/)
- If you experience housing discrimination based on sexual orientation, gender identity, or HIV status, you can file a complaint with CRD, and many cases are also automatically filed with HUD. [calcivilrights.ca](https://calcivilrights.ca.gov/housing/)

Eviction and tenant rights  
- California Rural Legal Assistance explains that the only legal way to evict a tenant is by filing a court case; landlords cannot lock you out, shut off utilities, or remove your belongings to force you out. [crla](https://crla.org/get-help/housing/evictions-and-lockouts/know-your-rights-eviction)
- LawHelpCA’s directory shows local legal aid organizations that help with housing issues, including eviction defense. [lawhelpca](https://www.lawhelpca.org/find-legal-help/directory/area)
- In LA County, Stay Housed LA is a county initiative that connects tenants facing eviction with legal assistance and workshops on tenant rights. [dcba.lacounty](https://dcba.lacounty.gov/newsroom/stay-housed-l-a-county-tenant-assistance-program-launched-free-legal-services-to-tenants-facing-eviction/)

Workplace discrimination  
- ACLU of Southern California notes that California law bans discrimination based on actual or perceived sexual orientation, gender identity, and gender expression in employment. [aclusocal](https://www.aclusocal.org/know-your-rights/california-lgbtq-employment-rights/)
- If you experience harassment, wrongful termination, or discrimination at work because you are LGBTQ+, you can contact your local ACLU affiliate and/or file with CRD’s employment division. [aclusocal](https://www.aclusocal.org/know-your-rights/california-lgbtq-employment-rights/)

Immigration and LGBTQ+  
- LawHelpCA lists nonprofit immigration legal providers, including those experienced with LGBTQ+ asylum, U visas for DV survivors, and other protections. [lawhelpca](https://www.lawhelpca.org/find-legal-help/directory/area)
- NCLR’s Legal Help Line and Lambda Legal’s Western Regional Office can help triage complex cases involving both immigration and LGBTQ+ issues. [lambdalegal](https://lambdalegal.org/contact/)

**Section G citations:** [resources.legallink](https://resources.legallink.org/referral/national-center-for-lesbian-rights-advice-line/)

---  

H) REGIONAL DIRECTORY (STATEWIDE + LA + BAY AREA + SAN DIEGO)  

Statewide / Anywhere in California  

| Need | Resource | Contact |
| --- | --- | --- |
| General help (food, shelter, DV, etc.) | 211 California | Dial 2-1-1, https://211ca.org.  [211ca](https://211ca.org) |
| Crisis line | 988 Suicide & Crisis Lifeline | Dial 988.  [gov.ca](https://www.gov.ca.gov/2025/07/16/following-trump-cut-to-lgbtq-youth-suicide-hotline-california-steps-up-to-fill-the-gap/) |
| LGBTQ youth crisis | The Trevor Project | 1-866-488-7386.  [alhambraca](https://www.alhambraca.gov/835/LA-County-Department-of-Mental-Health) |
| Trans peer support | Trans Lifeline | 877-565-8860.  [en.wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trans_Lifeline) |
| Legal aid directory | LawHelpCA | https://www.lawhelpca.org.  [lawhelpca](https://www.lawhelpca.org/find-legal-help/directory/area) |
| Civil rights in housing | California Civil Rights Department | https://calcivilrights.ca.gov/housing.  [calcivilrights.ca](https://calcivilrights.ca.gov/housing/) |
| Homeless veterans | VA National Call Center for Homeless Veterans | 877-4AID-VET (877-424-3838).  [va](https://www.va.gov/loma-linda-health-care/health-services/homeless-veteran-care/) |
| Benefits (Medi-Cal, CalFresh, CalWORKs) | BenefitsCal | https://benefitscal.com.  [sonomacounty](https://sonomacounty.gov/health-and-human-services/human-services/apply-online-at-benefitscal) |

Los Angeles County  

| Need | Resource | Contact |
| --- | --- | --- |
| LGBTQ+ center | Los Angeles LGBT Center | 323-993-7400, https://lalgbtcenter.org.  [lalgbtcenter](https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/housing/) |
| Youth housing | LA LGBT Center Youth Housing | Via Center housing page: https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/housing.  [lalgbtcenter](https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/housing/) |
| HIV care and support | APLA Health | 213-201-1426, https://aplahealth.org/service-type/hiv-support-services.  [aplahealth](https://aplahealth.org/service-type/hiv-support-services/) |
| HIV/STI, PrEP/PEP | LA LGBT Center Sexual Health Services | 323-993-7500, https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/sexual-health-services.  [lalgbtcenter](https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/sexual-health-services/) |
| Shelter/housing navigation | 211 LA, LA County CES | Dial 2-1-1 or 800-339-6993, https://211la.org.  [211la](https://211la.org/homeless-housing-support-programs) |
| Behavioral health access | LA County DMH Help Line | 800-854-7771 (24/7).  [dmh.lacounty](https://dmh.lacounty.gov/our-services/disaster-services/access-hotline/) |
| Eviction help | Stay Housed LA | https://www.stayhousedla.org.  [dcba.lacounty](https://dcba.lacounty.gov/newsroom/stay-housed-l-a-county-tenant-assistance-program-launched-free-legal-services-to-tenants-facing-eviction/) |
| Legal/LGBTQ impact | Lambda Legal Western Regional Office | 213-382-7600, https://lambdalegal.org/contact.  [lambdalegal](https://lambdalegal.org/contact/) |

Bay Area (focus on SF/Alameda)  

| Need | Resource | Contact |
| --- | --- | --- |
| LGBTQ+ center | SF LGBT Center | 415-865-5555, https://sfcenter.org.  [sfcenter](https://sfcenter.org) |
| Housing/financial counseling | SF LGBT Center Financial & Housing Services | https://www.sfcenter.org/program/housing-financial.  [sfcenter](https://www.sfcenter.org/program/housing-financial/) |
| Coordinated Entry (Alameda example) | Alameda County Coordinated Entry | https://homelessness.acgov.org/coordinated-entry.page.  [homelessness.acgov](https://homelessness.acgov.org/coordinated-entry.page) |
| HIV legal help | AIDS Legal Referral Panel (via LawHelpCA) | Access via LawHelpCA directory.  [lawhelpca](https://www.lawhelpca.org/find-legal-help/directory/area) |
| Behavioral health access | SF Behavioral Health Access Line | 888-246-3333.  [med.stanford](https://med.stanford.edu/content/dam/sm/childpsychiatry/documents/Medi-Cal-Bx-Health-Access-Line-Information-by-County-2021-.pdf) |

San Diego County  

| Need | Resource | Contact |
| --- | --- | --- |
| LGBTQ+ center | San Diego LGBT Community Center | 619-692-2077, https://thecentersd.org.  [thecentersd](https://thecentersd.org/timeline/the-sunburst-youth-housing-project/) |
| Youth housing | Sunburst Youth Housing Project (The Center) | Info via The Center’s site.  [thecentersd](https://thecentersd.org/timeline/the-sunburst-youth-housing-project/) |
| Behavioral health & crisis | San Diego Access & Crisis Line | 1-888-724-7240 or 988 (24/7).  [sandiegocounty](https://www.sandiegocounty.gov/content/sdc/hhsa/programs/bhs/ACL.html) |
| HIV care | AHF and county clinics | Find via 211 or AHF site.  [npin.cdc](https://npin.cdc.gov/organization/aids-healthcare-foundation-3) |
| Legal aid | LawHelpCA directory | https://www.lawhelpca.org.  [lawhelpca](https://www.lawhelpca.org/find-legal-help/directory/area) |

**Section H citations:** [va](https://www.va.gov/loma-linda-health-care/health-services/homeless-veteran-care/)

---  

I) PATHWAY MAP: FROM CRISIS TO STABILITY  

1) Safety + emergency shelter  
- First 24–72 hours: focus on where you can safely sleep and how to avoid immediate harm.  
- Call 211, local LGBTQ+ centers, and DV hotlines to get into emergency shelter, youth housing, DV shelter, or motel vouchers if available. [211ca](https://211ca.org)

2) ID + benefits setup  
- Within the first 1–2 weeks, work with case managers at shelters, LGBTQ+ centers, or outreach programs to replace ID and apply for benefits.  
- Use BenefitsCal to apply for Medi-Cal, CalFresh, and CalWORKs; these programs can stabilize food and health coverage while you focus on housing and work. [sonomacounty](https://sonomacounty.gov/health-and-human-services/human-services/apply-online-at-benefitscal)

3) Medical stabilization (HIV care, mental health, SUD treatment)  
- Once you have at least temporary shelter or a regular place to check in, connect with HIV/sexual health clinics, county behavioral health access lines, and SUD treatment programs.  
- Ask for LGBTQ+ competent providers where possible; LA LGBT Center, APLA Health, AHF, and county clinics can coordinate HIV care, mental health, and substance use support. [dmh.lacounty](https://dmh.lacounty.gov/our-services/disaster-services/access-hotline/)

4) Housing navigation (CES + housing programs)  
- Complete Coordinated Entry assessments with outreach teams or access points; make sure your LGBTQ+ identity and health needs (including HIV, disability, and DV) are recorded so they can prioritize you appropriately. [homelessness.acgov](https://homelessness.acgov.org/coordinated-entry.page)
- Stay in regular contact with your housing navigator and update them if your situation worsens (e.g., sleeping outside, safety threats). [homelessness.acgov](https://homelessness.acgov.org/coordinated-entry.page)

5) Income (employment + training)  
- When you have some stability, connect with AJCCs or LGBTQ+ center employment programs for job search, training, and placement support. [sfcenter](https://sfcenter.org)
- Focus first on income that keeps you stably housed (even if it’s not your dream job), then look at longer-term training. [ajcc.lacounty](https://www.ajcc.lacounty.gov/ajcc)

6) Long-term housing (vouchers, affordable housing, supportive housing)  
- Work with case managers and housing navigators to apply for vouchers, project-based units, or supportive housing that fits your needs (e.g., HIV supportive housing, youth housing, or permanent supportive housing). [211la](https://211la.org/homeless-housing-support-programs)
- Use SF LGBT Center’s financial counseling or similar services to plan for rent, debt, and credit, so you can keep housing once you get it. [sfcenter](https://www.sfcenter.org/community/how-the-center-helps-lgbtq-families-achieve-their-dreams/)

**Section I citations:** [dmh.lacounty](https://dmh.lacounty.gov/our-services/disaster-services/access-hotline/)

---  

J) COMMON PITFALLS (AND HOW TO AVOID THEM)  

1) Not asking for LGBTQ+-competent case management  
- Many systems will not automatically connect you with affirming providers; you have to ask.  
- When you call 211, clinics, or shelters, say: “I am LGBTQ+ and would like an affirming case manager or provider if possible.” [lalgbtcenter](https://lalgbtcenter.org/services/sexual-health-services/)

2) Not documenting discrimination or mistreatment  
- If a shelter, landlord, or employer discriminates against you, write down dates, names, what was said, and any witnesses.  
- This record helps when you contact Lambda Legal, NCLR, ACLU, or the Civil Rights Department to enforce your rights. [lambdalegal](https://lambdalegal.org/contact/)

3) Missing waitlist mail or losing contact  
- Housing programs often send letters or call once; if they can’t reach you, they may drop your spot.  
- Use a stable mailing address (LGBTQ+ center, shelter, or PO box) and voicemail greeting, and check in regularly with your housing navigator. [sfcenter](https://www.sfcenter.org/program/housing-financial/)

4) Not updating contact info  
- Whenever you change phones, emails, or addresses, immediately update 211 referrals, case managers, clinics, and housing programs.  
- You can usually update contact info by calling the program front desk or your county access line. [dmh.lacounty](https://dmh.lacounty.gov/get-help-now/)

5) Thinking “one application solves everything”  
- In California, you often need multiple applications: BenefitsCal for benefits, CES intake for housing, clinic intake for medical, AJCC intake for jobs, and separate legal intakes. [sonomacounty](https://sonomacounty.gov/health-and-human-services/human-services/apply-online-at-benefitscal)
- Build a simple list (on paper or in your phone) of: which programs you applied to, dates, contact names, and when to follow up. [sfcenter](https://www.sfcenter.org/program/housing-financial/)

**Section J citations:** [resources.legallink](https://resources.legallink.org/referral/national-center-for-lesbian-rights-advice-line/)

You deserve safety, competent care, and respect in every system you touch in California, no matter your gender, sexuality, HIV status, immigration status, or justice history. These tools are here to help you move from surviving tonight to building real stability over the months ahead.
