rows.summary: Comprehensive guide for domestic violence survivors in California. Covers emergency safety, restraining orders, confidential shelters, legal protections, housing pathways, CalWORKs assistance, and trauma recovery. Includes hotlines and resources for LA, Orange, and San Diego Counties, with support for all genders and LGBTQ+ survivors.

rows.title: Anger Management Classes in 2026 - California Court and Community Guide
rows.content:
Anger management classes in 2026 range from short online courses to long-term, court-approved programs, and the right choice depends on your goals, your court order (if any), and your budget. [courseforanger](https://courseforanger.com/states/CA)

***

## Section 1: What Is Anger Management?

Anger management is a structured, skills-based approach to understanding your anger, identifying triggers, and replacing impulsive reactions with safer, more effective responses. It is usually delivered as a class or group, not just unstructured talking, and focuses on practical tools like breathing, time-outs, communication skills, and problem-solving. [canr.msu](https://www.canr.msu.edu/alternatives_to_anger)

The main goals of anger management are to:  
- Reduce how often and how intensely you feel anger.  
- Help you pause before acting, so you avoid violence, threats, or destructive behavior.  
- Improve communication, relationships, and decision-making under stress. [dbtcentersouthbay](https://www.dbtcentersouthbay.com/dbt-skills-for-managing-anger/)

Anger management classes are different from individual therapy. Therapy usually focuses more deeply on trauma, depression, and long-term emotional patterns, while anger classes are often shorter, more educational, with a fixed curriculum and clear completion requirements (for example, 10–52 sessions). Many people take anger management for personal growth (to improve relationships, parenting, or work behavior), while others do it because a court, probation officer, CPS, or employer ordered it as a condition of probation, diversion, custody, or keeping a job. [bisclasses](https://www.bisclasses.com/angermanagementprogram.html)

Helpful references:  
- RELAX: Alternatives to Anger – Michigan State University Extension: https://www.canr.msu.edu/alternatives_to_anger [canr.msu](https://www.canr.msu.edu/alternatives_to_anger)
- DBT skills for managing anger – DBT Center of the South Bay: https://www.dbtcentersouthbay.com/dbt-skills-for-managing-anger/ [dbtcentersouthbay](https://www.dbtcentersouthbay.com/dbt-skills-for-managing-anger/)
- RELAX Online course overview: https://www.canr.msu.edu/alternatives_to_anger/relax_alternatives_to_anger_online [canr.msu](https://www.canr.msu.edu/alternatives_to_anger/relax_alternatives_to_anger_online)
- Christian Leaders Institute free anger class (faith-based): https://www.christianleadersinstitute.org/free-anger-management-class/ [christianleadersinstitute](https://www.christianleadersinstitute.org/free-anger-management-class/)

***

## Section 2: Court-Ordered vs. Personal Choice

Courts commonly require anger management in cases involving domestic violence–related charges, criminal threats, assault, road rage incidents, probation violations, and sometimes DUI where there was aggressive conduct. Family courts also use anger management in custody, visitation, and CPS cases where there are concerns about parenting under stress, verbal abuse, or intimidating behavior. [copefamilysupport](https://copefamilysupport.org/anger-management-classes/)

Your court order usually specifies:  
- The number of hours or weeks (e.g., “12-week anger management” or “52-week BTP/anger management”). [ajnovickgroup](https://www.ajnovickgroup.com/anger-management/weekly-classes.aspx)
- Whether the program must be “court-approved,” “probation-approved,” or on a specific county list. [thecaamp](https://www.thecaamp.com/pdf/Los%20Angeles%20County%20Probation%20Anger%20Management%20Providers_20230724_0001%20(1).pdf)
- Any format restrictions (for example, “in-person group,” or “no online-only classes”). [namass](https://www.namass.org)

To confirm which providers the court accepts, you can:  
- Ask the clerk, your attorney, or probation officer if there is an approved provider list.  
- Use official county or court referral lists (many are PDFs on court or probation websites). [file.lacounty](https://file.lacounty.gov/SDSInter/probation/1186203_BIPlistJune2025.pdf)
- Call the program and ask, “Do you have clients from [X Superior Court] or [X County Probation]? Are you on their approved list?” [ajnovickgroup](https://www.ajnovickgroup.com/anger-management/weekly-classes.aspx)

For documentation, courts typically want:  
- Proof of enrollment.  
- Regular attendance logs or progress reports (especially for longer programs).  
- A final certificate with your full name, dates, hours or sessions completed, program name and address, and a signature/license or credential of the facilitator. [schroedercounseling](https://www.schroedercounseling.com/court-approved-anger-management-classes)

Helpful references:  
- Los Angeles County Probation anger management provider list (PDF): https://www.thecaamp.com/pdf/Los%20Angeles%20County%20Probation%20Anger%20Management%20Providers_20230724_0001%20(1).pdf [thecaamp](https://www.thecaamp.com/pdf/Los%20Angeles%20County%20Probation%20Anger%20Management%20Providers_20230724_0001%20(1).pdf)
- Sacramento Superior Court anger management services criteria/list (PDF): https://www.saccourt.ca.gov/family/docs/fl-dv-anger-management-list.pdf [saccourt.ca](https://www.saccourt.ca.gov/family/docs/fl-dv-anger-management-list.pdf)
- COPE Family Support (Bay Area court-approved classes): https://copefamilysupport.org/anger-management-classes/ [copefamilysupport](https://copefamilysupport.org/anger-management-classes/)
- National Anger Management Association statement on court-ordered online programs: https://www.namass.org [namass](https://www.namass.org)

***

## Section 3: How to Choose the Right Class

When you choose a class, you want to satisfy your legal requirements and actually learn skills you can use. A few key dimensions matter.

### Accreditation and licensing

For court cases, look for:  
- Licensed mental health providers (LCSW, LMFT, LPCC, psychologist) or certified anger management specialists.  
- Programs recognized by local courts, probation, or professional bodies like the National Anger Management Association (NAMA). [namass](https://www.namass.org)

Some counties publish standards for anger programs (e.g., Sacramento’s Family Court requires specific core topics and minimum facilitator training). [saccourt.ca](https://www.saccourt.ca.gov/family/docs/fl-dv-anger-management-list.pdf)

### Court-required list or open choice

In some counties, you must pick a provider from a court or probation list (for example, LA County Probation anger management provider PDF). Other courts allow any “qualified” provider, but you still carry the risk that an unknown online-only website may not be accepted. Always check before you pay. [courseforanger](https://courseforanger.com/states/CA)

### Individual vs. group

- Group classes: Usually weekly, more affordable, and common for court orders (e.g., 10–52 weeks). [apathforchange](https://www.apathforchange.org)
- Individual sessions: More flexible and private, often higher cost per hour, sometimes used to meet work requirements or when groups are not available. [whatsgoodaboutanger](http://www.whatsgoodaboutanger.com)

### Online vs. in-person

- Fully online, self-paced courses are widely marketed and often acceptable for some courts and employers, but many judges, probation departments, and NAMA caution against online-only self-paced classes without a live component for serious or DV-related cases. [aatpp](https://aatpp.com/course-anger-management.php)
- Live online (Zoom/telehealth) groups can satisfy many court orders because they resemble in-person groups with attendance tracking. [angermanagementseminar](https://www.angermanagementseminar.com)
- In-person classes are still preferred by many courts, especially for higher-risk cases. [copefamilysupport](https://copefamilysupport.org/anger-management-classes/)

### Cost, insurance, and sliding scale

Typical ranges:  
- Community or court-referred group: about 20–35 USD per session, plus a one-time enrollment fee. [bisclasses](https://www.bisclasses.com/angermanagementprogram.html)
- Private practice therapist: 125–250 USD per session, sometimes billable to insurance if coded as therapy. [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/california?category=anger-management)
- Online self-paced courses: often 25–100 USD total, depending on hours. [americanhealthtraining](https://www.americanhealthtraining.com/online-anger-management-class/)

Some nonprofits and county programs offer sliding scale or low-cost options; they may ask for proof of income to set your fee. County mental health systems sometimes provide anger groups as part of broader services, especially for Medi-Cal or low-income clients. [dmh.lacounty](https://dmh.lacounty.gov/get-help-now/)

### Language access and trauma-informed care

If English is not your first language, look for classes in Spanish or other languages or bilingual facilitators (county lists often show languages). Trauma-informed providers recognize that past abuse, violence, or war can shape how anger shows up and focus on safety, shame reduction, and regulation rather than just punishment. [lavidacounselingcenter](https://www.lavidacounselingcenter.com/anger-management.html)

### Questions to ask before you sign up

You can use these sample questions when you call or email:  
- “Is your program on the approved list for [X County] Court or Probation?”  
- “How many weeks or hours is the program, and how often do classes meet?”  
- “Do you provide a certificate of completion that lists my hours, dates, and case number if needed?”  
- “What is the cost per session, are there any enrollment or workbook fees, and do you offer sliding scale?”  
- “Is this group in-person, live online, or self-paced online? Will my court accept this format?”  
- “Do you work with people who have domestic violence–related charges or child welfare cases?”  

Helpful references:  
- NAMA’s note on court-ordered online programs: https://www.namass.org [namass](https://www.namass.org)
- Behavioral Intervention Services Anger Management Program (pricing example): https://www.bisclasses.com/angermanagementprogram.html [bisclasses](https://www.bisclasses.com/angermanagementprogram.html)
- Course For Anger (national online cost breakdown): https://courseforanger.com/states/CA [courseforanger](https://courseforanger.com/states/CA)
- A Path for Change (BTP/anger management with sliding fees): https://www.apathforchange.org [apathforchange](https://www.apathforchange.org)

***

## Section 4: General National Resources

These resources are not California-specific and can be used across the U.S. Always confirm that a given option is acceptable in your court.

### Telamon Corporation Anger-Related Services

Telamon Corporation operates in 11 states and offers early childhood, family support, workforce, and housing programs, with mental health consultation and parenting/behavior support in some regions. In some local Telamon programs, parents can access behavioral supports that include managing children’s behavior and adult stress/anger; availability varies by state. [telamon](https://www.telamon.org)
- Website: https://www.telamon.org [telamon](https://www.telamon.org)
- Phone (National/Headquarters, check by state): listed by state office on https://www.telamon.org/what-we-do/ [telamon](https://www.telamon.org/what-we-do/)
- Cost: Often grant-funded or low-cost for eligible families; contact your local office for details. [telamon](https://www.telamon.org/early-childhood-mental-health-consultation/)
- Format: Typically in-person or on-site with partners, sometimes including consultation in early childhood programs. [telamon](https://www.telamon.org/early-childhood-mental-health-consultation/)

### Anger Management Institute (What’s Good About Anger)

The Anger Management Institute provides evidence-based anger management courses, books, and provider trainings, with options for individual Zoom sessions, 6–8 week online training courses, and court-ordered online anger programs. Some services are restricted to Illinois residents for live work, but self-guided online trainings are available nationally. [whatsgoodaboutanger](http://www.whatsgoodaboutanger.com)
- Website: http://www.whatsgoodaboutanger.com [whatsgoodaboutanger](http://www.whatsgoodaboutanger.com)
- Contact: Via contact form on website; phone listed in their “Contact Us” section. [whatsgoodaboutanger](http://www.whatsgoodaboutanger.com)
- Cost: Varies by course; online self-directed courses tend to be moderate cost (roughly in line with other online programs). [whatsgoodaboutanger](http://www.whatsgoodaboutanger.com)
- Format: Self-paced online courses, Zoom or phone individual sessions, resources for court-ordered clients. [whatsgoodaboutanger](http://www.whatsgoodaboutanger.com)

### Breathe For Change (Educator Wellbeing & Stress/Anger)

Breathe For Change focuses on social–emotional learning and mindfulness for educators, offering yoga, mindfulness, and emotional regulation training that can help with stress and anger in school settings. It is not a classic court-ordered anger management provider but is useful for teachers or school staff needing structured stress and emotion regulation support. [asset.library.wisc](https://asset.library.wisc.edu/1711.dl/23Y3PINAPV4TS9D/R/file-5ab8e.pdf)
- Website: https://www.breatheforchange.com (linked from coverage and program materials). [namidanecounty](https://www.namidanecounty.org/blog/2017/3/14/breathe-for-change)
- Cost: Program-based tuition; often paid by districts or as professional development.  
- Format: Online and retreat-style trainings for educators, with SEL and mindfulness for stress and anger. [asset.library.wisc](https://asset.library.wisc.edu/1711.dl/23Y3PINAPV4TS9D/R/file-5ab8e.pdf)

### Psychology Today Anger Management Directory

Psychology Today hosts a national directory of therapists, treatment centers, and groups, including filters for “Anger Management” and location. You can search by ZIP code and then filter for insurance, language, and type of service (individual, group, in person, or telehealth). [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/ca/los-angeles?category=anger-management)
- Directory for groups (California example): https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/california?category=anger-management [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/california?category=anger-management)
- Directory for Los Angeles County groups: https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/ca/los-angeles-county?category=anger-management [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/ca/los-angeles-county?category=anger-management)
- Cost: Varies; many listings show session rates and whether they accept insurance. [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/california?category=anger-management)
- Format: Individual therapy, groups, DBT skills groups, both in-person and online. [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/ca/los-angeles?category=anger-management)

### Mental Health America (MHA) Anger Resources

Mental Health America provides online information about anger and frustration, including self-help tips, screening tools, and resource links. These pages are not “classes” but are helpful for education, worksheets, and finding local mental health support. [screening.mhanational](https://screening.mhanational.org/content/im-really-angry-world/)
- “Dealing with Anger and Frustration”: https://mhanational.org/resources/dealing-with-anger-and-frustration/ [mhanational](https://mhanational.org/resources/dealing-with-anger-and-frustration/)
- “I’m really angry at the world”: https://screening.mhanational.org/content/im-really-angry-world/ [screening.mhanational](https://screening.mhanational.org/content/im-really-angry-world/)
- Cost: Free educational content.  
- Format: Online articles, self-help tools, links to local affiliates. [mhanational](https://mhanational.org/resources/dealing-with-anger-and-frustration/)

### DBT Skills Groups (Anger Modules)

Dialectical Behavior Therapy (DBT) skills groups often include anger-related content under Emotion Regulation, Distress Tolerance, and Interpersonal Effectiveness modules. Some DBT groups are open to court-ordered clients, though they may not be labeled “anger management.” [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/ca/los-angeles?category=anger-management)
- Example DBT resource: DBT Center of South Bay – “DBT Skills for Managing Anger”: https://www.dbtcentersouthbay.com/dbt-skills-for-managing-anger/ [dbtcentersouthbay](https://www.dbtcentersouthbay.com/dbt-skills-for-managing-anger/)
- Example directory listing: DBT-focused groups in Los Angeles on Psychology Today: https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/ca/los-angeles?category=anger-management [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/ca/los-angeles?category=anger-management)
- Cost: Usually similar to therapy groups, often 50–80 USD per group session; some accept insurance. [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/california?category=anger-management)
- Format: Weekly group, in-person or virtual, structured workbook-based skills training. [dbtcentersouthbay](https://www.dbtcentersouthbay.com/dbt-skills-for-managing-anger/)

***

## Section 5: California-Specific Anger Management Classes

Below are examples of programs and directories; availability and acceptance can change, so always confirm with your court or probation officer.

### A) Los Angeles County

1. **Sherman Oaks Anger Management / Anger Management 411 (court- and probation-oriented)**  
   - Appears on LA County probation/BIP provider lists under “Anger Management 411” and “Sherman Oaks Anger Management.” [file.lacounty](https://file.lacounty.gov/SDSInter/probation/1186203_BIPlistJune2025.pdf)
   - Website: https://www.shermanoaksangermanagement.com (listed in LA Probation PDF). [thecaamp](https://www.thecaamp.com/pdf/Los%20Angeles%20County%20Probation%20Anger%20Management%20Providers_20230724_0001%20(1).pdf)
   - Phone: (818) 754-4754. [thecaamp](https://www.thecaamp.com/pdf/Los%20Angeles%20County%20Probation%20Anger%20Management%20Providers_20230724_0001%20(1).pdf)
   - Cost: Similar programs charge around 20–35 USD per class plus enrollment; confirm current rates. [bisclasses](https://www.bisclasses.com/angermanagementprogram.html)
   - Format: Group classes, with both in-person and Zoom-based sessions reported via directories. [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/ca/los-angeles-county?category=anger-management)
   - Notes: Serves self-referred and court-ordered clients; appears on LA County probation-approved lists. [file.lacounty](https://file.lacounty.gov/SDSInter/probation/1186203_BIPlistJune2025.pdf)

2. **Anger Under Control – South Bay**  
   - Listed on LA County Probation’s approved anger management provider list as “Anger Under Control.” [thecaamp](https://www.thecaamp.com/pdf/Los%20Angeles%20County%20Probation%20Anger%20Management%20Providers_20230724_0001%20(1).pdf)
   - Email: angerundercontrol@yahoo.com. [thecaamp](https://www.thecaamp.com/pdf/Los%20Angeles%20County%20Probation%20Anger%20Management%20Providers_20230724_0001%20(1).pdf)
   - Phone: (310) 873-3113. [thecaamp](https://www.thecaamp.com/pdf/Los%20Angeles%20County%20Probation%20Anger%20Management%20Providers_20230724_0001%20(1).pdf)
   - Format: Group classes; many probation-approved programs offer in-person or hybrid; confirm by phone. [thecaamp](https://www.thecaamp.com/pdf/Los%20Angeles%20County%20Probation%20Anger%20Management%20Providers_20230724_0001%20(1).pdf)
   - Notes: On LA County Probation approved list; good option when probation requires a listed provider. [thecaamp](https://www.thecaamp.com/pdf/Los%20Angeles%20County%20Probation%20Anger%20Management%20Providers_20230724_0001%20(1).pdf)

3. **LA County Department of Mental Health (DMH) – Access Line**

   LA County DMH coordinates county-funded mental health services; some contract clinics include anger management or emotional regulation groups as part of treatment. [dmh.lacounty](https://dmh.lacounty.gov/get-help-now/)
   - Website: https://dmh.lacounty.gov/get-help-now/ [dmh.lacounty](https://dmh.lacounty.gov/get-help-now/)
   - 24/7 Help Line: (800) 854‑7771 (TTY: 711) – ask for clinics offering anger or emotional regulation groups.  
   - Cost: Often Medi-Cal funded or low/no cost for eligible residents. [dmh.lacounty](https://dmh.lacounty.gov/get-help-now/)
   - Format: In-person or telehealth groups and individual therapy depending on clinic. [dmh.lacounty](https://dmh.lacounty.gov/get-help-now/)
   - Notes: Not all are “court programs,” so confirm with court if you plan to use DMH groups for a legal requirement. [dmh.lacounty](https://dmh.lacounty.gov/get-help-now/)

4. **Community & Private Groups via Psychology Today (LA County)**  
   - Directory: https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/ca/los-angeles-county?category=anger-management [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/ca/los-angeles-county?category=anger-management)
   - Example listing: New Directions, La Mirada – anger management group appropriate for DCFS, court, or probation requirements; 10–52 sessions with enrollment and completion certificates. [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/ca/los-angeles-county?category=anger-management)
   - Phone (example New Directions): (562) 943‑6000. [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/ca/los-angeles-county?category=anger-management)
   - Cost: Varies; many groups are mid-range (40–80 USD per group) and some accept insurance. [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/california?category=anger-management)
   - Format: In-person, online, or hybrid weekly groups. [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/ca/los-angeles-county?category=anger-management)

5. **Court Referral Lists (LA Superior Court)**  
   - LA Superior Court Parent Education and related services referral list (includes some parenting/anger-focused programs): https://www.lacourt.org/division/familylaw/pdf/referrallistforparents.pdf [lacourt](https://www.lacourt.org/division/familylaw/pdf/referrallistforparents.pdf)
   - Notes: These lists are “courtesy” lists and not endorsements, but they show programs often accepted in family court. [lacourt](https://www.lacourt.org/division/familylaw/pdf/referrallistforparents.pdf)

Key LA references:  
- LA County Probation anger management providers (PDF): https://www.thecaamp.com/pdf/Los%20Angeles%20County%20Probation%20Anger%20Management%20Providers_20230724_0001%20(1).pdf [thecaamp](https://www.thecaamp.com/pdf/Los%20Angeles%20County%20Probation%20Anger%20Management%20Providers_20230724_0001%20(1).pdf)
- LA DMH help page: https://dmh.lacounty.gov/get-help-now/ [dmh.lacounty](https://dmh.lacounty.gov/get-help-now/)
- Psychology Today LA anger groups: https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/ca/los-angeles-county?category=anger-management [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/ca/los-angeles-county?category=anger-management)

### B) Orange County

1. **AJ Novick Group – Anger Management Classes**

   - Website: https://www.ajnovickgroup.com/anger-management/weekly-classes.aspx [ajnovickgroup](https://www.ajnovickgroup.com/anger-management/weekly-classes.aspx)
   - Phone: (949) 715‑2694. [ajnovickgroup](https://www.ajnovickgroup.com/anger-management/weekly-classes.aspx)
   - Cost: Typically per-session fee; classes are open-ended with recommended minimum 10 sessions; exact rates listed on site (commonly similar to 30–40 USD per group). [ajnovickgroup](https://www.ajnovickgroup.com/anger-management/weekly-classes.aspx)
   - Format: Live, instructor-led classes via Zoom for adults. [ajnovickgroup](https://www.ajnovickgroup.com/anger-management/weekly-classes.aspx)
   - Notes: Approved by Orange County Probation Department since 2004; offers 10, 12, 22, 26, and 52-week classes for court- and probation-ordered clients. [ajnovickgroup](https://www.ajnovickgroup.com/anger-management/weekly-classes.aspx)

2. **La Vida Life Counseling Center – Anger Management**

   - Website: https://www.lavidacounselingcenter.com/anger-management.html [lavidacounselingcenter](https://www.lavidacounselingcenter.com/anger-management.html)
   - Phone: Listed on the center’s site (La Vida Counseling Center contact page). [lavidacounselingcenter](https://www.lavidacounselingcenter.com/anger-management.html)
   - Cost: 10-week class; specific pricing on request; many similar programs are 25–35 USD per class. [lavidacounselingcenter](https://www.lavidacounselingcenter.com/anger-management.html)
   - Format: 10-week classes for youth and adults; in-person, with English and Spanish options. [lavidacounselingcenter](https://www.lavidacounselingcenter.com/anger-management.html)
   - Notes: Fulfills requirements of court or probation-ordered classes in Orange County, California. [lavidacounselingcenter](https://www.lavidacounselingcenter.com/anger-management.html)

3. **County Mental Health / OC Health Care Agency**

   Some Behavioral Health Services programs in Orange County provide groups for emotional regulation and related issues, though they may not be labeled strictly as anger management.  
   - General Behavioral Health info (San Diego example for structure): https://www.sandiegocounty.gov/content/sdc/hhsa/programs/bhs.html [sandiegocounty](https://www.sandiegocounty.gov/content/sdc/hhsa/programs/bhs.html)
   - For Orange County, check OC Health Care Agency Behavioral Health website and ask specifically about anger groups and court acceptance.  

4. **Additional Providers via Directories**

   Use Psychology Today’s anger management filter for Orange County to identify local therapists and groups; many list “court-ordered anger management accepted” in descriptions. [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/california?category=anger-management)
   - Directory: https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/california?category=anger-management [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/california?category=anger-management)

Key OC references:  
- AJ Novick Group anger management: https://www.ajnovickgroup.com/anger-management/weekly-classes.aspx [ajnovickgroup](https://www.ajnovickgroup.com/anger-management/weekly-classes.aspx)
- La Vida Life Counseling Center: https://www.lavidacounselingcenter.com/anger-management.html [lavidacounselingcenter](https://www.lavidacounselingcenter.com/anger-management.html)
- CA-wide anger providers search (Psychology Today): https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/california?category=anger-management [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/california?category=anger-management)

### C) San Diego County

1. **San Diego County Behavioral Health Services**

   San Diego County BHS oversees prevention and treatment programs; some contracted providers offer group-based interventions for anger, aggression, and emotional regulation as part of mental health treatment. [sandiegocounty](https://www.sandiegocounty.gov/content/sdc/hhsa/programs/bhs.html)
   - Website: https://www.sandiegocounty.gov/content/sdc/hhsa/programs/bhs.html [sandiegocounty](https://www.sandiegocounty.gov/content/sdc/hhsa/programs/bhs.html)
   - Access and Crisis Line: Listed on the BHS website; call and ask for clinics that run anger/emotion regulation groups.  
   - Cost: Often Medi-Cal funded or sliding scale.  
   - Format: In-person or telehealth groups; not all will be set up as “certificate” programs, so confirm if you need court documentation. [sandiegocounty](https://www.sandiegocounty.gov/content/sdc/hhsa/programs/bhs.html)

2. **Private & Treatment-Center–Based Anger Programs**

   Several treatment centers in San Diego County include anger management as part of broader mental health or substance use programs (especially for teens and adults with co-occurring issues). [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/treatment-rehab/ca/san-diego-county?category=anger-management)
   - Psychology Today directory for treatment centers: https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/treatment-rehab/ca/san-diego-county?category=anger-management [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/treatment-rehab/ca/san-diego-county?category=anger-management)
   - Cost: Program-based (PHP/IOP or residential); may be covered by insurance.  
   - Format: Structured group curricula, including DBT and CBT for anger and impulse control. [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/treatment-rehab/ca/san-diego-county?category=anger-management)

3. **Local Court-Approved Providers**

   San Diego Superior Court and Probation often maintain internal lists of approved anger management providers; you can ask the probation department or court clerk for the most recent list. If unavailable, choose programs that can document curriculum and hours clearly, and ask them whether they regularly serve San Diego court-referred clients. [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/treatment-rehab/ca/san-diego-county?category=anger-management)

Key SD references:  
- San Diego County Behavioral Health: https://www.sandiegocounty.gov/content/sdc/hhsa/programs/bhs.html [sandiegocounty](https://www.sandiegocounty.gov/content/sdc/hhsa/programs/bhs.html)
- San Diego anger-related treatment centers directory: https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/treatment-rehab/ca/san-diego-county?category=anger-management [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/treatment-rehab/ca/san-diego-county?category=anger-management)

### D) Other Major California Cities (Sacramento, San Francisco, Alameda/Bay Area)

1. **COPE Family Support Center – Bay Area (East Bay / SF / Santa Clara)**  
   - Website: https://copefamilysupport.org/anger-management-classes/ [copefamilysupport](https://copefamilysupport.org/anger-management-classes/)
   - Phone: Listed on site under contact; serves Contra Costa, Alameda, San Francisco, and Santa Clara referrals. [copefamilysupport](https://copefamilysupport.org/anger-management-classes/)
   - Cost: Sliding scale classes; fees vary by income; many families find them more affordable than private therapy. [copefamilysupport](https://copefamilysupport.org/anger-management-classes/)
   - Format: Court-approved anger management classes; group-based, often online or in-person as available. [copefamilysupport](https://copefamilysupport.org/anger-management-classes/)
   - Notes: Approved by Contra Costa, Alameda, San Francisco, and Santa Clara Superior Courts; trauma-informed and culturally respectful. [copefamilysupport](https://copefamilysupport.org/anger-management-classes/)

2. **Sacramento Superior Court – Anger Management Service Requirements**

   Sacramento publishes criteria and a list for anger management service providers for Family Court cases. [saccourt.ca](https://www.saccourt.ca.gov/family/docs/fl-dv-anger-management-list.pdf)
   - Provider requirements and core topics (PDF): https://www.saccourt.ca.gov/family/docs/fl-dv-anger-management-list.pdf [saccourt.ca](https://www.saccourt.ca.gov/family/docs/fl-dv-anger-management-list.pdf)
   - Notes: This document explains what the court expects (40 hours facilitator training, required curriculum topics); use it to choose a provider that meets these standards. [saccourt.ca](https://www.saccourt.ca.gov/family/docs/fl-dv-anger-management-list.pdf)

3. **Local Providers in Sacramento and SF via Directories**

   - Use Psychology Today to find anger management groups in Sacramento, San Francisco, and Alameda counties, filtering by “Anger Management” and “Group” or “Telehealth.” [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/california?category=anger-management)
   - Confirm with each provider whether they are accepted by the local court or probation.  

Key references:  
- COPE Family Support anger classes: https://copefamilysupport.org/anger-management-classes/ [copefamilysupport](https://copefamilysupport.org/anger-management-classes/)
- Sacramento anger management provider guidelines: https://www.saccourt.ca.gov/family/docs/fl-dv-anger-management-list.pdf [saccourt.ca](https://www.saccourt.ca.gov/family/docs/fl-dv-anger-management-list.pdf)
- CA anger group directory: https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/california?category=anger-management [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/california?category=anger-management)

***

## Section 6: Free or Low-Cost Options

If money is tight, you still have real options.

- **County mental health clinics**: In LA and other counties, publicly funded behavioral health clinics can offer groups for emotional regulation, stress, and sometimes anger as part of treatment, usually at low or no cost with Medi-Cal. [sandiegocounty](https://www.sandiegocounty.gov/content/sdc/hhsa/programs/bhs.html)
- **Nonprofit programs**: COPE Family Support (Bay Area) offers sliding scale court-approved classes; some community organizations in LA and other counties also run low-cost groups. [211la](https://211la.org/services/HxNxbmpqmUE42voEHJBE2NWhEBWd8N/anger-management)
- **Community colleges and adult education**: Some community college continuing education or extension programs offer stress and anger management workshops, which may help for personal growth; courts may or may not accept them, so always ask first.  
- **Free online modules**: MSU Extension’s RELAX: Alternatives to Anger is a self-paced, free or low-cost online course to improve anger and stress skills, though it is not usually marketed as a court compliance tool. Christian Leaders Institute offers a free faith-based anger management class after a short orientation. [canr.msu](https://www.canr.msu.edu/alternatives_to_anger/relax_alternatives_to_anger_online)

Key references:  
- LA County DMH: https://dmh.lacounty.gov/get-help-now/ [dmh.lacounty](https://dmh.lacounty.gov/get-help-now/)
- San Diego County Behavioral Health: https://www.sandiegocounty.gov/content/sdc/hhsa/programs/bhs.html [sandiegocounty](https://www.sandiegocounty.gov/content/sdc/hhsa/programs/bhs.html)
- RELAX Online course: https://www.canr.msu.edu/alternatives_to_anger/relax_alternatives_to_anger_online [canr.msu](https://www.canr.msu.edu/alternatives_to_anger/relax_alternatives_to_anger_online)
- Christian Leaders Institute free anger class: https://www.christianleadersinstitute.org/free-anger-management-class/ [christianleadersinstitute](https://www.christianleadersinstitute.org/free-anger-management-class/)

***

## Section 7: Online Anger Management Courses

Online options are convenient, but always verify court acceptance, especially for criminal or DV-related cases.

### CBT-Based Self-Paced Courses

1. **Course For Anger – California & Nationwide**  
   - Website: https://courseforanger.com/states/CA [courseforanger](https://courseforanger.com/states/CA)
   - Cost: 4-hour course 25 USD, 8-hour 45 USD, 12-hour 65 USD, with higher-hour options; certificate included. [courseforanger](https://courseforanger.com/states/CA)
   - Format: 100% online, self-paced, accessible on any device; instant certificate by email on completion. [courseforanger](https://courseforanger.com/states/CA)
   - Notes: Markets itself as satisfying court, legal, probation, and employment requirements nationwide, but your judge/probation still has final say. [courseforanger](https://courseforanger.com/states/CA)

2. **AATPP – Online Anger Management Course**  
   - Website: https://aatpp.com/course-anger-management.php [aatpp](https://aatpp.com/course-anger-management.php)
   - Cost: Offers 4-, 8-, and 12-hour courses with variable timeframes; pricing similar to other online CBT courses. [aatpp](https://aatpp.com/course-anger-management.php)
   - Format: Self-paced CBT-based program for adults and teens; used for court, school, probation, or personal development, with certificate. [aatpp](https://aatpp.com/course-anger-management.php)

3. **OnlineCourseForCourt – California Anger Management Course**

   - Website: https://onlinecourseforcourt.com/california/product/anger-management-course/ [onlinecourseforcourt](https://onlinecourseforcourt.com/california/product/anger-management-course/)
   - Format: Structured online modules teaching anger awareness, triggers, coping strategies, and relaxation, with certificates and flexible pacing. [onlinecourseforcourt](https://onlinecourseforcourt.com/california/product/anger-management-course/)
   - Cost: Listed on product page; generally similar to other online court programs. [onlinecourseforcourt](https://onlinecourseforcourt.com/california/product/anger-management-course/)

4. **American Health Training – Online Anger Management**

   - Website: https://www.americanhealthtraining.com/online-anger-management-class/ [americanhealthtraining](https://www.americanhealthtraining.com/online-anger-management-class/)
   - Format: Flexible 100% online course with certificate and QR-code verification; geared for both personal development and mandates. [americanhealthtraining](https://www.americanhealthtraining.com/online-anger-management-class/)
   - Cost: Varies by course length; view on enrollment page. [americanhealthtraining](https://www.americanhealthtraining.com/online-anger-management-class/)

5. **AngerMasters – Court-Approved Anger Management Classes**

   - Website: https://angermasters.com/court [angermasters](https://angermasters.com/court)
   - Format: Online court-approved classes ranging from 1 to 52 hours/weeks, with instant certificates. [angermasters](https://angermasters.com/court)
   - Cost: Tiered based on hours; details on site. [angermasters](https://angermasters.com/court)

### Live Online and Hybrid Programs

- **AJ Novick Group (Orange County, but via Zoom statewide)** – live instructor-led weekly anger groups. [ajnovickgroup](https://www.ajnovickgroup.com/anger-management/weekly-classes.aspx)
- **Anger Management Institute (What’s Good About Anger)** – Zoom-based individual sessions and structured online courses. [whatsgoodaboutanger](http://www.whatsgoodaboutanger.com)
- **AngerManagementClass.info** – live virtual 6-hour course with counselor plus 1:1 sessions (verify court acceptance): https://angermanagementclass.info [angermanagementclass](https://angermanagementclass.info)

Important: NAMA explicitly warns that strictly self-paced online programs (no live component) are often not sufficient for court-ordered cases, especially DV; many courts agree. [namass](https://www.namass.org)

Key references:  
- Course For Anger (CA page): https://courseforanger.com/states/CA [courseforanger](https://courseforanger.com/states/CA)
- AATPP online course: https://aatpp.com/course-anger-management.php [aatpp](https://aatpp.com/course-anger-management.php)
- AngerMasters: https://angermasters.com/court [angermasters](https://angermasters.com/court)
- NAMA statement on online-only programs: https://www.namass.org [namass](https://www.namass.org)

***

## Section 8: What to Expect in Class

Most anger management classes follow a fairly standard curriculum:

- Education about what anger is, how it shows up in your body, and how it links to thoughts and beliefs. [canr.msu](https://www.canr.msu.edu/alternatives_to_anger)
- Identifying triggers (situations, people, thoughts) and early warning signs.  
- Cognitive-behavioral skills: catching “hot thoughts,” challenging distorted beliefs, and replacing them with more balanced thinking. [angermanagementasb](https://www.angermanagementasb.com/post/what-to-expect-in-court-ordered-anger-management-classes-a-comprehensive-guide)
- DBT-informed skills such as mindfulness, distress tolerance, and emotion regulation for intense feelings. [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/ca/los-angeles?category=anger-management)
- Communication skills: assertiveness, boundary-setting, listening, and conflict de-escalation. [schroedercounseling](https://www.schroedercounseling.com/court-approved-anger-management-classes)

Attendance requirements:  
- Court programs frequently run for 10–52 sessions, once per week; missing classes can delay completion and may be reported to the court. [apathforchange](https://www.apathforchange.org)
- Programs may require you to arrive on time, sign in, and complete homework to get credit. [schroedercounseling](https://www.schroedercounseling.com/court-approved-anger-management-classes)

Homework can include:  
- Tracking anger episodes and triggers.  
- Practicing coping skills (time-outs, breathing, replacement thoughts).  
- Applying new communication strategies at home or work and reporting back. [angermanagementasb](https://www.angermanagementasb.com/post/what-to-expect-in-court-ordered-anger-management-classes-a-comprehensive-guide)

Certificates and documentation:  
- At the end, you receive a certificate listing your name, course dates, number of hours/weeks completed, and provider credentials or license. [schroedercounseling](https://www.schroedercounseling.com/court-approved-anger-management-classes)
- Some providers send progress or completion reports directly to your attorney, probation, or CPS worker, if you request it. [schroedercounseling](https://www.schroedercounseling.com/court-approved-anger-management-classes)

Key references:  
- RELAX: Alternatives to Anger curriculum: https://www.canr.msu.edu/alternatives_to_anger [canr.msu](https://www.canr.msu.edu/alternatives_to_anger)
- Schroeder Counseling – what court-approved anger classes cover: https://www.schroedercounseling.com/court-approved-anger-management-classes [schroedercounseling](https://www.schroedercounseling.com/court-approved-anger-management-classes)
- DBT skills for anger: https://www.dbtcentersouthbay.com/dbt-skills-for-managing-anger/ [dbtcentersouthbay](https://www.dbtcentersouthbay.com/dbt-skills-for-managing-anger/)
- Anger Management ASB “What to expect in court-ordered classes”: https://www.angermanagementasb.com/post/what-to-expect-in-court-ordered-anger-management-classes-a-comprehensive-guide [angermanagementasb](https://www.angermanagementasb.com/post/what-to-expect-in-court-ordered-anger-management-classes-a-comprehensive-guide)

***

## Section 9: Documentation & Compliance

To stay compliant and avoid setbacks in your case:

- Ask for a written proof of enrollment immediately when you start; bring it to court or send it to your attorney or probation officer. [apathforchange](https://www.apathforchange.org)
- Keep a personal folder with all receipts, attendance slips, progress letters, and your final certificate. [schroedercounseling](https://www.schroedercounseling.com/court-approved-anger-management-classes)
- If you must miss a class, talk to the provider ahead of time; some allow make-up sessions and can document excused absences. [bisclasses](https://www.bisclasses.com/angermanagementprogram.html)

Courts usually want to see on your certificate:  
- Your full legal name and (often) your date of birth or case number.  
- Total hours or number of sessions completed and the date range.  
- Program name, address, and phone number.  
- Signature and credential/license of the facilitator. [saccourt.ca](https://www.saccourt.ca.gov/family/docs/fl-dv-anger-management-list.pdf)

To avoid non-compliance:  
- Never assume any random website will be accepted; confirm first with court/probation.  
- Start early; a 26- or 52-week class takes many months to complete. [apathforchange](https://www.apathforchange.org)
- If your case is in a different state than your residence, confirm whether out-of-state or online programs are accepted. [angermasters](https://angermasters.com/court)

Key references:  
- Sacramento anger program requirements (what must be documented): https://www.saccourt.ca.gov/family/docs/fl-dv-anger-management-list.pdf [saccourt.ca](https://www.saccourt.ca.gov/family/docs/fl-dv-anger-management-list.pdf)
- Schroeder Counseling – completion certificates: https://www.schroedercounseling.com/court-approved-anger-management-classes [schroedercounseling](https://www.schroedercounseling.com/court-approved-anger-management-classes)
- Course For Anger – sample certificate: https://courseforanger.com/states/CA [courseforanger](https://courseforanger.com/states/CA)

***

## Section 10: Common Mistakes & Recommendations

Frequent mistakes include:

- Picking the cheapest online class without checking court acceptance; some certificates are rejected, forcing you to start over. [namass](https://www.namass.org)
- Ignoring format requirements (e.g., doing a self-paced online class when the order requires “in-person group” or “live online”). [namass](https://www.namass.org)
- Not checking for accreditation/licensing or court approval; some providers are legitimate for self-help but not set up for court documentation. [saccourt.ca](https://www.saccourt.ca.gov/family/docs/fl-dv-anger-management-list.pdf)
- Assuming all anger management is the same; domestic violence–related cases often require specialized batterer intervention programs, not just generic anger classes. [file.lacounty](https://file.lacounty.gov/SDSInter/probation/1186203_BIPlistJune2025.pdf)

Recommendations:

- If your case is in California, start by asking your attorney or probation officer if there’s a list (LA, Sacramento, and many Bay Area counties publish standards or provider lists). [copefamilysupport](https://copefamilysupport.org/anger-management-classes/)
- For personal growth, you have more flexibility—consider DBT skills groups, RELAX classes, or private therapy focusing on anger. [canr.msu](https://www.canr.msu.edu/alternatives_to_anger)

Key references:  
- NAMA statement on online-only programs: https://www.namass.org [namass](https://www.namass.org)
- LA Probation provider list: https://www.thecaamp.com/pdf/Los%20Angeles%20County%20Probation%20Anger%20Management%20Providers_20230724_0001%20(1).pdf [thecaamp](https://www.thecaamp.com/pdf/Los%20Angeles%20County%20Probation%20Anger%20Management%20Providers_20230724_0001%20(1).pdf)
- COPE Family Support court-approved classes: https://copefamilysupport.org/anger-management-classes/ [copefamilysupport](https://copefamilysupport.org/anger-management-classes/)

***

## Section 11: Next Steps Checklist

Use this checklist whether you’re doing this for yourself or to satisfy a legal requirement:

1. **Read your court order carefully.** Note the required number of weeks or hours, any specific program type (anger management vs. batterer’s intervention), and any format requirements (in-person, live online, group). [ajnovickgroup](https://www.ajnovickgroup.com/anger-management/weekly-classes.aspx)
2. **Confirm whether your court or probation uses an approved provider list.** Ask your attorney, probation officer, or the court clerk, and look for PDFs on the court or probation website (for example, LA Probation list or Sacramento Family Court list). [saccourt.ca](https://www.saccourt.ca.gov/family/docs/fl-dv-anger-management-list.pdf)
3. **Identify several potential providers.** Use county lists, COPE or other nonprofit sites, and directories like Psychology Today’s anger management filter for your city or county. [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/california?category=anger-management)
4. **Call or email and ask key questions.** Confirm court acceptance, cost and payment policies, language options, schedule, live vs. self-paced format, and what type of documentation they provide. [ajnovickgroup](https://www.ajnovickgroup.com/anger-management/weekly-classes.aspx)
5. **Enroll and confirm start date and plan.** Make sure your timeline fits your court deadlines; if you have a 26- or 52-week requirement, starting early is critical. [apathforchange](https://www.apathforchange.org)
6. **Keep all receipts and certificates together.** Maintain a folder with proof of enrollment, progress reports, and your final certificate so you can quickly provide them to court, probation, CPS, or your lawyer. [schroedercounseling](https://www.schroedercounseling.com/court-approved-anger-management-classes)

Helpful references for planning:  
- Psychology Today CA anger groups: https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/california?category=anger-management [psychologytoday](https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/groups/california?category=anger-management)
- LA County DMH “Get Help Now” page: https://dmh.lacounty.gov/get-help-now/ [dmh.lacounty](https://dmh.lacounty.gov/get-help-now/)
- COPE Family Support anger management: https://copefamilysupport.org/anger-management-classes/ [copefamilysupport](https://copefamilysupport.org/anger-management-classes/)
- Course For Anger (timeline and hours overview): https://courseforanger.com/states/CA [courseforanger](https://courseforanger.com/states/CA)

rows.title: Documents and IDs in California - Complete Recovery and Replacement Guide
rows.content:
SECTION 1: DOCUMENT RECOVERY PRIORITY ROADMAP  
“How to get your life back on paper”

When you’ve lost several key documents, the order you replace them matters because most agencies will ask for one document to issue another. [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/pages/vital-records.aspx)

### Recommended order (for most adults in California and nationwide)

1. Birth certificate  
2. Social Security card  
3. State ID / driver’s license (ideally a Real ID)  
4. Marriage certificate and/or divorce certificate  
5. GED or high school diploma  
6. College transcripts and degrees  
7. Military discharge papers (DD‑214), professional licenses, and immigration documents  

**Why this order matters**

- Birth certificate is your **core** identity and citizenship document; almost every other agency accepts it as primary proof of identity or U.S. birth. [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/CDPH%20Document%20Library/VS111.pdf)
- Social Security card connects your legal name and SSN, which is needed for work, taxes, and many ID applications. [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/faqs/en/questions/KA-02017.html)
- State ID/driver’s license is the main photo ID used for nearly everything in daily life and is required for many in‑person applications. [dmv.ca](https://www.dmv.ca.gov/portal/driver-licenses-identification-cards/replace-your-driver-license-or-identification-dl-id-card/)
- Marriage/divorce certificates prove name changes and marital status, which you may need to update SSA, DMV, or a passport. [lavote](https://www.lavote.gov)
- Education documents and DD‑214 are usually needed for jobs, licensing, or benefits but generally require basic ID first. [archives](https://www.archives.gov/veterans/military-service-records)

If you are unhoused or low‑income in California, you may be able to get a free California birth certificate and free California photo ID if a homeless service provider completes the required fee‑waiver forms with you. [housingca](https://housingca.org/resources/community/individuals/get-ca-birthcert/)

***

SECTION 2: GETTING A BIRTH CERTIFICATE  

### What a birth certificate is and why it matters

A birth certificate is an official vital record showing your full name at birth, date and place of birth, and parent information, issued by a state or local vital records office. [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/pages/vital-records.aspx)
Agencies use certified copies (not photocopies) to prove identity, age, and citizenship for Social Security, passports, Real ID, school, and benefits. [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/CDPH%20Document%20Library/VS111.pdf)

### Finding the right office (nationwide)

- If born in the U.S.:  
  - Your record is held by the **state vital records office** (usually “Department of Health” or “Vital Records”) and often also by the **county** where you were born. [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/pages/vital-records.aspx)
  - To find your state office:  
    - Go to your state’s official .gov site (for example, search: “[Your State] vital records birth certificate”).  
- If born in California:  
  - State level: **California Department of Public Health – Vital Records (CDPH‑VR)**. [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/pages/vital-records.aspx)
  - County level: County **Registrar/Recorder** or **Clerk** where you were born (e.g., Los Angeles County Registrar‑Recorder). [publichealth.lacounty](http://publichealth.lacounty.gov/dca/dcabirth.htm)

Key California links:  
- CDPH Vital Records main page: https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/pages/vital-records.aspx [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/pages/vital-records.aspx)
- CDPH birth certificate instructions (VS 111): https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/CDPH%20Document%20Library/VS111.pdf [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/CDPH%20Document%20Library/VS111.pdf)
- CDPH online ordering via approved vendors: https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/Pages/Obtaining-Certified-Copies-Online.aspx [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/Pages/Obtaining-Certified-Copies-Online.aspx)
- VitalChek California ordering page: https://www.vitalchek.com/v/birth-certificates/california/california-vital-statistics [vitalchek](https://www.vitalchek.com/v/birth-certificates/california/california-vital-statistics)

### When and how to use VitalChek

VitalChek is an authorized online service that contracts with many states and counties to process certified birth, death, marriage, and divorce certificate orders. [vitalchek](https://www.vitalchek.com/v/marriage-records/california/los-angeles-county-registrar-recorder)

Use VitalChek when:  
- You want to order online with a debit/credit card and can wait for mail delivery. [vitalchek](https://www.vitalchek.com/v/birth-certificates/california/california-vital-statistics)
- You are out of state and cannot appear in person at a county office. [vitalchek](https://www.vitalchek.com/v/marriage-records/california/los-angeles-county-registrar-recorder)

What to expect with VitalChek:  
- You choose the state/county and type of record, answer identity questions, and upload ID if required. [vitalchek](https://www.vitalchek.com/v/birth-certificates/california/california-vital-statistics)
- VitalChek charges:  
  - State/County record fee (for California birth: typically around 31 USD at the state level; counties may vary). [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/pages/vital-records-fees.aspx)
  - Vendor processing fee (varies by location). [vitalchek](https://www.vitalchek.com/v/marriage-records/california/los-angeles-county-registrar-recorder)
- Processing time:  
  - State CDPH can take weeks; some counties are faster. CDPH ships by USPS First Class Mail. [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/Pages/Obtaining-Certified-Copies-Online.aspx)

Official links:  
- VitalChek main site: https://www.vitalchek.com [vitalchek](https://www.vitalchek.com/v/birth-certificates/california/california-vital-statistics)

### California-specific steps (especially LA / OC / SD)

You can order a California birth certificate from either CDPH‑VR (state) or your county. [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/CDPH%20Document%20Library/VS111.pdf)

**A. Ordering through CDPH‑VR (mail or online)**

1. Download and complete the Birth Certificate Application (Form VS 111). [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/CDPH%20Document%20Library/VS111.pdf)
2. Decide whether you need:  
   - “Certified Copy” (authorized) – usable as ID proof, requires notarized sworn statement. [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/CDPH%20Document%20Library/VS111.pdf)
   - “Informational Copy” – cannot be used for identity. [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/CDPH%20Document%20Library/VS111.pdf)
3. Prepare your payment:  
   - Current state fee is about 31 USD per certified copy (check CDPH fee page to confirm latest). [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/Pages/Vital-Records-Obtaining-Certified-Copies-of-Birth-Records.aspx)
   - Pay by check or money order to “CDPH – VR.” [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/Pages/Vital-Records-Obtaining-Certified-Copies-of-Birth-Records.aspx)
4. If requesting a certified copy, sign the sworn statement in front of a notary. [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/CDPH%20Document%20Library/VS111.pdf)
5. Mail your application and payment to:  
   - California Department of Public Health – Vital Records, MS 5103, P.O. Box 997410, Sacramento, CA 95899‑7410. [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/Pages/Vital-Records-Obtaining-Certified-Copies-of-Birth-Records.aspx)
6. Wait times: CDPH warns that mailed orders can take several weeks; they mail via USPS First Class and do not track ordinary mail. [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/Pages/Obtaining-Certified-Copies-Online.aspx)

**B. Ordering through your county (often faster)**

Los Angeles County  
- Vital records information: http://publichealth.lacounty.gov/dca/dcabirth.htm [publichealth.lacounty](http://publichealth.lacounty.gov/dca/dcabirth.htm)
- County Registrar‑Recorder site: https://www.lavote.gov [locator.lacounty](https://locator.lacounty.gov/lac/Location/3175505/los-angeles-county-registrar-recordercounty-clerk---beverly-hills)
- Fees: LA County notes that, effective Jan 1, 2026, fees for certified birth records increased pursuant to AB 64; check the site for the current amount (recent notices put it around 34 USD). [lavote](https://www.lavote.gov)
- You can request in person at Registrar‑Recorder offices (Norwalk main office or district locations) or by mail/online via VitalChek. [locator.lacounty](https://locator.lacounty.gov/lac/Location/3175505/los-angeles-county-registrar-recordercounty-clerk---beverly-hills)

Orange County  
- Look up “Orange County CA birth certificate” and go to the official ocgov.com / ochealthinfo.com vital records page; they provide in‑person, mail, and online (often via VitalChek) ordering. [vitalchek](https://www.vitalchek.com/v/birth-certificates/california/california-vital-statistics)

San Diego County  
- Search “San Diego County birth certificate” and go to the official sandiegocounty.gov Assessor/Recorder/County Clerk vital records page. They offer in‑person and mail orders, plus online ordering through approved vendors. [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/pages/vital-records.aspx)

### What information and ID you usually need

Typical birth certificate application asks for: [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/CDPH%20Document%20Library/VS111.pdf)

- Full name at birth  
- Date of birth (or approximate)  
- City and county of birth  
- Parent names (including parent last name before marriage)  
- Your relationship to the person whose record you’re ordering  
- Reason for the request  

For a certified copy (authorized):  
- Notarized sworn statement that you are an authorized person (self, parent, child, legal representative, etc.). [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/CDPH%20Document%20Library/VS111.pdf)
- A copy of a valid government photo ID if ordering through some counties or vendors. [vitalchek](https://www.vitalchek.com/v/marriage-records/california/los-angeles-county-registrar-recorder)

### What if you have no ID in California?

California law allows eligible people experiencing homelessness to get **fee‑exempt** copies of their California birth certificate if they provide an affidavit from a homeless services provider. [ccr.saccounty](https://ccr.saccounty.gov/content/ccr/us/en/no-fee-birth-certificate-for-homeless-persons.html)

Basic steps (California, including LA/OC/SD):

This fee waiver also connects with free California ID cards for unhoused people (see Section 4). [housingca](https://housingca.org/resources/community/individuals/get-ca-birthcert/)

SECTION 3: REPLACING YOUR SOCIAL SECURITY CARD  

### Overview

The Social Security Administration (SSA) issues replacement Social Security cards at **no charge**. [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/faqs/en/questions/KA-02017.html)
You can usually request a replacement online, by starting an application online, or by completing Form SS‑5 and visiting or mailing documents to a local SSA office. [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/forms/ss-5.pdf)

Official SSA links:  
- Replacement card info: https://www.ssa.gov/ssnumber [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/ssnumber/ss5doc.htm)
- Online account (“my Social Security”): https://www.ssa.gov/myaccount [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/myaccount/assets/materials/EN-05-10288.pdf)
- Application for a Social Security Card (Form SS‑5, PDF): https://www.ssa.gov/forms/ss-5.pdf [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/forms/ss-5.pdf)

### Option 1: Online replacement (many Californians)

You may be able to replace your card entirely online if: [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/myaccount/assets/materials/EN-05-10288.pdf)

- You are a U.S. citizen age 18 or older.  
- You have a driver’s license or state ID from a participating state (California participates). [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/myaccount/assets/materials/EN-05-10288.pdf)
- You have a U.S. mailing address.  
- You do not need to change your name, date/place of birth, or gender. [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/faqs/en/questions/KA-02017.html)

Steps:  
1. Create/sign into your **my Social Security** account at https://www.ssa.gov/myaccount. [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/myaccount/assets/materials/EN-05-10288.pdf)
2. Select “Replace your Social Security card” and confirm eligibility questions. [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/myaccount/assets/materials/EN-05-10288.pdf)
3. Enter your identity details (name, SSN, DOB, driver’s license/ID info, address, phone). [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/myaccount/assets/materials/EN-05-10288.pdf)
4. Submit your request; SSA mails the new card, usually within 10–14 business days. [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/faqs/en/questions/KA-02017.html)

### Option 2: Start online, finish at a local office

If you cannot fully complete your request online, SSA allows you to: [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/faqs/en/questions/KA-02017.html)

- Answer screening questions on the SSN web page.  
- Begin your application online and self‑schedule an appointment at a local SSA office. [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/faqs/en/questions/KA-02017.html)
- Bring required original documents in person to finish.  

### Option 3: Paper Form SS‑5 (mail or in person)

Use this if you:  
- Have never had a SSN,  
- Need to correct data, or  
- Cannot use the online tools.  

Steps:  
1. Download and fill out Form SS‑5: https://www.ssa.gov/forms/ss-5.pdf. [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/forms/ss-5.pdf)
2. Gather **original** documents proving identity (and citizenship/immigration status, if needed). [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/ssnumber/ss5doc.htm)
3. Mail or take the form and documents to your local SSA office; find locations at https://www.ssa.gov/locator. [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/faqs/en/questions/KA-02017.html)

Acceptable identity documents (for adults, replacement card):  
- U.S. driver’s license  
- State‑issued ID card  
- U.S. passport  
SSA may accept alternative documents if you cannot get one of these, but they must be current and show your name, identifying information, and a recent photo (for example, employee ID, school ID, health insurance card). [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/ssnumber/ss5doc.htm)

There is **no fee** for a replacement Social Security card. [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/faqs/en/questions/KA-02017.html)

### What if you have no ID yet?

Because SSA generally requires valid ID, many people should first secure a birth certificate and then a state ID. [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/ssnumber/ss5doc.htm)
If you lack ID, you can:  

- Ask SSA which alternate documents they will accept in your situation (for example, school, medical, or employment records). [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/ssnumber/ss5doc.htm)
- Use your birth certificate plus another secondary document (like health insurance card) if accepted. [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/ssnumber/ss5doc.htm)

Key SSA links for this section:  
- Replacement card FAQs: https://www.ssa.gov/faqs/en/questions/KA-02017.html [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/faqs/en/questions/KA-02017.html)
- Identity document requirements: https://www.ssa.gov/ssnumber/ss5doc.htm [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/ssnumber/ss5doc.htm)
- Form SS‑5: https://www.ssa.gov/forms/ss-5.pdf [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/forms/ss-5.pdf)
- my Social Security: https://www.ssa.gov/myaccount [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/myaccount/assets/materials/EN-05-10288.pdf)

SECTION 4: STATE ID / DRIVER’S LICENSE (CALIFORNIA FOCUSED)  

### ID card vs. driver’s license

- **Driver’s license (DL)**: Photo ID that also authorizes you to drive.  
- **ID card**: Photo ID only; no driving privileges.  

In California, both are issued by the Department of Motor Vehicles (DMV). [dmv.ca](https://www.dmv.ca.gov/portal/driver-licenses-identification-cards/replace-your-driver-license-or-identification-dl-id-card/)

Key California DMV link:  
- Replace your DL/ID: https://www.dmv.ca.gov/portal/driver-licenses-identification-cards/replace-your-driver-license-or-identification-dl-id-card/ [dmv.ca](https://www.dmv.ca.gov/portal/driver-licenses-identification-cards/replace-your-driver-license-or-identification-dl-id-card/)

### Replacing a lost California DL or ID

For most Californians, you can request a replacement (duplicate) if your card is lost, stolen, or damaged. [dmv.ca](https://www.dmv.ca.gov/portal/driver-licenses-identification-cards/replace-your-driver-license-or-identification-dl-id-card/)

**Online replacement (driver’s license only)**  
1. Go to the DMV replacement DL page and follow the “Request a replacement DL” link. [dmv.ca](https://www.dmv.ca.gov/portal/driver-licenses-identification-cards/replace-your-driver-license-or-identification-dl-id-card/)
2. Complete the online application (you may need a DMV account). [dmv.ca](https://www.dmv.ca.gov/portal/driver-licenses-identification-cards/replace-your-driver-license-or-identification-dl-id-card/)
3. Pay the replacement fee (varies; typically around the standard replacement DL fee). [dmv.ca](https://www.dmv.ca.gov/portal/driver-licenses-identification-cards/replace-your-driver-license-or-identification-dl-id-card/)
4. Receive your license in the mail, usually in 3–4 weeks; if not received within 60 days, check status. [dmv.ca](https://www.dmv.ca.gov/portal/driver-licenses-identification-cards/replace-your-driver-license-or-identification-dl-id-card/)

**In‑office replacement (DL or ID)**  
1. Complete a new application online before you go, or on a DMV kiosk at the office. [dmv.ca](https://www.dmv.ca.gov/portal/driver-licenses-identification-cards/replace-your-driver-license-or-identification-dl-id-card/)
2. Bring documents if requested, and be prepared to:  
   - Have your photo taken,  
   - Provide thumbprint,  
   - Pay the replacement fee. [dmv.ca](https://www.dmv.ca.gov/portal/driver-licenses-identification-cards/replace-your-driver-license-or-identification-dl-id-card/)
3. DMV mails your card typically within 3–4 weeks. [dmv.ca](https://www.dmv.ca.gov/portal/driver-licenses-identification-cards/replace-your-driver-license-or-identification-dl-id-card/)

### Real ID in California

A Real ID is a federally compliant version of a DL or ID that you will eventually need to board domestic flights and enter many federal facilities.  

To obtain or convert to a Real ID you must provide:  
- Identity document (e.g., U.S. birth certificate, passport).  
- Social Security number.  
- Two documents showing California residency (utility bills, lease, bank statement, etc.).  

California DMV explains Real ID requirements on its Real ID pages (linked from dmv.ca.gov). [abc7](https://abc7.com/post/325000-californians-required-replace-real-ids-due-dmv-software-error-impacting-legal-immigrants/18340822/)

Recent update: California DMV is reissuing approximately 325,000 Real IDs because of a software error and is waiving fees for those affected; notices are mailed to impacted customers. [foxla](https://www.foxla.com/news/california-dmv-real-id-error)

### Fee waivers and free IDs (California, including LA/OC/SD)

California law allows certain people to receive an original or replacement ID card **without paying a fee**, including: [calmatters.digitaldemocracy](https://calmatters.digitaldemocracy.org/bills/ca_201720180ab790)

- Seniors (specific ages/conditions)  
- People experiencing homelessness (verified)  

For people experiencing homelessness:  
1. Go to a homeless service provider or county human services office and ask for help getting a **“No Fee Identification Card Eligibility Verification” (Form DL 933)**. [housingca](https://housingca.org/resources/community/providers/help-someone-get-a-ca-photo-id/)
2. The provider completes DL 933 verifying you meet the federal definition of homelessness. [file.lacounty](http://file.lacounty.gov/SDSInter/dmh/1062827_4e0dfda1-41dc-4303-a03c-e1cbdc606ebb.pdf)
3. Take the completed DL 933 to the DMV office to get a **no‑fee California ID card**. [housingca](https://housingca.org/resources/community/providers/help-someone-get-a-ca-photo-id/)

Housing California offers plain‑language guides on this process:  
- Get a CA photo ID (for individuals): https://housingca.org/resources/community/individuals/get-my-ca-photo-id/ [housingca](https://housingca.org/resources/community/individuals/get-my-ca-photo-id/)
- Help someone get a CA photo ID (for providers): https://housingca.org/resources/community/providers/help-someone-get-a-ca-photo-id/ [housingca](https://housingca.org/resources/community/providers/help-someone-get-a-ca-photo-id/)

### What if you lack supporting documents?

If you lack a birth certificate or SSN card:  
- Use the roadmap order: get a birth certificate (with homeless fee waiver if eligible), then your SSN card or proof, then return to DMV. [housingca](https://housingca.org/resources/community/providers/help-someone-get-ca-birthcert/)
- Ask DMV and/or a homeless service provider what alternative documents may be accepted as proof of identity or residency (for example, shelter letters, benefit letters). [housingca](https://housingca.org/resources/community/individuals/get-my-ca-photo-id/)

Key DMV and ID links:  
- Replace DL/ID: https://www.dmv.ca.gov/portal/driver-licenses-identification-cards/replace-your-driver-license-or-identification-dl-id-card/ [dmv.ca](https://www.dmv.ca.gov/portal/driver-licenses-identification-cards/replace-your-driver-license-or-identification-dl-id-card/)
- Housing California – CA ID guides: https://housingca.org/resources/community/individuals/get-my-ca-photo-id/  and https://housingca.org/resources/community/providers/help-someone-get-a-ca-photo-id/ [housingca](https://housingca.org/resources/community/individuals/get-my-ca-photo-id/)
