SECTION 6: GED / HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMAS  

### GED certificates

There is no single national office for GED records; each state or testing service holds its own records. [ged](https://www.ged.com/blog/how-to-obtain-a-copy-of-your-ged-transcript.html)

National GED portal:  
- https://www.GED.com [ged](https://www.ged.com/life-after-ged.html)

If you earned a GED:  
- Many states (including California) use GED.com for registrations, testing, and transcript requests. [ged](https://www.ged.com/transcripts/california.html)

California GED transcript link:  
- https://www.ged.com/transcripts/california.html [ged](https://www.ged.com/transcripts/california.html)

Typical steps (California / most GED.com states):  
1. Go to the state‑specific transcript page (example for CA above). [ged](https://www.ged.com/transcripts/california.html)
2. Sign in to your GED.com account, or create one using your testing information. [ged](https://www.ged.com/blog/how-to-obtain-a-copy-of-your-ged-transcript.html)
3. Order official transcripts or a diploma replacement; choose mail or electronic delivery. [study](https://study.com/academy/popular/how-to-get-a-new-ged-certificate.html)
4. Pay the fee (commonly around 15–20 USD per transcript/diploma; confirm on site). [study](https://study.com/academy/popular/how-to-get-a-new-ged-certificate.html)
5. Electronic copies may arrive same day; printed diplomas may take up to 2–3 weeks. [study](https://study.com/academy/popular/how-to-get-a-new-ged-certificate.html)

If you don’t remember how you tested or where:  
- The GED.com help article recommends contacting your **state Department of Education** if you cannot locate your record through GED.com. [ged](https://www.ged.com/blog/how-to-obtain-a-copy-of-your-ged-transcript.html)

### High school diplomas and transcripts

For traditional high school diplomas:  
- Contact the high school directly (registrar or counseling office) and ask how to request a transcript or diploma reprint.  
- If the school closed, contact the **school district** or **state Department of Education** to see who holds archived records. [ged](https://www.ged.com/blog/how-to-obtain-a-copy-of-your-ged-transcript.html)

Information you usually need:  
- Full name at time of attendance  
- Date of birth  
- Approximate years attended and graduation year  
- School name and city  
- Photo ID (state ID, license, or birth certificate)  

Key links for this section:  
- GED main site: https://www.ged.com [ged](https://www.ged.com/life-after-ged.html)
- California GED transcripts: https://www.ged.com/transcripts/california.html [ged](https://www.ged.com/transcripts/california.html)

***

SECTION 7: COLLEGE DEGREES & TRANSCRIPTS  

College diplomas and transcripts are issued by your specific college or university, not by a central government office.  

### How to request college transcripts

1. Find your school registrar’s page by searching “[College/University name] registrar transcripts.”  
2. Most registrars use systems like **Parchment**, **National Student Clearinghouse**, or internal portals. [study](https://study.com/academy/popular/how-to-get-a-new-ged-certificate.html)
3. Create an account or log in and submit a request, including:  
   - Your name (include former names),  
   - Student ID or SSN (if requested),  
   - Dates of attendance,  
   - Destination (your address, employer, another school).  
4. Pay transcript fee (often 5–15 USD per copy, plus mailing or electronic delivery fees). [study](https://study.com/academy/popular/how-to-get-a-new-ged-certificate.html)

### Replacing a college diploma

Most colleges allow you to order a replacement diploma:  
- Check the registrar’s or alumni page for “replacement diploma.”  
- Fees may range from about 25–75 USD, plus shipping.  

### If the school closed

If a college closed:  
- Check your state’s Department of Education or licensing agency for “closed school records.”  
- Many closed schools have their student records transferred to a designated custodian or state archive.  

Because this process is school‑specific, always confirm instructions on the official college or state education website.

***

SECTION 8: OPTIONAL DOCUMENTS (DD‑214, PROFESSIONAL LICENSES, TRIBAL & IMMIGRATION DOCUMENTS)  

### Military discharge papers (DD‑214)

The DD‑214 is your official military discharge document; it is critical for VA benefits, job applications, and some licenses. [dd214](https://www.dd214.com/dd214_faq)

Primary sources:  
- National Archives – Military Service Records (NPRC): https://www.archives.gov/veterans/military-service-records [archives](https://www.archives.gov/veterans/military-service-records)
- eVetRecs online request system: https://vetrecs.archives.gov/s/ [vetrecs.archives](https://vetrecs.archives.gov/s/)
- VA DD‑214 info page: https://www.va.gov/records/get-military-service-records/ [va](https://www.va.gov/records/get-military-service-records/)

Key points:  
- Veterans and next‑of‑kin can request DD‑214s at **no cost** in most cases. [dd214](https://www.dd214.com/dd214_faq)
- You can request records online using eVetRecs, then print, sign, and mail or fax a signature page, or use Standard Form SF‑180 by mail. [blog.dd214direct](https://blog.dd214direct.com/i-need-a-copy-of-my-dd214-what-do-i-do-now)

Basic steps via eVetRecs:  
1. Go to https://vetrecs.archives.gov/s/ and select “Make a new request.” [vetrecs.archives](https://vetrecs.archives.gov/s/)
2. Answer the online questions about your branch, dates of service, and reason for request. [archives](https://www.archives.gov/veterans/military-service-records)
3. Print, sign, and date the signature page, then mail or fax it to the address given, or follow the online authentication instructions. [blog.dd214direct](https://blog.dd214direct.com/i-need-a-copy-of-my-dd214-what-do-i-do-now)
4. Wait for mailed copies; processing time depends on backlog, but emergency options exist (for example, for burial or urgent medical needs). [va](https://www.va.gov/records/get-military-service-records/)

### Professional licenses (California example: nurses, contractors, etc.)

- Each profession has its own licensing board (e.g., California Board of Registered Nursing, Contractors State License Board).  
- To replace a license card or print verification, go to the board’s official website (always .gov or .ca.gov) and look for “duplicate license” or “license verification.”  

You will usually need:  
- License number or personal info,  
- Proof of identity,  
- A fee (commonly 10–30 USD).  

### Tribal ID

- Tribal identification cards are issued by your federally recognized tribe.  
- Contact your tribe’s enrollment or membership office for replacement procedures and fees.  
- Some tribes require you to submit a copy of a state ID or birth certificate plus an application and fee.  

### Immigration documents (USCIS)

Common replacement forms:  
- **Permanent Resident Card (Green Card)** – Form I‑90, Application to Replace Permanent Resident Card.  
- **Employment Authorization Document (EAD/work permit)** – Form I‑765, Application for Employment Authorization (replacement option for lost/stolen). [citizenpath](https://citizenpath.com/form-i-765-guide/lost-ead-replacement/)

Key links:  
- USCIS forms: https://www.uscis.gov/forms [citizenpath](https://citizenpath.com/form-i-765-guide/lost-ead-replacement/)
- I‑90 info and filing: https://www.uscis.gov/i-90 [citizenpath](https://citizenpath.com/form-i-765-guide/lost-ead-replacement/)
- I‑765 info: https://www.uscis.gov/i-765 [manifestlaw](https://manifestlaw.com/blog/form-i-765/)

Typical process:  
1. Create a USCIS online account (optional but strongly recommended).  
2. Select and complete the appropriate form, choosing “replacement” if the card was lost, stolen, or destroyed. [citizenpath](https://citizenpath.com/form-i-765-guide/lost-ead-replacement/)
3. Upload supporting documents (proof of identity, immigration status) and pay filing fees unless eligible for a fee waiver (Form I‑912). [citizenpath](https://citizenpath.com/form-i-765-guide/lost-ead-replacement/)
4. USCIS sends a receipt; processing can take several months, depending on the form and category. [manifestlaw](https://manifestlaw.com/blog/form-i-765/)

***

SECTION 9: FREE OR LOW-COST HELP  

### Fee waivers and free copies

- **SSA**: Replacement Social Security cards are always free. [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/faqs/en/questions/KA-02017.html)
- **California birth certificates for unhoused people**: Fee‑exempt for eligible homeless persons with an affidavit from a homeless service provider. [ccr.saccounty](https://ccr.saccounty.gov/content/ccr/us/en/no-fee-birth-certificate-for-homeless-persons.html)
- **California ID cards for unhoused people**: No‑fee ID cards with completed DL 933 verification form from a homeless service provider. [file.lacounty](http://file.lacounty.gov/SDSInter/dmh/1062827_4e0dfda1-41dc-4303-a03c-e1cbdc606ebb.pdf)
- Some vital records offices offer reduced or waived fees after disasters or for low‑income individuals; check your state/county website, especially in fire or flood recovery pages (California example: “Marriage certificates 2025 Los Angeles Fires”). [ca](https://www.ca.gov/lafires/help-for-you/replace-personal-documents/marriage-certificates/)

### Legal aid and ID recovery support (California focus)

- Call **211** from any phone in California to reach local referrals for shelters, legal aid, and ID recovery help.  
- Many legal aid groups assist with name changes, immigration document issues, and identity theft.  

Examples (you can search by county):  
- Search “Los Angeles legal aid ID replacement” or check LA County Legal Aid Foundation/Neighborhood Legal Services sites.  
- Similar organizations exist in Orange and San Diego Counties.  

### Social services and case management

People who are unhoused, at risk of homelessness, or survivors of disaster can often get help through:  
- County departments of public social services  
- Homeless outreach teams and coordinated entry systems  
- Veterans Resource Centers and VA social workers (for veterans’ documents and DD‑214). [va](https://www.va.gov/records/get-military-service-records/)

These providers can help:  
- Complete homeless affidavits and DMV form DL 933. [housingca](https://housingca.org/resources/community/providers/help-someone-get-a-ca-photo-id/)
- Navigate SSA, DHS, and DMV visits.  
- Pay or waive fees when possible via emergency funds.

Key low‑cost help links:  
- Housing California birth certificate/ID guides: https://housingca.org/resources/community/individuals/get-ca-birthcert/ and https://housingca.org/resources/community/individuals/get-my-ca-photo-id/ [housingca](https://housingca.org/resources/community/individuals/get-my-ca-photo-id/)

***

SECTION 10: COMMON PROBLEMS & WORKAROUNDS  

### 1. No ID at all

If you truly have zero photo ID, start with:  

1. **Birth certificate** – use homeless fee‑waiver in CA if eligible. [ccr.saccounty](https://ccr.saccounty.gov/content/ccr/us/en/no-fee-birth-certificate-for-homeless-persons.html)
2. Use birth certificate to help get Social Security card (SSA will accept it plus possibly other non‑photo records). [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/forms/ss-5.pdf)
3. Use birth certificate + SSN proof + homeless verification (if applicable) to get free CA ID card. [file.lacounty](http://file.lacounty.gov/SDSInter/dmh/1062827_4e0dfda1-41dc-4303-a03c-e1cbdc606ebb.pdf)

Service providers (shelters, outreach workers) can be crucial in verifying identity and homelessness status. [housingca](https://housingca.org/resources/community/individuals/get-ca-birthcert/)

### 2. Name discrepancies and name changes

- If your name changed due to marriage, divorce, or court order, you will often need a **marriage certificate**, **divorce decree**, or **court order** to update SSA, DMV, and other records. [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/PSB/Pages/BirthDeathMarriageCertificates.aspx)
- SSA lets you correct or update your name and other details when applying for a replacement card; you will need proof of the legal name change. [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/ssnumber/ss5doc.htm)
- If your birth certificate, SSA record, and ID show different names, start by correcting SSA and then updating DMV to match. [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/ssnumber/ss5doc.htm)

### 3. Missing or unknown parental information

Birth certificate applications may ask for parent names; if you are unsure: [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/CDPH%20Document%20Library/VS111.pdf)

- Provide as much as you know (approximate spelling, partial names). [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/CDPH%20Document%20Library/VS111.pdf)
- If the record cannot be found, CDPH may issue a **Certificate of No Public Record**, and you may need to contact the county where you think you were born for help with a manual search. [housingca](https://housingca.org/resources/community/providers/help-someone-get-ca-birthcert/)

### 4. Destroyed records (fires, floods, older military service)

- California has special information pages for replacing personal documents after disasters such as wildfires (example: marriage certificates for LA fires). [ca](https://www.ca.gov/lafires/help-for-you/replace-personal-documents/marriage-certificates/)
- For military records damaged or destroyed (e.g., 1973 NPRC fire), NPRC can sometimes reconstruct records from alternative sources. [usamm](https://www.usamm.com/blogs/news/how-to-get-a-dd214-for-deceased-relative)

### 5. Immigration and deportation status complications

- If you are a non‑citizen and lost your immigration documents (green card, EAD, I‑94), contact USCIS and, if possible, a legal aid/immigration attorney.  
- Use Form I‑90 for green cards and Form I‑765 for EADs; check Form I‑912 for possible fee waivers if you cannot afford filing fees. [manifestlaw](https://manifestlaw.com/blog/form-i-765/)

***

SECTION 11: CHECKLISTS & SAMPLE LANGUAGE  

### Quick checklists (California‑oriented)

**Birth certificate (California):**  
- Completed VS 111 form. [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/CDPH%20Document%20Library/VS111.pdf)
- Notarized sworn statement (if requesting certified copy). [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/CDPH%20Document%20Library/VS111.pdf)
- Check/money order to “CDPH – VR” or county recorder (correct amount). [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/pages/vital-records-fees.aspx)
- Homeless affidavit if applying for fee‑exempt copy. [ccr.saccounty](https://ccr.saccounty.gov/content/ccr/us/en/no-fee-birth-certificate-for-homeless-persons.html)

**SSA replacement card:**  
- Online: my Social Security account, CA DL/ID. [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/myaccount/assets/materials/EN-05-10288.pdf)
- In person/mail: Completed Form SS‑5, original ID document, birth certificate if born outside U.S. or to show age/citizenship. [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/forms/ss-5.pdf)

**California ID / DL replacement:**  
- Completed online application or DMV form. [dmv.ca](https://www.dmv.ca.gov/portal/driver-licenses-identification-cards/replace-your-driver-license-or-identification-dl-id-card/)
- Proof of identity and California residency (for Real ID or initial issuance). [dmv.ca](https://www.dmv.ca.gov/portal/driver-licenses-identification-cards/replace-your-driver-license-or-identification-dl-id-card/)
- DL 933 no‑fee verification form if unhoused and seeking free ID. [file.lacounty](http://file.lacounty.gov/SDSInter/dmh/1062827_4e0dfda1-41dc-4303-a03c-e1cbdc606ebb.pdf)

**Marriage certificate (LA/OC/SD):**  
- Names of both spouses, date and county of marriage. [lavote](https://www.lavote.gov/home/recorder/marriage-records/marriage-records-request/inperson-request)
- Application form (county‑specific). [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/PSB/Pages/BirthDeathMarriageCertificates.aspx)
- Payment (check fee schedule). [lavote](https://www.lavote.gov)

**GED/High school/College:**  
- Name at time of attendance, DOB, school name and city, years attended. [ged](https://www.ged.com/blog/how-to-obtain-a-copy-of-your-ged-transcript.html)
- Photo ID (or birth certificate + other documents if no ID yet). [ged](https://www.ged.com/blog/how-to-obtain-a-copy-of-your-ged-transcript.html)

**DD‑214:**  
- Full name, SSN or service number, branch, approximate service dates. [vetrecs.archives](https://vetrecs.archives.gov/s/)

### Sample phone scripts

When calling a county vital records office (example for LA County birth certificate):  

> “Hello, my name is [Name]. I was born in [Year] in Los Angeles County, and I need a certified copy of my birth certificate. I’m calling to ask: What is the current fee, what forms do I need, and can I apply by mail or in person? I am also [experiencing homelessness / low‑income] and want to ask if there is a fee waiver available for my situation.”

When calling SSA for ID issues:  

> “Hi, I lost my Social Security card and I don’t have a current driver’s license or state ID. I do have [birth certificate/other documents]. What documents will you accept to prove my identity, and how should I submit them to apply for a replacement card?”

When contacting a GED or high school registrar:  

> “Hello, my name is [Name]. I completed my [GED / high school diploma] at [School or program name] around [Year]. I lost my original diploma and transcripts. Can you tell me how to request an official transcript or a replacement diploma, what the fee is, and what identification you require?”

When calling the National Archives for DD‑214 help:  

> “Hello, I am a veteran and I need a copy of my DD‑214. I started a request online through eVetRecs but I don’t have a printer. Can you explain how I can submit the required signature and what my options are for getting my record as quickly as possible?”

***

SECTION 12: TIMELINE EXPECTATIONS & FOLLOW‑UP  

Typical timelines (these are general ranges; always check current estimates on each site):  

- California birth certificate (state CDPH): Several weeks or longer by mail, depending on volume. [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/Pages/Obtaining-Certified-Copies-Online.aspx)
- California birth certificate (county LA/OC/SD): Sometimes same day in person, or 1–3 weeks by mail. [publichealth.lacounty](http://publichealth.lacounty.gov/dca/dcabirth.htm)
- SSA replacement card: Often 10–14 business days after SSA accepts your application. [ssa](https://www.ssa.gov/myaccount/assets/materials/EN-05-10288.pdf)
- California DL/ID replacement: 3–4 weeks by mail; contact DMV if not received within 60 days. [dmv.ca](https://www.dmv.ca.gov/portal/driver-licenses-identification-cards/replace-your-driver-license-or-identification-dl-id-card/)
- Marriage certificate (LA County via VitalChek): Processing plus mailing time (often 1–3 weeks, but can vary). [vitalchek](https://www.vitalchek.com/v/marriage-records/california/los-angeles-county-registrar-recorder)
- GED/college transcripts: Electronic delivery often same day, paper copies 1–3 weeks plus mailing. [ged](https://www.ged.com/transcripts/california.html)
- DD‑214: Timelines vary; routine requests can take weeks, but emergency requests (for burial or urgent needs) may be expedited. [va](https://www.va.gov/records/get-military-service-records/)

If it takes longer than expected:  
- Use tracking tools where available (e.g., eVetRecs status page, VitalChek order tracking, SSA online account). [vetrecs.archives](https://vetrecs.archives.gov/s/)
- Call the issuing office with your order number or case number.  
- For mail lost by USPS, some agencies require you to submit a new application and fee; CDPH, for example, is not responsible for lost mail and does not refund after an order is accepted. [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/pages/vital-records.aspx)

By following the priority roadmap—starting with birth certificate, then Social Security card, then California ID or driver’s license—you can steadily rebuild the documents needed to restore access to work, housing, benefits, and education in Los Angeles, Orange County, San Diego, and across the United States. [cdph.ca](https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/CHSI/pages/vital-records.aspx)

rows.title: Women's Damascus Road Recovery Program - Union Rescue Mission Guide
rows.content:
Women’s Damascus Road Recovery Program (Hope Gardens)

Damascus Road is a one-year, faith-based residential recovery program for single women, located at URM’s Hope Gardens Family Center in the mountains above Sylmar, away from the concentrated trauma of Skid Row.​
Program Overview

Damascus Road is designed for women seeking recovery from addiction, trauma, and life instability. The program has four phases over about 12 months:​

    Stabilization & Detox (Phase 1 – about 2 months).

    Trauma & Healing Work (Phase 2 – about 4 months).

    Life Skills & Job Readiness (Phase 3 – about 3 months).

    Employment & Permanent Housing (Phase 4 – about 3 months).​

Who This Is For

This program is for:

    Single adult women experiencing homelessness or near-homelessness who want long-term, structured recovery.​

    Women with substance use disorders or destructive behavioral patterns rooted in pain and trauma.​

    Women ready to live in a faith-based, residential community environment for approximately one year.​

Women with young children may be housed at Hope Gardens but Damascus Road, as described, is specifically a life-transformation program for single women; staff can explain family program options at Hope Gardens.​​
Location, Length, and Faith-Based Components

    Location: Hope Gardens Family Center, a URM campus in the hills near Sylmar, CA.​​

    Length: Approximately 12 months, divided into four phases (2 + 4 + 3 + 3 months).​

    Faith-based elements: Regular chapel services, prayer, Celebrate Recovery groups, and Christian discipleship are integrated throughout the program.​

Participation in spiritual activities is a core part of the program’s design, though women from different or no faith backgrounds can discuss expectations with staff before enrolling.​
Phase 1: Stabilization & Detox

Focus

    Initial stabilization from street life, crisis, and substance use.​

    First steps in recovery, including detoxification and establishing safety.​

What happens

    First approximately 14 days focused on detox, monitoring, and basic stabilization (in coordination with medical providers where needed).​

    Orientation to program rules, schedule, and community expectations.​

    Start attending weekly group meetings, chapel services, and Celebrate Recovery groups.​

Goals

    Achieve physical safety and a stable daily routine.

    Begin to build trust with staff and peers.

    Prepare mentally and physically for deeper trauma and recovery work.​

Phase 2: Trauma & Healing Work

Focus

    Transformation through deeper recovery, healing, and self-discovery.​

    Addressing root causes of addiction and destructive patterns, often tied to trauma and domestic violence.​

Core elements

    Trauma-informed groups and counseling to process past abuse, loss, and violence.​

    Classes and groups in anger management, parenting, domestic violence healing, addiction and relapse prevention, and boundaries.​

    Ongoing Celebrate Recovery participation and chapel services.​

Trauma-informed care

    Staff and clinicians understand trauma as central to many guests’ histories and design care that prioritizes safety, choice, collaboration, and empowerment.​

    Sessions are structured to avoid re-traumatization and to help women regain a sense of control and voice.​

Phase 3: Life Skills & Job Readiness

Focus

    Developing practical life skills, financial management, and job readiness while continuing recovery work.​

Key components

    Continuation of Phase 2 classes (healing, relapse prevention, boundaries) plus:​

        Financial management and budgeting.

        Resume building and job readiness skills.

        Work therapy assignments within URM or related settings.​

Work therapy model

    Work assignments help women practice responsibility, punctuality, teamwork, and communication in a supportive environment.​

    Tasks may include administrative support, kitchen or hospitality work, or other roles depending on ability and program needs.​

Phase 4: Employment & Permanent Housing

Focus

    Transitioning from recovery to stable employment and permanent housing.​

Core elements

    Continuation of classes from Phases 2 and 3 as needed.​

    Active job search: applications, interviews, and coordinated support with employment partners.​

    Housing search and transition planning, including applications for permanent supportive housing or independent rentals.​

    Setting and pursuing education goals (e.g., GED completion, college or trade school entry).​

Housing transition strategy

    Case managers work with each woman to develop a realistic housing plan based on her income, benefits, and support network.​

    Plans may include shared housing, supportive housing, or independent apartments; savings and budgeting are central to this phase.​

    Timelines vary; some women obtain employment and housing within the final three months, while others may need extended support or step-down programs.​

Celebrate Recovery, Parenting, and Domestic Violence Healing

Celebrate Recovery

    A Christ-centered 12-step program that addresses hurts, habits, and hang-ups.​

    Used as a structured framework for working through addiction, codependency, and past pain.​

Parenting classes

    Classes on child development, positive discipline, and rebuilding trust with children.​

    Support around reunification where appropriate, in coordination with child welfare, courts, and family members.​

Domestic violence healing

    Education on cycles of abuse, safety planning, and healthy relationships.​

    Trauma-focused groups that help women recognize and avoid abusive dynamics in the future.​

Eligibility, Application Process, and Waiting List

Eligibility

    Adult women, typically 18+, experiencing homelessness or unstable housing and seeking substance use recovery.​

    Willingness to commit to a one-year, residential, faith-based program.​

    Ability to live in a communal environment and follow program rules.​

Some medical or psychiatric needs may require coordination with external providers or may indicate that a different level of care is more appropriate; URM staff will screen and refer accordingly.​

How to apply

    If you are currently at URM Downtown, speak with your case manager or chaplain and ask about “Damascus Road at Hope Gardens.”​

    If you are not at URM, call URM’s main line at (213) 347-6300 and ask for information about the women’s recovery program at Hope Gardens.​

    Staff will typically conduct a phone or in-person pre-screen, then schedule a more detailed intake if you appear eligible.​

Waiting list expectations

    Because space is limited, there may be a waiting list; wait times can range from a few days to several weeks or more depending on demand.​

    During the wait, you may stay in URM emergency shelter or be referred to another safe location, where available.​

    Staying in contact with intake staff and keeping your phone/email updated is important so they can reach you when a bed opens.​

What To Expect Day to Day

    Structured daily schedule including classes, groups, chapels, chores, and personal reflection time.​

    Curfews and rules about substance use, relationships, and conduct that support a safe environment.​

    Regular check-ins with counselors, case managers, and possibly Pepperdine mental health providers via URM partnerships.​

    A supportive community of women working through similar challenges, with staff who combine professional training and faith-based care.​

rows.title: Union Rescue Mission Learning Centers - Education and Job Skills Guide
rows.content:
Union Rescue Mission Learning Center & Education Programs

URM’s Learning Centers help adults experiencing homelessness build education and job skills needed for stable employment and long-term independence. Programs are tailored and flexible, recognizing that many learners are balancing recovery, shelter requirements, and health challenges.​
Overview of Education Services

URM Learning Centers, supported by credentialed LAUSD instructors and qualified educators, offer:​

    Adult Basic Education (reading, writing, math).

    GED/HiSET preparation.

    English as a Second Language (ESL).

    Computer literacy and digital skills.

    Financial stewardship and budgeting.

    Vocational training connections and certifications.

    Credit recovery and secondary education planning.

    Education planning and career goal setting.​

Who This Is For

Education services are designed for:

    URM guests in emergency shelter (S.E.S., F.E.S.) who want to improve skills to exit homelessness.​

    Participants in Emmaus and Damascus Road recovery programs seeking to rebuild careers or start new ones.​

    Adults who did not finish high school, need to improve English, or want to change careers.​

Most programs have no tuition cost for URM guests; availability of specific courses can depend on staffing and partnerships.​
Adult Basic Education & GED/HiSET Prep

Adult Basic Education (ABE)

    Focuses on reading, writing, and math at foundational levels.​

    Helps learners who may have been out of school for years regain confidence and basic academic skills.​

GED/HiSET preparation

    Structured preparation for high school equivalency exams (GED or HiSET), including practice tests and targeted instruction.​

    Learning Center staff work with LAUSD instructors and adaptive learning software to create individualized study plans.​

Typical pathway

    Initial assessment to determine current reading and math level (e.g., TABE or similar tests).​

    Assignment to classes or tutoring sessions at your level.​

    Gradual progression toward test readiness, followed by referral to official testing centers or partner schools.​

ESL and Computer Literacy

English as a Second Language (ESL)

    Classes for adults whose first language is not English, focusing on conversation, reading, and everyday survival language.​

    Integrated with life skills (e.g., filling out forms, speaking with employers, understanding instructions).​

Computer literacy

    Basic computer skills: using a mouse and keyboard, navigating the internet, email, and online forms.​

    Job-search skills: resume creation, online applications, setting up email, and accessing government benefit portals.​

    Some classes may cover productivity software, online safety, and video interviews.​

Financial Stewardship & Vocational Training

Financial stewardship

    Classes on budgeting, banking, saving, and credit.​

    Support aligns with S.E.S. and F.E.S. program expectations to save monthly and manage program fees.​

    Topics may include opening accounts, avoiding predatory lending, and planning for rent and utilities.​

Vocational training and trade school connections

    URM connects guests with trade schools and vocational programs (e.g., construction, culinary, caregiving, commercial driving) through partner organizations.​

    Learning Center staff help with applications, placement tests, and financial aid forms when possible.​

    Past partners have included LA Mission College, Five Keys Schools and Programs, and other workforce organizations.​

Credit Recovery & Education Planning

Credit recovery

    For adults who were close to finishing high school, URM and partner schools can help identify missing credits and pathways to completion.​

    In some cases, guests can enroll with charter or adult high school programs that specialize in credit recovery.​

Education planning

    One-on-one support to map out education goals: GED, trade license, community college, or certification.​

    Assistance with applications, transcripts, and referrals to programs that fit your pace and recovery stage.​

How Guests Enroll

Step 1: Express interest

    Talk to your case manager, program staff, or the Learning Center directly.​

    If you are in Emmaus, Damascus Road, S.E.S., or F.E.S., education is often built into your case plan.​

Step 2: Assessment

    You may take placement tests (e.g., TABE) to determine reading and math levels.​

    Staff discuss your goals and available time (considering work therapy, appointments, and childcare).​

Step 3: Build a learning plan

    Together you and the educator design a schedule: classes, tutoring, computer lab time, and homework expectations.​

    Plans are flexible so they can be adjusted if your health or program schedule shifts.​

Step 4: Start classes

    You attend classes on-site in the Learning Center, often located within the URM building.​

    You may also be connected to online or external classes through partner schools.​

Typical Weekly Schedule

While exact schedules vary, a realistic weekly pattern for a program participant might include:​

    2–4 sessions per week of academic classes (ABE, GED/HiSET, or ESL).

    1–2 sessions per week of computer lab focused on job readiness.

    1 financial stewardship or life-skills workshop each week.

    1–2 hours of individual tutoring or homework support.

    Integration with work therapy, recovery groups, and appointments.

Guests in full-time recovery programs may spend more time in classes, while those working or in S.E.S./F.E.S. may attend fewer but targeted sessions.​
Certification Pathways & Realistic Outcomes

Possible certifications

    High school equivalency (GED/HiSET) certificate.​

    Specialized vocational certificates from partner programs (e.g., ServSafe for food handling, basic computer certificates, industry-specific trainings).​

    Documented course completion or training hours that can support job applications.​

Realistic timelines

    Basic literacy improvements: noticeable gains may occur over 2–6 months with steady attendance.​

    GED/HiSET: many guests need 6–12 months to prepare and pass all sections, depending on starting level and life disruptions.​

    Vocational certificates: some short programs last 4–12 weeks; longer or licensed programs can require many months of training.​

Realistic outcomes

    Improved confidence, ability to complete job applications, and readiness for interviews.​

    Better access to higher-paying jobs due to GED or training credentials.​

    Stronger financial habits and a clearer plan for housing and employment.​

What To Expect as a Student

    A supportive environment that understands relapse, mental health struggles, and life disruption are common; staff aim to encourage, not shame.​

    Flexible pacing; if you miss classes due to appointments or crises, you can often re-engage without starting from zero.​

    Use of adaptive learning software so you can work at your own level and speed.​

    Collaboration between education staff, case managers, and therapists to align your education goals with recovery and housing plans.​

How To Apply or Get Started

    If you are already at URM, ask for the Learning Center or talk to your case manager.​

    If you are not yet staying at URM, start by entering emergency services or a transitional/recovery program; education services are primarily for guests.​

    For questions, URM lists a Learning Center contact phone (e.g., Learning Center Director at 213-316-2752; confirm with URM’s current directory as numbers can change over time).​

More information:

    URM Support Services – Learning Centers: https://urm.org/support-services (navigate to Learning Centers section).

rows.title: Union Rescue Mission Medical and Dental Services - Access Guide
rows.content:
Union Rescue Mission Medical, Dental, Mental Health & Legal Clinics

Union Rescue Mission partners with major institutions—including UCLA Health, USC, and Pepperdine University—to provide free or low-barrier medical, dental, mental health, and legal services on or connected to the URM campus.​​
Overview of Partner Clinics

At or through URM, guests can access:

    UCLA Homeless Healthcare Collaborative (mobile and street-based medical care).​​

    USC Dental Clinic, providing comprehensive dental care including pediatric dentistry.​

    Pepperdine Mental Health Clinic (Jerry Butler Clinic) for trauma and substance-use-related psychological care.​

    Pepperdine Legal Aid Clinic for civil legal help, especially family law, tickets, and records issues.
    ​

These clinics focus on people experiencing homelessness or extreme poverty, and services are generally free to URM guests.
​
Who This Is For

These clinics are particularly for:

    Current URM emergency guests (using shelter or meals).​

    Participants in URM recovery and transitional programs (Emmaus, Damascus Road, S.E.S., F.E.S.).​

    People experiencing homelessness in Skid Row referred by URM or partner shelters.​​

Some services may also be available to neighboring unhoused community members if capacity allows, especially through mobile outreach like UCLA’s Homeless Healthcare Collaborative.​
UCLA Homeless Healthcare Collaborative at URM

The UCLA Homeless Healthcare Collaborative (HHC) offers mobile primary and urgent care services to people experiencing homelessness across Los Angeles, including URM and Hope Gardens.
​

What services are provided

    Primary care (checkups, chronic disease management for conditions like diabetes, hypertension, asthma).

    Urgent care for minor injuries, infections, wound care, respiratory illnesses, and similar issues.

    Vaccinations, basic lab work, medication refills, and health education, depending on mobile clinic capabilities.​

    Trauma-informed care that considers the impact of long-term homelessness and trauma on health.

Who qualifies

    People experiencing homelessness in Los Angeles, including URM guests and nearby residents of Skid Row.​

    No insurance is required; lack of ID should not prevent care.​

Cost

    Services are provided free of charge to patients.​

How to access

    At URM, ask front desk or case management when the UCLA HHC team is onsite or doing street outreach nearby.​​

    Clinics may take place inside URM’s clinic space or from a mobile van parked near the facility.​

    You may be seen on a first-come, first-served basis or given a same-day time slot, depending on the day’s schedule.​

Required documents

    Typically none are strictly required; if you have ID and medical cards, bring them, but they are not a barrier to care.​

Referral process and timeline

    Walk-in when the team is present or get a referral from URM staff.​​

    Many patients can be seen same day when the clinic is onsite; follow-up visits may be set for the next visit day at URM or another HHC location.​

    For specialty care (e.g., surgery, complex diagnostics), UCLA or other hospital systems may arrange referrals; timelines vary from a few days to several weeks.

Partner link

    UCLA Homeless Healthcare Collaborative:
    https://www.uclahealth.org/programs/hhc
    ​

USC Dental Clinic at Union Rescue Mission

USC’s School of Dentistry operates a clinic at URM providing free dental care, including one of the only pediatric dental services on Skid Row.​

What services are provided

    Comprehensive dental exams and cleanings.​

    Fillings, extractions, and treatment of infections as capacity allows.​

    Dentures or partial dentures in selected cases, subject to program resources.​

    Pediatric dental care for children staying at URM or in nearby shelters.​

Who qualifies

    Adults and children experiencing homelessness or living in poverty in downtown Los Angeles.​

    Priority is typically given to URM guests and program participants, especially families and those with significant pain or urgent need.​

Cost

    Services are generally provided free of charge to patients.​

How to access

    Ask URM staff or front desk to be placed on the dental clinic list or for the next clinic day.​

    You may need a brief screening or referral through URM’s support services to prioritize your case.​

Required documents

    Usually minimal; if you have ID, bring it, but lack of documentation should not stop emergency pain treatment.​

Referral process and timeline

    For non-urgent care, expect to wait days to weeks depending on demand and clinic schedule, as USC faculty, residents, and students rotate through.​

    Urgent cases (severe pain, infection, swelling) may be prioritized more quickly.​

    URM or USC may refer you to other dental facilities if specialized procedures are needed and capacity is limited.​

Partner link

    Herman Ostrow School of Dentistry of USC (community and mobile clinics overview): https://dentistry.usc.edu (navigate to community programs; URM clinic details are often listed under community/clinical outreach).​

Pepperdine Mental Health Clinic (Jerry Butler Clinic)

The Jerry Butler Pepperdine Mental Health Clinic, located at URM, provides psychological services to guests, with a strong focus on trauma, substance use recovery, and long-term mental health.​

What services are provided

    Individual therapy and counseling (e.g., depression, anxiety, PTSD, grief, and substance-related issues).​

    Group therapy focused on trauma recovery, relapse prevention, emotional regulation, and relationships.​

    Psychological support integrated into URM’s recovery programs, especially the Emmaus men’s program and Damascus Road for women.​

    Coordination with medical providers for medication evaluation via external psychiatrists or clinics when needed.​

Who qualifies

    Primarily URM program participants (Emmaus, Damascus Road, S.E.S., F.E.S.), as well as some emergency guests depending on capacity.​

    People experiencing homelessness or recent homelessness who need therapy to support recovery.​

Cost

    Services are provided to URM guests without out-of-pocket cost, as the clinic functions as a training and service site for Pepperdine University’s psychology and counseling programs.​

How to access

    Tell your URM case manager or program staff you want mental health services.​

    Program participants may be automatically referred for assessment as part of Emmaus or Damascus Road.​

Required documents

    Normally minimal; your URM program file and intake forms serve as the base record.​

    You may be asked to sign consent forms and a confidentiality agreement for therapy services.​

Referral process and timeline

    Referral usually goes through URM staff to Pepperdine clinicians; you may have an intake appointment within days to a few weeks depending on caseload.​

    Emmaus and Damascus Road participants often receive more structured, ongoing therapy as part of their program timeline.​

Partner link

    Pepperdine Graduate School of Education and Psychology – community clinics overview: https://gsep.pepperdine.edu (search “Union Rescue Mission” or “Jerry Butler Clinic”).​

Pepperdine Legal Aid Clinic at URM

The Pepperdine Legal Aid Clinic serves teens and adults overcoming homelessness and poverty, with a full clinic located inside URM.
​

What services are provided

    Interviewing, advising, and counseling for civil legal issues.​​

    Assistance resolving tickets and warrants (e.g., minor infractions, some misdemeanors).​

    Help preparing court paperwork in child support, custody, and visitation cases.​​

    Record-cleaning support such as expungements and dismissals of some criminal convictions, when permitted by law.​

    Guidance on government benefits (e.g., SSI, SSDI, CalFresh, General Relief) and income tax controversies.​

    Preparation and support for Homeless Court, where available.​

Who qualifies

    Unhoused or formerly unhoused adults and youth connected to URM or partner shelters.​​

    People with low income who cannot afford private legal representation, particularly in family law and related civil matters.​​

Cost

    Services are offered free of charge as pro bono legal aid.​​

How to access

    Ask your URM case manager, chaplain, or front desk about the “Pepperdine Legal Aid Clinic” schedule at the Mission.​​

    You may need to attend an intake session or legal clinic time, where staff or student law clerks will review your situation.​

Required documents

    Any court papers, tickets, warrants, child support orders, or prior judgments related to your case.​

    Any ID, Social Security card, or benefits letters you have, to help verify your identity and case history.​

Referral process and timeline

    Initial screening can happen the same day on clinic dates; complex cases may be opened for ongoing representation.​​

    Family law and record-clearing matters can take weeks to many months depending on court schedules; the clinic will explain realistic timelines.​

    If your case is outside the clinic’s scope, they may refer you to other legal aid agencies in Los Angeles.​

Partner link

    Legal Aid Clinic at Union Rescue Mission:
    https://law.pepperdine.edu/experiential-learning/clinical-education/clinics/legal-aid-clinic/
    ​

    Pepperdine/URM Family Law Clinic:
    https://law.pepperdine.edu/experiential-learning/clinical-education/clinics/family-law-clinic/
    ​

What To Expect When Using URM Clinics

    Services are often run by licensed professionals working with supervised students and residents (medicine, dentistry, law, psychology).
    ​

    Appointments may be limited by clinic days and provider availability; you may spend time waiting but can usually access other URM services while on campus.​

    Most services focus on essential, stabilizing care: pain relief, safety, stabilizing health and legal status, and supporting recovery goals.​

    You retain confidentiality protections under health and legal ethics, within the limits staff will explain to you (e.g., mandated reporting).

How To Apply or Get Connected

You typically do not submit an online application; instead, you connect while staying at or visiting URM.

    Start by visiting URM at 545 S. San Pedro St or calling (213) 347-6300.

    Ask the front desk or your case manager for:

        “UCLA medical clinic,”

        “USC dental clinic,”

        “Pepperdine mental health,” or

        “Pepperdine legal aid at Union Rescue Mission.”​

    Bring any relevant documents (medical records, court papers, tickets, medication lists).​

    Expect screening and scheduling based on urgency, with some services available same day and others booked out for future dates.

rows.title: Union Rescue Mission Emergency Services - What You Can Access Today
rows.content:
Union Rescue Mission Emergency Services: What You Can Access Today

Union Rescue Mission’s Downtown Ministry on Skid Row provides walk-in emergency help every day, including meals, shelter, showers, and access to clinics and case management. This article explains what you can use immediately, who qualifies, and how to navigate arrival and intake.​​
Overview of Emergency Services

    3,000 warm meals served three times a day, every day.​​

    Shelter space for 1,300+ men, women, and children without a referral.​​

    Personal care: hot showers, hygiene items, diapers, laundry facilities.​​

    Access to medical, dental, mental health, legal aid, education, and recovery resources onsite or by referral.
    ​

    Location: Union Rescue Mission Downtown Ministry, 545 S. San Pedro St, Los Angeles, CA 90013.

    Phone (main line/intake): (213) 347-6300.​

    Hours: Facility is open 24 hours a day, 7 days a week (programs have specific schedules).

Who This Is For

Emergency Services at URM are designed for people who:

    Are currently unhoused or in unsafe, unstable living conditions (streets, vehicles, encampments, couch-surfing, unsafe motels).​​

    Need immediate access to food, shelter, showers, or basic care and are in the Skid Row / downtown Los Angeles area.​​

    May have untreated medical or mental health needs, substance use issues, or legal barriers but are not yet ready or able to enter a longer-term recovery or transitional program.​

    Include: single men, single women, and families with children; URM is one of the few missions on Skid Row that keeps families together in shelter.

There is no requirement to be sober on arrival, but dangerous or disruptive behavior (violence, weapons, open drug/alcohol use inside) can affect access to services.​​
Meals: What You Can Access Today

URM serves approximately 3,000 warm meals per day, three times daily.​​

What is offered

    Breakfast, lunch, and dinner served onsite in the dining area.
    ​

    Hot, prepared meals with basic nutrition; menus vary and may include protein, starch, vegetables, and beverages.​

    Some meals are available both to overnight guests and walk-in day guests, subject to daily capacity.​​

Who qualifies

    People experiencing homelessness or extreme poverty in the Skid Row area.​​

    Families, single adults, and older youth; there are typically no geographic restrictions.​​

Cost

    Meals are provided free of charge to guests.​​

How to access meals (same day)

    Go to URM Downtown Ministry at 545 S. San Pedro St, LA, CA 90013.​

    Arrive ahead of posted meal times; exact schedules can change, so check at the front desk or call (213) 347-6300 for current meal times.

    Follow staff instructions for meal lines and seating; priority may be given to overnight guests, families, older adults, or those with health needs.​​

Shelter: Beds and Day Rooms

URM offers shelter for more than 1,300 men, women, and children, with no outside referral required.​​

Types of shelter

    Night shelter dorms for single men and women.​​

    Family emergency shelter for parents with children (separate section, more privacy and child-focused support).​

    Day rooms that provide daytime rest, seating, and a safe place off the streets.

Who qualifies

    Adults and families experiencing homelessness who can safely stay in a congregate shelter environment.​​

    Families with minor children seeking to stay together in a single facility.​​

    Some beds and floors may be gender-specific; families are placed together in family areas.​​

How long you can stay

    Emergency night shelter is generally short-term, often night-to-night with sign-ups each day; the exact length depends on space, behavior, and program fit.​​

    Families in Family Emergency Services (F.E.S.) can typically stay at least six months while working with a case manager and following program guidelines.​

    Guests who demonstrate stability and interest in next steps may be invited to apply for longer-term programs such as S.E.S., Emmaus Recovery, or Damascus Road.​

Personal Care Services

URM provides basic personal care to support health, dignity, and safety.​​

Available services

    Hot showers for men, women, and families.​​

    Hygiene supplies (soap, shampoo, toothpaste, toothbrushes, menstrual products) as available.​

    Diapers and infant care supplies for families with babies and toddlers.​

    Laundry facilities and help with washing clothes, subject to schedules and availability.​​

    Access to clean clothing and donated items when available.​​

How to access

    Check in at the front desk to learn the current schedule for showers and laundry.​

    Staff may give you a time slot, wristband, or ticket depending on capacity and gender-specific scheduling.​

    Families with young children or people with mobility issues may be prioritized for limited slots.​

How Intake Works (Emergency Services)

For basic emergency services (meals, day rooms, some personal care), intake can often be same-day and relatively simple. For overnight shelter and program enrollment, more structured intake is used.​​

Basic walk-in intake

    You may be asked for your name and basic identifying information.​​

    If you have an ID, it can help but is not always required for a first meal or initial contact.​​

    Staff may ask brief questions about your situation (safety concerns, medical issues, children with you) to connect you with the right area.​

Overnight shelter intake

    Daily bed sign-up or check-in times (often late afternoon or evening) are posted at the Mission; times can change, so ask at the front desk or call.

    You may need to complete a brief intake form, including name, date of birth, emergency contact if available, and basic health/safety questions.​

    Staff may perform a quick safety check (bags may be searched; weapons, drugs, and alcohol are generally prohibited inside the facility).​​

Program intake (for recovery / transitional)

    If you’re interested in longer-term programs like S.E.S., F.E.S., Emmaus, or Damascus Road, intake includes more detailed assessments and interviews.​

    Intake staff may schedule a separate appointment to talk about your goals, medical needs, income, and any legal or custody issues.​

Who Qualifies for Emergency Services

Generally eligible

    Adults (18+) and families with children experiencing homelessness in Los Angeles.​​

    People sleeping on the streets, in vehicles, in shelters, in encampments, or in unsafe overcrowded housing.​

    Individuals regardless of religious background; URM is faith-based but services are open to all faiths and to those with no faith.​​

Possible limitations

    Severe medical or psychiatric conditions that require hospital-level care may be referred to emergency departments or specialty facilities.

    Individuals with active violent behavior or serious safety concerns may be limited or redirected for everyone’s safety.​​

    Registered sex offenders or people under certain court orders may face restrictions in some shelter areas due to law or policy; staff can explain options.​

What to Bring

Bringing the right items can make intake and your stay smoother, but you can still access basic services even if you have nothing.

Helpful items

    Any photo ID (driver’s license, state ID, consular ID, passport, student ID, or hospital ID) and Social Security card if available.​

    Important documents: benefits letters, discharge papers, court documents, custody orders, or medical information.​

    A small bag with essential clothing and personal items; URM offers some storage for belongings, especially for S.E.S. participants.​

    Medications in original bottles, including prescriptions for chronic conditions (diabetes, blood pressure, mental health medications).​​

What not to bring

    Weapons, illegal drugs, alcohol, or drug paraphernalia.​​

    Large amounts of cash if you can avoid it; consider storing or protecting valuables separately.​

    Bulky items that cannot be stored; storage is limited and prioritized for program participants.​

Step-by-Step Arrival Process

Below is a realistic same-day process for someone arriving at URM for the first time.

    Travel to URM Downtown Ministry

        Go to 545 S. San Pedro St, Los Angeles, CA 90013.​

        Public transit (buses/Metro) and rideshare are available; many people also arrive on foot from nearby Skid Row streets.​

    Check in at the front entrance / security

        Follow directions from security staff; they may ask you to briefly open bags and walk through a screening process for safety.​​

        Let staff know if you are with children, pregnant, elderly, or have a disability so they can guide you appropriately.​

    Speak with front desk / triage staff

        Share what you need today: food, shower, shelter, or help with medical/legal issues.​

        If you’re seeking a bed tonight, ask specifically about “emergency shelter beds” and “family shelter” (if you have children).​

    Complete basic intake information

        Provide your name and any ID you have; staff may ask brief questions about your health and safety.​

        If English is difficult, ask for help; staff and volunteers may speak multiple languages or help find interpretation.​

    Get directions for the day

        Staff will tell you when and where you can eat, whether you can access a shower or laundry that day, and how to sign up for a bed.​​

        If beds are full, ask about wait lists, overflow options, or return times.​

    Access meals and personal care

        Follow signs and staff directions to the dining hall, showers, and other services.​​

        Keep any ticket or wristband they give you; you may need it for meals or entry to certain areas.​

    Ask about next steps

        If you think you may want a longer-term program (recovery or transitional), tell your caseworker or front desk you are interested in S.E.S., F.E.S., Emmaus, or Damascus Road.​

        They can share basic eligibility and let you know when to come back for an intake or orientation.​

How Long You Can Stay

Emergency shelter

    Often night-to-night, subject to daily sign-ups and capacity.​​

    There is no guaranteed long-term stay in emergency beds, but guests who follow rules and work with staff may remain longer while they explore other options.​

Family Emergency Services (F.E.S.)

    Families are typically able to stay at least six months, as long as they participate in case management and follow program expectations.​

Singles Emergency Services Program (S.E.S.)

    S.E.S. is a one-year program for single adults needing more than basic emergency shelter but not a full recovery program; residents stay onsite during this period.​

Recovery programs

    Damascus Road for women is a one-year residential recovery program at Hope Gardens, with four distinct phases.​

    Emmaus Recovery for men includes a 1-month assessment phase, 6–9 months of intensive recovery, and up to 18 months of apprenticeship housing.​

What To Expect Day to Day (Emergency Level)

    Structured meal times with lines and seating; you may wait outside or in day rooms depending on space.

    Curfew for overnight guests; you must return by specified time to keep your bed.​

    Basic rules around behavior, quiet hours, and respect for staff and other guests.​​

    Regular opportunities to connect with caseworkers, chaplains, and program staff if you want to explore next steps.​

    Optional faith-based activities such as chapel services, prayer, and Bible studies; participation may be strongly encouraged in some programs but emergency services remain open regardless of religious belief.​​

How To Apply or Get Started

For emergency services, you generally do not submit a formal application; you arrive and check in.

Same-day steps

    Call URM: (213) 347-6300 to confirm meal times and bed availability.​

    Go to 545 S. San Pedro St, Los Angeles, CA 90013.​

    Tell staff you are new and need emergency shelter, food, or showers.​

If you are coming with children

    Call ahead if possible to ask specifically about Family Emergency Services (F.E.S.) and family beds.​

    Bring any documents related to your children (birth certificates, custody orders, medical records) if you have them; lack of paperwork should not stop you from seeking help.​

Next steps beyond emergency

    Ask for an appointment with a case manager to discuss S.E.S., F.E.S., or a recovery program once you are ready.​

    Case managers will review eligibility, help with required paperwork, and discuss realistic timelines for program entry and housing.​

Contact Information and Links

    Address: Union Rescue Mission Downtown Ministry, 545 S. San Pedro St, Los Angeles, CA 90013.​

    Phone (main / intake): (213) 347-6300.​

    Website – Get Help:
    https://urm.org/get-help/
    ​

    Emergency Services Overview:
    https://urm.org/the-way-home/emergency-services/
    ​

    Downtown Ministry Location Info:
    https://urm.org/locations/union-rescue-mission-downtown-ministry/

rows.title: Union Rescue Mission Transitional Programs - SES and FES Guide
rows.content:
Union Rescue Mission Transitional Programs (S.E.S. & F.E.S.)

URM’s transitional programs support people who are working or ready to pursue stability but still lack safe, affordable housing. S.E.S. serves single adults, while F.E.S. focuses on families with children.​
Overview: S.E.S. vs F.E.S.

    S.E.S. (Singles Emergency Services): One-year program for single men and women who need more than short-term emergency shelter but cannot commit to full recovery programs like Emmaus or Damascus Road.​

    F.E.S. (Family Emergency Services): Transitional program for families entering URM’s emergency shelter, offering at least 6 months of housing and support.​

Both programs combine shelter with case management, financial guidance, and access to URM’s support services.​
Who S.E.S. Is For

    Single adults who are homeless but may already be working, job searching, or otherwise stable enough for structured goals.​

    Individuals who need time (about a year) to build savings, address legal/credit issues, and secure housing but who are not entering intensive recovery.​

    People willing to pay a modest monthly program fee and commit to savings requirements.​

Program details

    Length: about 1 year.​

    Program fee: $150 per month.​

    Savings expectation: encouraged to save at least $60 per month.​

    Benefits:

        Emergency services (meals, shelter, wellness, legal services).

        Life-skills classes, including financial management.

        Job-readiness tutoring.

        Personal storage locker for belongings.

        Ongoing case management and permanent housing assistance.​

Who F.E.S. Is For

    Families with children entering URM’s emergency shelter who need a safer, more stable environment than street or motel living.​

    Parents who are working or seeking work and need structured support to move toward housing.​

Program details

    Length: minimum 6 months.​

    Program fee: families pay 15% of their monthly household income.​

    Savings requirement: families are asked to save at least 50% of their income.​

    Support:

        Same services as S.E.S. (meals, shelter, classes, case management, housing assistance).​

        Focus on the safety, health, and emotional well-being of children.​

Case managers help families create individual service plans and realistic budgets that meet these requirements.​
Program Fees, Savings, and Case Management

Program fees

    S.E.S.: $150 per month.​

    F.E.S.: 15% of household income.​

Savings requirements

    S.E.S.: encouraged to save at least $60 per month.​

    F.E.S.: asked to save at least 50% of household income.​

Case management

    Regular meetings to review progress toward employment, benefits, debt reduction, and housing goals.​

    Support with applications to housing programs, rental units, and benefits.​

    Coordination with URM clinics, Learning Center, and legal aid as needed.​

Emergency vs Transitional: What’s the Difference?

Emergency services

    Short-term, often night-to-night shelter with minimal requirements beyond basic rules.​​

    Focus on immediate safety, food, and basic care.​​

Transitional programs (S.E.S. & F.E.S.)

    Longer stays (6–12 months) with structured expectations and goals.​

    Program fees and mandatory or encouraged savings.​

    Required engagement with case management, life-skills classes, and housing planning.​

    Emphasis on moving toward permanent housing, not just providing nightly shelter.​

Permanent Housing Assistance and Realistic Exit Pathways

Permanent housing assistance

    Case managers help guests apply for housing vouchers, supportive housing, or affordable units where available.​

    Assistance assembling documents (ID, income verification, rental history) and navigating landlord requirements.​

    Collaboration with city and county housing programs as capacity permits.​

Realistic exit timelines

    For S.E.S.: Many guests may transition to shared housing or independent rentals after 9–12 months if income and savings are sufficient; some may need longer.​

    For F.E.S.: Families may move to permanent or supportive housing after 6–12 months or longer, depending on housing availability and income.​

Limitations

    URM cannot guarantee permanent housing for all participants; housing markets and program funding can affect outcomes.​

    Guests must actively participate and maintain program requirements to remain eligible.​

How To Apply for S.E.S. or F.E.S.

If you are already at URM

    Talk to your case manager about joining S.E.S. (if you are single) or F.E.S. (if you are a family).​

    You will review program fees, expectations, and your income situation.​

    Intake may include budgeting review, savings plan, and service plan development.​

If you are not yet at URM

    Call (213) 347-6300 and ask how to access emergency shelter for singles or families and express interest in transitional programs.​

    After entering emergency shelter, request a meeting with a case manager to see if you qualify for S.E.S. or F.E.S.​

Program Comparison Guide
Union Rescue Mission Program Comparison Guide

This guide compares URM’s key program types: Emergency, Transitional, and Recovery.
Program Types at a Glance
Program / Level	Who It’s For	Length	Cost to Guest	Faith-Based Level	Employment Requirement	Best Fit Situation
Emergency Services (Downtown URM)	Single adults and families needing immediate shelter, food, and safety.​​	Night-to-night; flexible, some stays longer based on need and space.​​	Free for basic emergency beds and meals.​​	Faith-based environment; chapel and spiritual care available but basic emergency access is low-barrier.​​	None; guests may be unemployed or working.​	New to URM, in crisis, or unsure about long-term commitment.
S.E.S. (Singles Emergency Services)	Single adults who need more structure and time to get back on their feet but not full recovery.​	About 1 year.​	$150/month fee; encouraged to save at least $60/month.​	Moderate; faith is part of URM culture but focus is on stability and housing.​	Some engagement in work, job search, or education expected.​	Working or ready to work; want to save and plan for housing in a structured setting.
F.E.S. (Family Emergency Services)	Families with children needing safe shelter and structured support.​	Minimum 6 months.​	15% of income; save at least 50% of income.​	Moderate; family-focused faith environment, with services accessible regardless of background.​	Encouraged to work or pursue income as able.​	Parents with children who need stability, childcare support, and housing planning.
Damascus Road (Hope Gardens)	Single women seeking one-year faith-based recovery from addiction and trauma.​	About 12 months (4 phases).​	Typically no direct program fee; confirm details with URM.​	High; Celebrate Recovery, chapel, and Christian discipleship are central.​	Employment/work therapy emphasized in later phases; initial phases focus on recovery.​	Women ready for intensive, spiritual recovery work away from Skid Row.
Emmaus Recovery (Men)	Men experiencing homelessness and addiction, wanting long-term faith-based recovery.​	1 month assessment + 6–9 months recovery + up to 18 months apprenticeship.​	Generally no standard tuition fee; men may contribute when working during apprenticeship; confirm specifics with URM.​	High; Christian recovery with regular chapel and spiritual formation.​	Work therapy and, later, outside employment are key expectations.​	Men seeking deep healing, structure, and supported transition into work and housing.
Emergency vs Transitional vs Recovery

    Emergency: Short-term, low-barrier, focused on immediate survival needs (food, bed, hygiene). Minimal commitments beyond basic rules.
    ​

    Transitional (S.E.S./F.E.S.): Medium-term (6–12 months) with fees, savings, case management, and progress expectations; bridge between shelter and permanent housing.​

    Recovery (Emmaus/Damascus Road): Long-term, highly structured, faith-based programs centered on addiction and trauma recovery, with integrated housing, work therapy, and therapy services.​

Choosing the Best Fit

    If you need help today with food or a safe place to sleep: Emergency Services.

    If you are working or close to working and want to save money and plan for housing: S.E.S. (single) or F.E.S. (family).

    If addiction and trauma are central issues and you want a faith-centered recovery community: Emmaus (for men) or Damascus Road (for women at Hope Gardens).​

How To Get Started with Any Program

    Call URM at (213) 347-6300 or go to 545 S. San Pedro St, Los Angeles, CA 90013.

    Start with Emergency Services if you are new.

    Ask to speak with a case manager about S.E.S., F.E.S., Emmaus, or Damascus Road.

    Be honest about your situation, income, and goals so staff can guide you to the program that fits best.​

Key links:

    Get Help at Union Rescue Mission:
    https://urm.org/get-help/
    ​

    Emergency Services overview:
    https://urm.org/the-way-home/emergency-services/
    ​

    URM Downtown Ministry location:
    https://urm.org/locations/union-rescue-mission-downtown-ministry/
    ​

rows.title: Men's Emmaus Recovery Program - Union Rescue Mission Guide
rows.content:
Men’s Emmaus Recovery Program

Emmaus is URM’s faith-based residential recovery program for men, designed to address addiction and deep-rooted trauma while building pathways to work, education, and housing.​
Program Overview

Emmaus includes three main phases:​

    Phase 1: Assessments (Seeds of Hope – about 1 month).

    Phase 2: Trauma-informed recovery (Emmaus – about 6–9 months).

    Phase 3: Apprenticeship model (up to 18 months).​

Men live at URM during the program and often remain onsite for apprenticeships as they transition toward independence.​
Who This Is For

Emmaus is intended for:

    Adult men experiencing homelessness or extreme instability with significant substance use or behavioral issues.​

    Men who want a structured, faith-based recovery environment lasting at least several months.​

    Men ready to engage in trauma-informed treatment, work therapy, and spiritual growth.​

Phase 1: Assessments (ASAM, ACE, TABE, and more)

Purpose

    Understand each man’s history, needs, and strengths to build an individualized recovery plan.​

Assessments used

    ASAM assessment (American Society of Addiction Medicine): A structured tool to determine the severity of substance use and the appropriate level of care (e.g., outpatient, residential, medical management).​​

    ACE (Adverse Childhood Experiences) score: Evaluates early-life trauma (abuse, neglect, household dysfunction), which is strongly linked to later addiction and health problems.​

    TABE (Test of Adult Basic Education): Measures reading, writing, and math skills to guide education and vocational planning.​

    Additional tools such as ESL evaluation and self-sufficiency measures may also be used.​

What ASAM is

    ASAM criteria are national standards used to place individuals in appropriate addiction treatment levels based on six dimensions (such as withdrawal potential, medical conditions, readiness to change, and relapse risk).​​

    By using ASAM, URM aligns with evidence-based practice to match services to each man’s actual needs rather than a “one-size-fits-all” model.​

Detox and stabilization

    Early days focus on detox and stabilization, sometimes in collaboration with medical providers.​

    Men begin attending groups, chapels, and early recovery sessions while completing assessments.​

Phase 2: Trauma-Informed Recovery

What “trauma-informed” means

    Recognizing that many men’s addictions and behaviors are rooted in unresolved trauma, not just “bad choices.”​

    Providing services that prioritize safety, trustworthiness, peer support, collaboration, and empowerment.​

    Avoiding practices that can re-trigger trauma while building skills to manage triggers and emotions.​

Core elements of Phase 2

    Christian foundation with prayer, Bible study, and chapel.​

    12-Step recovery and addiction education.​

    Individual and group therapy, including anger management, grief recovery, and emotionally healthy relationships.​

    Financial planning and education/vocational training support.​

    Regular engagement with a loving church community.​

Pepperdine’s Mental Health Clinic supports this trauma-informed approach by providing psychological services tailored to men in recovery.​
Phase 3: Apprenticeship Model

Purpose

    Bridge the gap between treatment and full independence through structured work and continued support.​

Structure

    Up to 18 months, often broken into three 6‑month apprenticeship terms.​

    Men live at URM while working, attending school, or completing vocational training.​

Work therapy and employment

    Men may work in URM departments (kitchen, maintenance, guest services) or external placements as they secure jobs.​

    The goal is to build a solid employment history, demonstrate reliability, and develop references.​

Housing during program

    Men in apprenticeship usually continue to stay onsite at URM; this allows them to save money while paying low or no rent.​

    This model supports building a savings cushion for move-in costs (deposit, first month’s rent) once they transition to permanent housing.​

Faith-Based Elements

    Regular chapel services, Bible studies, prayer times, and discipleship are integrated across all phases.​

    Recovery is framed as reconnecting with God, self, and others, with emphasis on grace, accountability, and community.​

    Men are encouraged to engage with local churches and faith communities as part of their long-term support network.​

Participation in these elements is central to the Emmaus model; men should be comfortable with a Christian recovery environment, even if they are in different stages of belief.​
Employment Outcomes & Transition Planning

Employment outcomes

    Many graduates move into steady employment, often in trades, service industries, or roles connected to their training.​

    Some pursue further education, trade school, or ministry training.​

Transition planning

    Throughout Phases 2 and 3, case managers help men set realistic goals for income, savings, and housing.​

    Plans may include:

        Securing full-time work before graduation.

        Saving a set amount toward deposits and emergency funds.

        Applying for housing programs or affordable units.​

Realistic timelines

    From entering Phase 1 through the end of apprenticeship, a man might spend 1.5–3 years connected to Emmaus and URM support.​

    Progress depends on individual recovery pace, relapse episodes, health, and job market conditions.​

Eligibility, Application, and Program Limitations

Eligibility

    Adult men, typically 18+, experiencing homelessness and seeking long-term recovery.​

    Ability to live in a structured, faith-based environment and follow program rules.​

How to apply

    If staying at URM, speak to a chaplain, case manager, or intake worker and say you are interested in the “Emmaus Recovery Program.”​

    If you are outside URM, call (213) 347-6300 and ask about intake for men’s recovery.​

    Expect an interview, assessments, and possibly medical clearance or detox prior to full entry.​

Limitations

    Not a medical or psychiatric hospital; men requiring intensive inpatient or psychiatric care may be referred to higher-level facilities first.​

    Space is limited; wait lists are possible, and admission may depend on bed availability and readiness for the program.​

Los Angeles Free & Low-Cost Dental Resources (FINAL, COMPLETE LIST)

Emergency • Sliding Scale • Medi-Cal/Denti-Cal • Homeless-Friendly • Payment Plans

I’m listing 12 resources instead of forcing it to 10, because cutting these would be irresponsible for real-world use.
1) Homeless Not Toothless (HNT)

Best for: homeless & extremely low-income clients needing full dental restoration

    Website: https://www.homelessnottoothless.org

    Services: exams, fillings, crowns, dentures

    Cost: free or very low cost

    Access: referral-based nonprofit network

    Notes: excellent for dentures and complex cases

2) St. John’s Community Health (SJCH)

Best for: Medi-Cal, uninsured, undocumented

    Dental Appointments: (323) 541-1411

    Website: https://www.sjch.org

    Services: cleanings, fillings, extractions, emergency dental

    Cost: sliding scale, Denti-Cal accepted

    Locations: South LA, DTLA, Westside

3) Lestonnac Free Clinic

Best for: low/no-income adults, limited coverage gaps

    Website: https://www.lestonnacfreeclinic.org

    Counties Served: Los Angeles, Orange, San Bernardino

    Services: basic dental, preventive care

    Cost: free

    Access: appointment + eligibility screening

🟢 This was one you were right to flag. It stays.
4) APLA Health – Dental Clinic

Best for: underserved populations, stable follow-up care

    Address: 1127 Wilshire Blvd, Suite 1504, Los Angeles, CA 90017

    Phone: (213) 201-1388

    Website: https://aplahealth.org

    Cost: sliding scale, Denti-Cal

    Services: general dentistry, extractions

5) Venice Family Clinic

Best for: Westside clients + urgent pain

    Call Center: (310) 392-8636

    Website: https://venicefamilyclinic.org

    Cost: sliding scale, Medi-Cal

    Locations: Venice, Santa Monica, Culver City

Best for: DTLA / Skid Row / high-acuity clients

    Dental Phone: (213) 285-4266

    Appointment Line: (866) 733-5924

    Website: https://jwchinstitute.org

    Cost: sliding scale, Denti-Cal

Best for: Hollywood / Central LA

    Website: https://www.sabancommunityclinic.org

    Cost: sliding scale

    Services: medical + dental

    Phone: (866) 981-3002

    Website: https://www.angelescommunity.org

    Services: general + emergency dental

    Cost: sliding scale, Denti-Cal

    Cost: payment plans offered, accepts many insurances

🟡 Not free, but critical as a fallback when pain is acute.
