Best for: complex work at reduced cost

    Address: 714 Tiverton Dr, Los Angeles, CA 90095

    Phone: (310) 206-3904

    Website: https://dentistry.ucla.edu

    Cost: reduced student/resident fees

    Note: slower intake, excellent quality

11) USC Ostrow School of Dentistry – Urgent Care

Best for: trauma, infection, severe pain

    Address: 925 W 34th St, Los Angeles, CA 90089

    Urgent Line: (213) 740-1576

    Website: https://dentistry.usc.edu

    Emergency fees: ~$59–$350

    Denti-Cal: limited emergency acceptance

12) Emergency Dental Relief Los Angeles

Best for: same-day emergencies + payment plans

    Address: 10458 Vermont Ave, Los Angeles, CA 90044

    Phone: (213) 212-5046

    Website: https://emergencydentist.la

    Hours: extended / near-24-hour

    Payment plans: explicitly offered

Parenting Classes in Los Angeles
LA County Department of Public Health — Maternal, Child and Adolescent Health Programs
Offers free parenting education workshops and support groups.
Topics include prenatal care, child development, and positive parenting.
Website: publichealth.lacounty.gov
Phone: (213) 240-7941
Homeboy Industries
Provides parenting classes and family support services, especially for formerly incarcerated individuals and their families.
Website: homeboyindustries.org
Phone: (323) 526-1254
Parenting for LA’s Future (P-LAF)
Offers free parenting workshops focused on empowering families in underserved communities.
Website: parentingforlafuture.org
Phone: (213) 617-2002
Local Family Resource Centers
Many neighborhoods have centers offering free or low-cost parenting classes and resources.
Example: Central City Neighborhood Partners (ccnpinc.org)
Couples Counseling in Los Angeles
Los Angeles County Department of Mental Health (LACDMH)
Offers low-cost or no-cost couples counseling at various community mental health clinics.
Services are income-based and often covered by Medi-Cal.
Website: dmh.lacounty.gov
Access Line: (800) 854-7771

Provides affordable couples therapy with sliding scale fees in LA.
Website: cnvsocal.org
Phone: (626) 314-9930

Offers counseling and support groups for couples at low or no cost.
Website: lalgbtcenter.org
Phone: (323) 993-7400
University Training Clinics
UCLA Therapy Training Program and Pepperdine University offer low-cost couples counseling through their graduate training clinics.
UCLA: (310) 825-2536
Pepperdine: (310) 568-5600

Great, focusing on Los Angeles. I will begin an in-depth search for verified free transit ride
programs and housing voucher solutions, gathering specific application steps, eligibility criteria,
and contact info. I'll report back with concrete findings and instructions for accessing these
programs.
Here are concrete Los‑Angeles‑specific programs that can help your clients obtain free transit
rides and housing vouchers/assistance. I only included programs with verifiable sign‑up
information, eligibility requirements and phone numbers so you know exactly who to contact and
how to apply.
1 – Free bus and subway rides
Program/Agen
cy
Eligibility & benefits (what’s
offered)
How to sign up / contact
Metro LIFE
Program
(Low‑Income
Fare is Easy)
LA County residents age 18+
who are head‑of‑household
and can self‑certify that their
household income is below
the limits ($48,550 for one
person, $55,450 for two, etc.)
qualify for up to 20 free rides
every month or a discounted
monthly pass on Metro and
other participating transit
agencies. New participants
receive a free 90‑day pass;
unused rides roll over for up to
eight months. People who
already get fare discounts
through a school/university
U‑Pass, employer program or
Access Services are not
eligible.
1. Create a TAP card account at
taptogo.net and choose “LIFE” under
Programs. 2. Self‑certify your household
size and income and upload photo ID for
each household member. 3. Once
approved, log into your TAP account each
month and select “Add LIFE 20‑Ride” to
load your free rides (or visit a Metro
customer center or TAP vendor). If you
have trouble adding rides, call TAP
Customer Service at 866‑827‑8646. For
LIFE program questions, email
lifeinfo@metro.net or call the LIFE team
at 213‑922‑2378. Applications can also be
submitted by mail or in person at Metro
customer centers and Big Blue Bus transit
store drop‑offs.
LADOT
Cityride
For LA residents age 65+ or
qualified persons with
disabilities. Once approved,
participants receive a Cityride
card loaded with $84 of fare
value per quarter, which
costs $21 ($9 for low‑income
participants); the card can be
used for discounted taxi rides,
dial‑a‑ride trips and free
DASH bus rides.
Download the application from LADOT
Cityride and return it by mail with proof of
age or disability. Once approved, the
Cityride card and instructions on
reordering value are sent to the
participant. For help or to request a paper
application, call the Cityride hotline at
213/310/323/818‑808‑7433; TDD users
call 800‑559‑1950.
GoPass (LA
Metro)
K‑12 and community college
students attending
participating schools can ride
Metro buses and trains for
free, along with many
municipal bus systems. A
special GoPass TAP card
provides unlimited rides
throughout the school year.
Schools distribute unique GoPass
eligibility codes. Students (or a
parent/guardian) go to
taptogo.net/gopass, enter the code and
complete the registration form. The school
can answer questions or call Metro’s
Customer Relations (213‑922‑6235) for
assistance.
Access
Services
Free‑Fare
Program
People who qualify for ADA
paratransit (Access Services)
can ride most bus and rail
lines in Los Angeles County
for free by showing their
Access ID card. Eligibility is
based on a person’s ability to
use accessible buses and
trains rather than age or a
specific disability; applicants
undergo an in‑person transit
evaluation.
Request an application and evaluation
appointment by calling Access Customer
Service at 800‑827‑0829 (TDD
800‑827‑1359). After receiving an Access
ID card, simply show it when boarding
participating bus/rail services—no
additional registration is needed.
DPSS
GROW/START
Transportation
Assistance
Participants in the General
Relief Opportunities for
Work (GROW)/START
program can receive bus
passes or gas vouchers to
attend orientation, training and
job search appointments.
Clients must first apply for General Relief
through DPSS (apply online or call
866‑613‑3777). After enrolling, a GROW
case manager will assess needs during
orientation and issue transportation
assistance (bus passes or gas vouchers)
as part of supportive services. Speak with
your GROW case manager for details.
2 – Housing vouchers and concrete housing solutions

(LACDA)

County’s Coordinated Entry

experiencing homelessness to

to check waiting‑list status, call

When the list opens,
applications are submitted
online with proof of identity
and income.
Emergency Housing
Vouchers (EHVs)
HUD‑funded vouchers for
people who are homeless, at
risk of homelessness, fleeing
domestic violence or recently
homeless. EHVs cover rent
similarly to Section 8 but are
time‑limited. Access is only
through referrals from LA’s
Coordinated Entry System,
not directly from applicants.
To be screened for an EHV,
clients must be connected to a
homeless services provider.
Direct them to call 2‑1‑1 or
LAHSA’s hotline
(800‑548‑6047). Service
providers determine eligibility
and refer clients to the housing
authority for an EHV.

Assistance Programs
(DPSS) – for families
receiving CalWORKs

or at‑risk families with children:

Assistance pays for

daily rates are around $85 for

rent ≤80 % of household

Assistance to Prevent
Eviction (EAPE) can pay
past‑due rent or utilities (up
to two months’ arrears or
$5,000 across multiple
payments). Four‑Month

# The Source: Monthly Resource Fair With Free Health & Homeless Shelter Services

**The Source** offers a one-stop-shop of resources and services to help homeless Angelenos transition to independent and supported living. Services are also available for eligible low-income residents. **All services are free of charge.**

## Services Offered
Services offered may vary by location and include:

- Free California ID vouchers for the DMV
- Birth certificate services
- Free cell phones
- Enrollment into Medi-Cal and CalFresh
- Housing assessment through the Coordinated Entry System
- Employment assistance
- Mental health services
- HIV education and resources
- Child support services
- Referrals to expert providers

## SECTION 4: LEGAL & RIGHTS PROTECTION

### California Civil Rights Department (CRD)
**Enforces Fair Housing Laws & Investigates Discrimination Complaints**

**Primary Contact:**
- **Phone**: 1-800-884-1684 (assistance with complaint filing)
- **TTY**: 1-800-700-2320 or California Relay Service 711
- **Website**: https://calcivilrights.ca.gov
- **Online Complaint System**: https://calcivilrights.ca.gov/complaintprocess (California Civil Rights System - CCRS)

**File a Complaint:**
- **Online**: Create account at CCRS portal (fastest method)
- **Phone**: Call 1-800-884-1684 for assistance
- **Mail/Download Forms**: Available at website

**What They Enforce:**
- Fair Employment and Housing Act (FEHA)
- Unruh Civil Rights Act
- Ralph Civil Rights Act
- Disabled Persons Act

**Protected Characteristics in Housing:**
- Race, color, national origin, ancestry
- Religion (including religious dress/grooming)
- Sex, gender, gender identity, gender expression
- Sexual orientation
- Marital status
- Disability (mental and physical)
- Source of income (including Section 8 vouchers - California law)
- Age
- Familial status (families with children)
- Genetic information
- Military/veteran status
- Citizenship status

**What Constitutes Housing Discrimination:**
- Refusing to rent or sell
- Different terms/conditions/privileges
- Discriminatory advertising
- Refusing reasonable accommodation for disabilities
- Refusing reasonable modification for disabilities
- Source of income discrimination (e.g., "No Section 8")
- Harassment based on protected characteristic
- Retaliation for asserting fair housing rights

**Timeline:**
- **Deadline to File**: Within 1 year of discriminatory act
- **Investigation Timeline**: CRD has up to 1 year to investigate and potentially file lawsuit

**Process:**
1. Submit Pre-Complaint Inquiry/Intake Form
2. CRD evaluates if complaint falls under their jurisdiction
3. If accepted, CRD prepares formal complaint for your signature
4. Complaint sent to alleged violator
5. Investigation (may include mediation/conciliation)
6. Determination of reasonable cause
7. Potential lawsuit or Right-to-Sue notice

**Offices:**
- Headquarters: Sacramento
- Regional offices in Los Angeles, Oakland, Fresno, and Elk Grove

**Important:**
- CRD (formerly DFEH - Department of Fair Employment and Housing)
- Largest state civil rights agency in the United States
- Provides broader protections than federal law (HUD)

**Alternative: File with HUD**
- **HUD Fair Housing Complaint Line**: 1-800-669-9777
- **Online HUD Complaint**: https://www.hud.gov/program_offices/fair_housing_equal_opp/online-complaint
- **TTY**: 1-800-877-8339

**New Protections Starting 2026:**

## IMPORTANT REMINDERS

**Know Your Rights:**
- You cannot be evicted without a court order
- Source of income discrimination is illegal in California
- You have 5 business days (now 10 court days as of 2025) to respond to eviction lawsuit
- Landlords cannot retaliate for asserting your rights

**Documentation:**
- Keep copies of all notices, leases, and communication
- Document discrimination with dates, names, and details
- Save text messages and emails
- Take photos of housing conditions if relevant

**Don't Wait:**
- Apply for assistance as soon as you know you'll have trouble paying rent
- Contact legal services immediately upon receiving eviction notice
- File discrimination complaints within 1 year

**Language Access:**
- Most services available in multiple languages
- 2-1-1 provides multilingual support
- Request interpreters when accessing services

Los Angeles County
Development Authority
(LACDA)

older adults and people with
disabilities pay for rental

County’s Coordinated Entry
System (CES) for homeless

Encourage clients

Housing Choice
Voucher – Housing
Authority of the City of
Los Angeles (HACLA)
HACLA administers Section 8
vouchers for the City of L.A.

inquiries at (213) 252‑2500.
When the list opens,
applications are submitted
online with proof of identity

Emergency Housing
Vouchers (EHVs)
HUD‑funded vouchers for
people who are homeless, at
risk of homelessness, fleeing
domestic violence or recently
homeless. EHVs cover rent
similarly to Section 8 but are
time‑limited. Access is only
through referrals from LA’s
Coordinated Entry System,
not directly from applicants.
To be screened for an EHV,
clients must be connected to a
homeless services provider.
Direct them to call 2‑1‑1 or
LAHSA’s hotline
(800‑548‑6047). Service
providers determine eligibility
and refer clients to the housing
authority for an EHV.
CalWORKs Homeless
Assistance Programs
(DPSS) – for families
receiving CalWORKs
These programs help homeless
or at‑risk families with children:
Temporary Homeless
Assistance pays for
motel/shelter for up to 16 days
(domestic‑violence survivors
may receive two payments);
daily rates are around $85 for
a family of four plus $15 per
additional person.
Permanent Homeless
Assistance covers security
deposit, last month’s rent and
utility fees for housing where
rent ≤80 % of household
income. Moving Assistance
provides up to $2,500 for
moving costs and $405 for
appliances.
Arrearage/Emergency
Assistance to Prevent
Eviction (EAPE) can pay
past‑due rent or utilities (up
to two months’ arrears or
$5,000 across multiple
payments). Four‑Month
Rental Assistance pays up to
$500/month for 4 months (or
8 months if in Family
Stabilization) after a family
secures permanent housing.
Families must already receive
CalWORKs. To apply, visit
your local DPSS office or call
(866) 613‑3777 and request
homeless assistance. Bring
identification, proof of
homelessness (e.g., eviction
notice, letter from shelter) and
proof of income. A CalWORKs
eligibility worker or Homeless
Case Management staff will
assess which program(s)
apply and process payments.
Housing for Health – LA
County Department of
Health Services
Provides Permanent
Supportive Housing paired
with intensive
case‑management services for
individuals experiencing
chronic homelessness and
facing complex
health/behavioral‑health
conditions; services include
in‑home caregiving,
mental‑health and
substance‑use treatment. Also
manages the Flexible
Housing Subsidy Pool to fund
rent subsidies and secure
units.
Clients must be referred
through LA County’s homeless
services system. Case
managers can call Housing
for Health at (323) 274‑3600
for program information.
Individuals experiencing
homelessness should call
LAHSA’s hotline
(800‑548‑6047) to get
connected to outreach and
assessment.
HOPWA (Housing
Opportunities for
Persons with AIDS) –
Los Angeles Housing
Department
Provides housing subsidies
and supportive services (e.g.,
Short‑Term
Rent/Mortgage/Utility
assistance, move‑in grants,
Tenant‑Based and
Project‑Based rental assistance
and scattered‑site master
leasing) for low‑income
persons living with HIV/AIDS.
Eligibility requires an HIV/AIDS
diagnosis and household
income ≤80 % of Area Median
Income; priority is given to
those who are homeless, at
risk of homelessness or
unstably housed.
Contact the HOPWA program
at lahd.hopwa@lacity.org or
use the CHIRP LA
(Comprehensive Housing
Information & Referral for
People Living with HIV/AIDS)
resource website. CHIRP LA
provides a searchable
database of available housing
and can connect clients to
service providers; call
1‑877‑7‑CHIRPLA for
assistance. Applicants should
be prepared to provide proof of
HIV status and income.
LA County Housing
Resource Center
(Housing.LACounty.gov)
An online database of
affordable, special‑needs and
emergency housing listings
across L.A. County. Provides
phone assistance for those
without internet access.
Case managers can search for
units at housing.lacounty.gov
or call the toll‑free hotline
(877‑428‑8844) for help
locating available housing.
Project Roomkey
(LAHSA & LA County)
Provides temporary hotel or
motel rooms for people
experiencing homelessness
who are high‑risk for severe
illness (e.g., over 65 or with
certain medical conditions).
Clients should call LAHSA’s
hotline (800‑548‑6047) or
2‑1‑1 for screening and
placement. Availability is
limited and determined by risk
factors.
Stay Housed LA (LA
County Dept. of
Consumer and Business
Affairs)
Offers free legal services,
mediation and
rental‑assistance referrals for
tenants facing eviction or
harassment.
Tenants can call (833)
223‑7368 for legal help or visit
stayhousedla.org. Case
managers can assist clients
with documentation and
connect them to the program.
LA County Development
Authority (LACDA) –
general housing
resources
In addition to Section 8,
LACDA oversees
affordable‑housing
developments, landlord
incentive programs and
home‑improvement loans.
For general inquiries or to
learn about available
programs, call (626) 262‑4511.
LACDA staff can direct you to
current opportunities (e.g.,
affordable units,
home‑improvement loans).
LA County Housing
Resource Center –
Housing Information
Another online resource run by
LAHD to list affordable rentals.
Search at housing.lacity.org
or call (866) 557‑7368. The
site includes a “Ask Housing”
feature and can connect
callers to LAHD staff for
assistance.
Tips for navigating these resources
● Dial 211 or 800‑548‑6047 for urgent shelter and housing – LAHSA’s call centers
screen families, adults and youth for emergency and longer‑term housing and can issue
referrals for vouchers or programs.
● Have documentation ready – Most programs require ID, Social Security cards, proof of
income, and (for homeless‑preference vouchers) proof of homelessness (e.g., eviction
notice, letter from shelter).
● Stay in contact – For voucher waitlists, applicants must update their contact
information; failure to respond to mailings can result in removal from the list.
● Case managers as advocates – Many programs (CalWORKs, Housing for Health,
HOPWA) require a referral from a service provider. As a case manager, you can initiate
those referrals and advocate for your clients when contacting agencies.
By leveraging these programs—LIFE, Cityride, GoPass, Access Services, Section 8,
CalWORKs assistance, HOPWA and LAHSA resources—you can help clients in Los Angeles

rows.title: MacArthur Park - 24hr Safe Area
rows.description: Well-lit area near restrooms, park security patrols regularly
rows.notes: Avoid dense bushes. Stay near the lake side. Security friendly to homeless.

rows.title: Grand Park - Safe Sleeping Spot
rows.description: Downtown park with security, open space, well-maintained
rows.notes: Security wakes you at 6am but doesn't harass. Good for overnight.

rows.title: Echo Park - Under Bridge Area
rows.description: Covered area under bridge, protected from rain
rows.notes: Gets crowded. Come early. Respectful community.

rows.title: Downtown Women's Center - Free Meals
rows.description: Hot meals served daily, women and children only
rows.notes: Breakfast 7-9am, Lunch 12-2pm. No ID required. Very kind staff.

rows.title: Midnight Mission - Dinner Line
rows.description: Free dinner served nightly on Skid Row
rows.notes: Line starts at 5pm, food runs out by 7pm. Get there early!

rows.title: Pershing Square - Water Fountain
rows.description: Public water fountain, works 24/7
rows.notes: Cold water, bottle fill-up friendly. Sometimes homeless advocates bring water here.

rows.title: LA Central Library - Water & Restrooms
rows.description: Public library with water fountains and clean restrooms
rows.notes: Open Mon-Sat 10am-5:30pm. Can also charge phones inside.

rows.title: Union Station - Public Restrooms
rows.description: 24hr accessible bathrooms, generally clean
rows.notes: Security is chill. Showers sometimes available through outreach programs.

rows.title: Grand Central Market - Restrooms
rows.description: Public market with restrooms during business hours
rows.notes: Open 8am-10pm. Clean. Security might ask you to buy something.

rows.title: LA Central Library - Free Charging Stations
rows.description: Multiple outlets throughout library, free WiFi
rows.notes: Outlets near reading tables. Can stay all day. WiFi password not needed.

rows.title: Starbucks - 7th & Flower (Outlet Friendly)
rows.description: Starbucks with lots of outlets, staff doesn't hassle
rows.notes: Buy a small coffee ($2), can stay for hours. Bathroom for customers.

rows.title: LA Central Library - Free WiFi
rows.description: Strong public WiFi, no password required
rows.notes: Access from outside too. Library card gets you faster WiFi inside.

rows.title: Pershing Square - Free Public WiFi
rows.description: Public park with free WiFi coverage
rows.notes: Works at night too. Signal strongest near the fountain.

rows.title: ⚠️ Aggressive Security - 5th & Spring
rows.description: Business improvement district security harasses homeless
rows.notes: They confiscate belongings and call cops. Avoid sleeping here.

rows.title: 🚨 SWEEP ALERT - Skid Row Cleanup Scheduled
rows.description: City announced cleanup for 6th & San Pedro on Thursday 6am
rows.notes: Move belongings by Wednesday night! They will throw away tents.

rows.name: LA Food Bank
rows.description: Free food distribution and emergency food assistance.

rows.name: Homeless Not Toothless (HNT)
rows.description: Best for homeless & extremely low-income clients needing full dental restoration. Services: exams, fillings, crowns, dentures. Excellent for dentures and complex cases.

rows.name: St. John's Community Health (SJCH)
rows.description: Best for Medi-Cal, uninsured, undocumented. Services: cleanings, fillings, extractions, emergency dental. Sliding scale, Denti-Cal accepted.

rows.name: Lestonnac Free Clinic
rows.description: Best for low/no-income adults, limited coverage gaps. Services: basic dental, preventive care. Completely free with eligibility screening.
rows.address: Los Angeles, Orange, San Bernardino Counties

rows.name: APLA Health – Dental Clinic
rows.description: Best for underserved populations, stable follow-up care. Services: general dentistry, extractions. Sliding scale, Denti-Cal accepted.
rows.address: 1127 Wilshire Blvd, Suite 1504, Los Angeles, CA 90017

rows.name: Venice Family Clinic
rows.description: Best for Westside clients + urgent pain. Sliding scale, Medi-Cal accepted. Locations: Venice, Santa Monica, Culver City.

rows.name: JWCH Institute
rows.description: Best for DTLA / Skid Row / high-acuity clients. Services: full dental services. Sliding scale, Denti-Cal accepted.
rows.address: 522 S San Pedro St, Los Angeles, CA 90013

rows.name: Saban Community Clinic
rows.description: Best for Hollywood / Central LA. Services: medical + dental. Sliding scale pricing.

rows.name: Angeles Community Health Center
rows.description: Best for Koreatown / Westlake / Central LA. Services: general + emergency dental. Sliding scale, Denti-Cal accepted.

rows.name: Western Dental
rows.description: Best for payment plans when clinics are full. Services: exams, extractions, root canals, dentures. Multiple locations across LA. Not free, but critical fallback for acute pain.

rows.name: UCLA School of Dentistry
rows.description: Best for complex work at reduced cost. Reduced student/resident fees. Slower intake, excellent quality.

rows.name: USC Ostrow School of Dentistry – Urgent Care
rows.description: Best for trauma, infection, severe pain. Emergency fees: ~$59–$350. Limited emergency Denti-Cal acceptance.

rows.name: Emergency Dental Relief Los Angeles
rows.description: Best for same-day emergencies + payment plans. Extended / near-24-hour hours. Payment plans explicitly offered.

rows.name: LA County Department of Public Health - Parenting Programs
rows.description: Free parenting education workshops and support groups. Topics include prenatal care, child development, and positive parenting.

rows.name: Homeboy Industries - Parenting & Family Support
rows.description: Provides parenting classes and family support services, especially for formerly incarcerated individuals and their families.

rows.name: Parenting for LA's Future (P-LAF)
rows.description: Free parenting workshops focused on empowering families in underserved communities.

rows.name: Central City Neighborhood Partners
rows.description: Local family resource center offering free or low-cost parenting classes and resources.

rows.name: LA County Department of Mental Health - Couples Counseling
rows.description: Low-cost or no-cost couples counseling at various community mental health clinics. Services are income-based and often covered by Medi-Cal.

rows.name: The Center for Nonviolent Solutions
rows.description: Provides affordable couples therapy with sliding scale fees in LA.

rows.name: LA LGBT Center - Couples Counseling
rows.description: Offers counseling and support groups for LGBTQ+ couples at low or no cost.
rows.address: 1625 N Schrader Blvd, Los Angeles, CA 90028

rows.name: UCLA Therapy Training Program
rows.description: Low-cost couples counseling through UCLA's graduate training clinic.

rows.name: Pepperdine University Community Counseling Clinic
rows.description: Low-cost couples counseling through Pepperdine's graduate training clinic.

rows.name: Metro LIFE Program (Low-Income Fare is Easy)
rows.description: LA County low-income transit program providing up to 20 free rides monthly or discounted passes, including a free 90-day pass for new participants.

rows.name: LADOT Cityride
rows.description: Discounted transportation for Los Angeles seniors and eligible riders with disabilities, including DASH rides and subsidized taxi/dial-a-ride value.

rows.name: Metro GoPass Program
rows.description: Free unlimited rides for eligible K-12 and community college students at participating schools across Metro and partner systems.

rows.name: Access Services Free-Fare Program
rows.description: ADA paratransit riders can use an Access ID for free fares on participating Los Angeles County bus and rail services.

rows.name: DPSS GROW/START Transportation Assistance
rows.description: Transportation support for General Relief GROW/START participants, including bus passes or gas vouchers for required program activities.

rows.name: LACDA Section 8 Housing Choice Voucher
rows.description: Rental assistance for very-low-income households, seniors, and people with disabilities in LA County through voucher subsidies.

rows.name: HACLA Housing Choice Voucher Program
rows.description: Section 8, project-based vouchers, and emergency voucher pathways administered for residents in the City of Los Angeles.

rows.name: Emergency Housing Vouchers (EHV) via CES
rows.description: HUD-funded rental vouchers for people who are homeless, at risk, or fleeing domestic violence, accessed through Coordinated Entry referrals.

rows.name: CalWORKs Homeless Assistance Programs (DPSS)
rows.description: Housing stabilization support for CalWORKs families including temporary shelter help, move-in assistance, rent arrears support, and short-term rental aid.

rows.name: Housing for Health (LA County DHS)
rows.description: Permanent supportive housing and intensive services for chronically homeless people with complex medical or behavioral health needs.

rows.name: HOPWA (Housing Opportunities for Persons with AIDS)
rows.description: Housing subsidies and supportive services for low-income people living with HIV/AIDS, including short-term rent and utility support.

rows.name: LA County Housing Resource Center
rows.description: County housing search and referral platform for affordable, special-needs, and emergency housing listings in Los Angeles County.

rows.name: Project Roomkey (LAHSA and LA County)
rows.description: Temporary hotel/motel shelter placements for high-risk people experiencing homelessness, based on screening and availability.

rows.name: Stay Housed LA
rows.description: Free legal assistance, mediation, and eviction defense support for tenants facing displacement or harassment in LA County.

rows.name: LACDA General Housing Resources
rows.description: General housing support from LACDA, including affordable housing programs, landlord incentives, and related housing opportunities.

rows.name: LA Housing Department Housing Information
rows.description: City housing information portal with affordable rental listings and housing support navigation for Los Angeles residents.

rows.name: Metro LIFE Program (Low-Income Fare is Easy)
rows.description: LA County residents age 18+ who are head-of-household with household income below limits qualify for up to 20 free rides every month or discounted monthly pass on Metro. New participants receive a free 90-day pass; unused rides roll over for up to 8 months.

rows.name: LADOT Cityride
rows.description: For LA residents age 65+ or qualified persons with disabilities. Participants receive a Cityride card loaded with $84 of fare value per quarter for $21 ($9 for low-income). Can be used for discounted taxi rides, dial-a-ride trips and free DASH bus rides.

rows.name: GoPass - LA Metro K-12 & Community College
rows.description: K-12 and community college students attending participating schools can ride Metro buses and trains for free. A special GoPass TAP card provides unlimited rides throughout the school year.

rows.name: Access Services Free-Fare Program
rows.description: People who qualify for ADA paratransit can ride most bus and rail lines in LA County for free by showing their Access ID card. Eligibility based on ability to use accessible buses and trains; applicants undergo an in-person transit evaluation.

rows.name: DPSS GROW/START Transportation Assistance
rows.description: Participants in the General Relief Opportunities for Work (GROW)/START program can receive bus passes or gas vouchers to attend orientation, training and job search appointments.

rows.name: Section 8 Housing Choice Voucher - LACDA
rows.description: Helps very-low-income families, older adults and people with disabilities pay for rental housing. Participants pay 30-40% of income, voucher covers the rest. Waiting list currently closed; new vouchers issued through LA County Coordinated Entry System (CES) for homeless individuals.

rows.name: Housing Choice Voucher - HACLA (City of LA)
rows.description: HACLA administers Section 8 vouchers for City of L.A. General waiting list not always open. Also administers project-based vouchers and Emergency Housing Vouchers.

rows.name: Emergency Housing Vouchers (EHVs)
rows.description: HUD-funded vouchers for people who are homeless, at risk of homelessness, fleeing domestic violence or recently homeless. EHVs cover rent similarly to Section 8 but are time-limited. Access only through LA's Coordinated Entry System referrals.

rows.name: CalWORKs Homeless Assistance Programs - DPSS
rows.description: Programs for homeless CalWORKs families: Temporary Homeless Assistance (16 days motel/shelter), Permanent Homeless Assistance (security deposit, last month's rent), Moving Assistance ($2,500), Arrearage/EAPE (past-due rent up to $5,000), Four-Month Rental Assistance ($500/month for 4-8 months).

rows.name: Housing for Health - LA County DHS
rows.description: Provides Permanent Supportive Housing with intensive case-management for individuals experiencing chronic homelessness and facing complex health/behavioral-health conditions. Services include in-home caregiving, mental-health and substance-use treatment. Manages Flexible Housing Subsidy Pool.

rows.name: HOPWA (Housing Opportunities for Persons with AIDS)
rows.description: Housing subsidies and supportive services for low-income persons living with HIV/AIDS. Services include Short-Term Rent/Mortgage/Utility assistance, move-in grants, Tenant-Based and Project-Based rental assistance. Priority given to those homeless, at risk or unstably housed.

rows.name: LA County Housing Resource Center
rows.description: Online database of affordable, special-needs and emergency housing listings across LA County. Provides phone assistance for those without internet access.

rows.name: Project Roomkey - LAHSA & LA County
rows.description: Temporary hotel or motel rooms for people experiencing homelessness who are high-risk for severe illness (over 65 or with certain medical conditions). Availability limited and determined by risk factors.

rows.name: Stay Housed LA
rows.description: Free legal services, mediation and rental-assistance referrals for tenants facing eviction or harassment.

rows.name: LA County Development Authority (LACDA) - General Housing
rows.description: Oversees affordable-housing developments, landlord incentive programs and home-improvement loans in addition to Section 8.

rows.name: LA County Housing Resource Center - LAHD
rows.description: Online resource to list affordable rentals with 'Ask Housing' feature to connect with LAHD staff for assistance.

rows.name: 211 California - Statewide
rows.description: Free, confidential, 24/7 service connecting you to local rental assistance, emergency shelter, food, utilities, employment, health and human services. Available in multiple languages.

rows.name: 211 Sacramento
rows.description: 24/7 information and referral for homeless services, rental assistance, emergency shelter, and community resources in Sacramento County.

rows.name: 211 Los Angeles
rows.description: 24/7 helpline and referral service for housing, food, health services, and emergency assistance in LA County.

rows.name: HUD Resource Locator
rows.description: Find affordable housing properties, Public Housing Authorities, HUD-approved housing counselors, and FHA-approved lenders nationwide. Interactive map tool.

rows.name: Housing Authority of the City of Los Angeles (HACLA)
rows.description: Section 8 Housing Choice Vouchers, project-based vouchers, and Emergency Housing Vouchers for LA City residents.

rows.name: San Francisco Housing Authority
rows.description: Public housing and Section 8 vouchers for San Francisco residents.

rows.name: Sacramento Housing & Redevelopment Agency (SHRA)
rows.description: Affordable housing, Section 8 vouchers, and redevelopment services for Sacramento residents.

rows.name: San Diego Housing Commission
rows.description: Housing vouchers, affordable housing, and homeless services for San Diego residents.

rows.name: Oakland Housing Authority
rows.description: Public housing and rental assistance programs for Oakland residents.

rows.name: LifeSTEPS
rows.description: Direct rental assistance, eviction prevention, security deposits, housing navigation, and case management. 93% housing retention rate. Serves Sacramento County, veterans, and Cal AIM participants.

rows.name: Catholic Charities of Los Angeles
rows.description: Emergency rent assistance, utility bills, eviction prevention, and food pantry. One-time emergency aid for families in crisis.
rows.address: 1531 James M Wood Blvd, Los Angeles, CA 90015

rows.name: Catholic Charities of San Francisco
rows.description: Rental assistance, eviction prevention, housing counseling. FEPCO partner. Services in English, Spanish, Vietnamese.

rows.name: Catholic Charities of Sacramento

rows.name: Catholic Charities of San Diego
rows.description: Emergency financial assistance and housing support for San Diego residents.

rows.name: CalWORKs Housing Support Program (HSP)
rows.description: Housing assistance for CalWORKs families experiencing or at risk of homelessness. Rental assistance, security deposits, moving costs, hotel vouchers, case management, credit repair.

rows.name: CalWORKs Homeless Assistance (HA)

rows.phone: (866) 613-3777 (LA County) or contact county CalWORKs office

rows.name: Housing and Disability Advocacy Program (HDAP)

rows.name: California Civil Rights Department (CRD)
rows.description: Enforces fair housing laws, investigates discrimination complaints. File within 1 year. Protects against source of income discrimination (including Section 8).

rows.name: Stay Housed LA
rows.description: Free legal representation for LA County tenants facing eviction. Know Your Rights workshops, legal clinics, self-help resources. CRITICAL: 5 business days to respond to eviction lawsuit.

rows.name: Legal Aid Foundation of Los Angeles (LAFLA)
rows.description: Free civil legal services for low-income LA County residents. Housing, eviction defense, domestic violence, public benefits.

rows.name: LawHelpCA

rows.name: VA Housing Services - National Hotline
